alias-load-error: Unable to load WDT model metadata from installed version
ca-cert-revoc-list-dp-title: Certificate Authority CRL Distribution Point Settings
file-select-add-dir-to-archive: Add this directory to the archive file
file-select-add-file-to-archive: Add this file to the archive file
file-select-use-dir-location: Use this directory path on the target file system
file-select-use-file-location: Use this file path on the target file system
file-select-archive-empty-dir: Use a new empty directory in the archive file
file-select-local-empty-dir: Use a directory on the target file system
add-app-use-app-install-dir-help: The application installation directory separates generated configuration files from the core application files, so that configuration files can be easily changed or replaced without disturbing the application itself. The directory structure also helps you to organize and maintain multiple versions of the same application deployment files.
add-install-dir-use-archive-label: Add Installation Directory to the Archive File
add-install-dir-use-archive-help: Add the installation directory to the archive file, and set the associated paths in the model
add-install-dir-install-dir-help: The path to the application's install-root directory
add-install-dir-not-directory-error: Must be a local directory to add to archive
add-install-dir-not-file-error: Must be a local file to add to archive
add-install-dir-not-exists-error: Must exist on local file system to add to archive
add-install-dir-not-sub-path-error: Must be a relative path or a subpath of application installation directory
add-install-dir-required-with-plan-dir-e: Required if plan directory is specified
add-install-dir-not-relative-plan-path-e: Must be a relative path if plan directory is specified
options-custom-identity-and-java-standar: Custom Identity and Java Standard Trust
options-builtin-ssl-validation-and-cert-: Built-in SSL Validation and CertPath Providers
attribute-dialog-option-remove: Remove the field from the model
attribute-dialog-variable-name-error: Variable names may only contain letters, numbers, and these characters: .-_
invalid-double-error: Value must be a decimal number, such as 4 or 3.5
invalid-range-error: Value must be in the range {{min}} to {{max}}
instance-name-error: Name may only contain letters, numbers, and these characters: .-_!
instance-name-in-use-error: This name is already in use
f-ServerTemplate_ServerDebug-a-any-help: Enable {{attribute}} for servers created from this server template.
a-AbandonTimeoutSeconds-help: Specifies the maximum amount of time, in seconds, a transaction manager persists in attempting to complete the second phase of a two-phase commit transaction. During the second phase of a two-phase commit transaction, the transaction manager continues to try to complete the transaction until all resource managers indicate that the transaction is completed. After the abandon transaction timer expires, no further attempt is made to resolve the transaction. If the transaction is in a prepared state before being abandoned, the transaction manager rolls back the transaction to release any locks held on behalf of the abandoned transaction.
a-AcceptBacklog-help: The number of backlogged, new TCP connection requests that should be allowed for this server's regular and SSL ports. Setting the backlog to 0 may prevent this server from accepting any incoming connection on some operating systems. The default value is 300.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-AcceptBacklog: The number of backlogged, new TCP connection requests that this network channel allows. A value of -1 indicates that the network channel obtains its backlog configuration from the server's configuration.
a-AcceptContextPathInGetRealPath-label: Accept Context Path In Get Real Path
a-AcceptContextPathInGetRealPath-help: Indicates whether this server allows the inclusion of the context path in the virtual path to context.getRealPath(). The default value is false.
f-any_SSL-a-AcceptKssDemoCertsEnabled-he: Sets the default Hostname Verifier to accept KSS Demo SSL Certificates. The default value is true.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_WatchN: Configures the Accept header of the HTTP request to the REST endpoint.
f-WTCServer_WTCLocalTuxDom-a-AccessPoint: The unique name used to identify this local Tuxedo access point. This name should be unique for all local and remote Tuxedo access points defined within a WTC Service. This allows you to define unique configurations having the same Access Point ID.
f-WTCServer_WTCRemoteTuxDom-a-AccessPoin: The unique name used to identify this remote Tuxedo access point. This name should be unique for all local and remote Tuxedo access points defined within a WTC Service. This allows you to define unique configurations having the same Access Point ID.
f-WTCServer_WTCLocalTuxDom-a-AccessPoint: The connection principal name used to identify this local Tuxedo access point when attempting to establish a session connection with remote Tuxedo access points. Note that the AccessPointId must match the corresponding DOMAINID in the *DM_REMOTE_DOMAINS section of your Tuxedo DMCONFIG file.
f-WTCServer_WTCRemoteTuxDom-a-AccessPoin: The connection principal name used to identify this remote domain access point when attempting to establish a session connection to local Tuxedo access points. This value must be globally unique among all interconnected Tuxedo and WTC Domains.
a-AccessTokenContextPath-itemHelp: Specifies a context path to allow to use an IDCS access token.
a-AccessTokenContextPath-help: Specifies the list of context paths that will be allowed to use an IDCS access token. The default is to allow any context path to use an IDCS access token.
a-AccessTokenTimeoutWindow-help: Specifies the number of seconds before an access token times out that a new access token is requested. Adjusting the timeout window impacts how long access tokens are cached for reuse before an updated access token is requested from the authorization server.
f-SAFAgent-a-AcknowledgeInterval-help: The maximum interval between two successive acknowledgements sent by the receiving side. A value of -1 specifies that there is no time limit between successive acknowledgement.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Connecti: Acknowledge policy for non-transacted sessions that use the CLIENT_ACKNOWLEDGE mode. All indicates that calling acknowledge on a message acknowledges all unacknowledged messages received on the session. Previous specifies that calling acknowledge on a message acknowledges only unacknowledged messages up to, and including, the given message.
a-AcknowledgementInterval-help: The maximum time a pending acknowledgement (set after the destination accepts a message) can wait before being delivered back to the RM source. String value in "Duration" format. Defaults to "P0DT0.2S" (200 milliseconds). Set at sequence creation time, and cannot be reset.
f-WTCServer_WTCRemoteTuxDom-a-AclPolicy-: The inbound access control list (ACL) policy toward requests from a remote Tuxedo access point.  The allowed values are Local or Global. Local causes the local Tuxedo access point modifies the identity of service requests received from a given remote Tuxedo access point to the principal name specified in the local principal name for a given remote Tuxedo access point. Global causes tocal Tuxedo access point passes the service request with no change in identity. Note that if Interoperate is set to Yes, the AclPolicy is ignored.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_Instru: The diagnostic actions attached to this monitor. Actions are relevant only for delegating and custom monitors.
a-ActiveContextHandlerEntry-itemHelp: Specifies a ContextHandler entry that the Audit provider should process.
f-any_DefaultAuditor-a-ActiveContextHand: Specifies the ContextHandler entries that the Audit provider should process.
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource_Coheren: The active directory for the default persistence environment. If no value is specified, the directory which will be used is the coherence/active sub-directory under Domain Home directory.
f-Cluster-a-CoherenceClusterSystemResour: Specifies the Coherence Cluster associated with this cluster.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCOr: Indicates a configured Active GridLink datasource. This attributed is set to true when using the console to create an Active GridLink datasource. It is ignored if FanEnabled is true or OnsNodeList is a non-null string.
a-ActiveType-itemHelp: Specifies a token type to add to the active list.
f-any_DefaultIdentityAsserter-a-ActiveTy: Specifies the token types that are currently active. The default value includes "AuthenticatedUser" and "weblogic-jwt-token".
f-any_LDAPX509IdentityAsserter-a-ActiveT: Specifies the token types that are currently active. The default value includes "X.509".
f-any_weblogic.security.providers.authen: Specifies the token types that are currently active. The default value includes "idcs_user_assertion" and "Idcs_user_assertion".
f-any_TrustServiceIdentityAsserter-a-Act: Specifies the token types that are currently active.
f-JMSBridgeDestination-a-AdapterJNDIName: The JNDI name of the adapter used to communicate with the specified destination. This name is specified in the adapter's deployment descriptor file and is used by the WebLogic Server Connector container to bind the adapter in WebLogic Server JNDI. The default value is eis.jms.WLSConnectionFactoryJNDIXA
a-AddWorkManagerThreadsByCpuCount-label: Add Work Manager Threads By CPU Count
a-AddWorkManagerThreadsByCpuCount-help: Enables increased efficiency of the self-tuning thread pool by aligning it with the Exalogic processor architecture threading capabilities. The default value is controlled by the effective value of the DomainMBean's ExalogicOptimizationEnabled attribute.
f-Cluster-a-AdditionalAutoMigrationAttem: A migratable server could fail to come up on every possible configured machine. This attribute controls how many further attempts, after the first one, should be tried. Note that each attempt specified here indicates another full circuit of migrations amongst all the configured machines. So for a 3-server cluster, and the default value of 3, a total of 9 migrations will be attempted. If it is set to -1, migrations will go on forever until the server starts.
a-AdditionalMigrationAttempts-help: A migratable service could fail to come up on every possible configured server. This attribute controls how many further attempts, after the service has failed on every server at least once, should be tried. Note that each attempt specified here indicates another full circuit of migrations amongst all the configured servers. So for a 3-server cluster, and a value of 2, a total of 4 additional migrations will be attempted (the original server is never a valid destination).
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource_Coheren: The DNS Name or IP Address.
a-AdminPassword-help: The password for the WebLogic Server administrative user used to create a new domain.
a-AdminReconnectIntervalSeconds-help: The number of seconds between reconnection attempts to the admin server. When the admin server fails the managed server will periodically try to connect back to it. The default value is 10.
a-AdminServerName-help: Specifies the name of the server that will act as the administration server for this domain.  The default value is "AdminServer".
a-AdminUserName-help: The WebLogic Server administrative user name used to create a new domain. The default value is "weblogic".
f-Server-a-AdministrationPort-help: The secure administration port for the server. This port requires that you enable the domain's administration port and that SSL is configured and enabled. By default, the server uses the administration port that is specified at the domain level. To override the domain-level administration port for the current server instance, set this server's administration port.
f-ServerTemplate-a-AdministrationPort-he: The secure administration port for the servers created with this server template. This port requires that you enable the domain's administration port and that SSL is configured and enabled. By default, the server uses the administration port that is specified at the domain level. To override the domain-level administration port for the current server instance, set this server's administration port.
f-Topology-a-AdministrationPort-help: The common secure administration port for this WebLogic Server domain. Requires enabling the administration port either using AdministrationPortEnabled or putting the domain in secure production mode. The default value is 9002.
a-AdministrationPortEnabled-help: Specifies whether the domain-wide administration port should be enabled for this WebLogic Server domain. Because the administration port uses SSL, enabling the administration port requires that SSL must be configured for all servers in the domain. The default value is false except in secure production mode, where it defaults to true.
a-AdministrationProtocol-help: The default protocol for communicating through the administration port or administration channels. (Requires you to enable the administration port or to create an administration channel.) If requests through the administration port or an administration channel do not specify a protocol, WebLogic Server uses the protocol specified here. The default value is "t3s".
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCOr: The affinity policy determines how JDBC connections to specific Oracle RAC instances are selected and returned to the application. When an initial connection is returned to the application, an affinity context is created that identifies the RAC instance. The affinity context is stored in the application context (global transaction or http session), propagates with the context, and is used during subsequent connection requests to return a connection to the same instance. The affinity policy only applies to Active GridLink data sources.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_WatchN: For automatic alarms, the time period, in milliseconds, to wait after the policy evaluates to true before the alarm is automatically reset. The default reset period is 60000 milliseconds, which is equivalent to 60 seconds.

The alarm type for the policy: manual or automatic. The default alarm type is manual. Once a manually set alarm has triggered, it must be reset through the WebLogic Server Administration Console or programmatically before it can trigger again. An automatic reset alarm will reset after the specified time period has elapsed.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCDa: The algorithm determines the connection request processing for the multi data source.
a-AllGroupsFilter-help: An LDAP search filter for finding all groups beneath the base group distinguished name (DN). If the attribute is not specified (that is, if the attribute is null or empty), a default search filter is created based on the Group schema.
a-AllUsersFilter-help: An LDAP search filter for finding all users beneath the base user distinguished name (DN). If the attribute (user object class) is not specified (that is, if the attribute is null or empty), a default search filter is created based on the user schema.
f-WebAppContainer-a-AllowAllRoles-help: In the security-constraints elements defined in a web application's web.xml deployment descriptor, the auth-constraint element indicates the user roles that should be permitted access to this resource collection. Here role-name = "*" is a compact syntax for indicating all roles in the Web application. In previous releases, role-name = "*" was treated as all users/roles defined in the realm. This parameter is a backward-compatibility switch to restore old behavior. Default behavior is one required by the specification, meaning all roles defined in the web application. If set, the value defined in weblogic.xml (container-descriptor -> allow-all-roles) takes precedence (if set) over this value.
f-WTCServer_WTCRemoteTuxDom-a-AllowAnony: Specifies whether the anonymous user is allowed to access remote Tuxedo services. Note that if the anonymous user is allowed to access Tuxedo, the default AppKey will be used for TpUsrFile and LDAP AppKey plug-ins. Interaction with the Custom AppKey plug-in depends on the design of the Custom AppKey generator.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Connecti: Specifies whether a connection factory creates message consumers that allow a close() or stop() method to be issued within its onMessage() method call.
a-AllowListRecordingEnabled-help: Specifies whether the domain will run with recording enabled to record allowlists.
a-AllowListViolationAction-help: Defines the AllowListViolationAction of all servers in a domain.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-AllowListViol: Sets the value of AllowListViolationAction attribute used with JEP 290 filtering. The default value is obtained from the domain allow list configuration.
f-WTCServer_WTCtBridgeGlobal-a-AllowNonS: Specifies whether non-standard data types are allowed to pass through this Tuxedo queuing bridge. A value of NO means that non standard types are rejected and placed onto a specified error location; a value of YES means that non-standard types are placed on the target location as BLOBs with a tag indicating the original type. Standard types are ASCII text (TextMessage, STRING) or BLOB (BytesMessage, CARRAY).
a-AllowShrinkingPriorityRequestQueue-hel: Specifies whether self-tuning should allow shrinking of its priority based queue for pending requests after it has grown in size due to busy workload, and whether it should try to purge work requests that have already been picked up for processing due to minimum threads constraints before growing the queue. Setting this to true would help reduce memory footprint after the busy work period has ended, at the expense of the overhead of growing the request queue again at the next period of busy workload. It would also help to reduce the amount of memory allocated for the request queue, at the expense of the overhead required in purging already processed work requests from the queue. The default value is true.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-AllowUnencryp: The AllowUnEncryptedNullCipher flag is used to control whether the NullCipher feature is enabled or not. If true, the SSL message may be unencrypted when SSL server and client shares no common cipher. Warning: this NullCipher feature should NOT be enabled for a production environment, as it may lead to unencrypted SSL messages.
f-any_SSL-a-AllowUnencryptedNullCipher-h: The AllowUnEncryptedNullCipher flag is used to control whether the NullCipher feature is enabled or not, if true, the SSL message may be unencrypted when SSL server and client shares no common cipher. his AllowUnEncryptedNullCipher flag is only effective to SSL providers which support the NullCipher feature. Warning: this NullCipher feature should NOT be enabled for a production environment, it may leads to unencrypted SSL message.
a-AllowedTargetHost-itemHelp: Specify a host to add to the allowed target list.
f-any_SingleSignOnServices-a-AllowedTarg: List of hosts to compare against the host in the SAML SP target redirect URL. When the list is empty, the target redirect URL will not be checked.
f-JMSServer-a-AllowsPersistentDowngrade-: Specifies whether JMS clients will get an exception when sending persistent messages to a destination targeted to a JMS server that does not have a persistent store configured. This parameter only has effect when the Store Enabled parameter is disabled (false).
a-AltClientIdTokenClaim-help: Specifies the token attribute to use to get the alternate client ID from the token. The default value is "client_faId".
a-AltDescriptorDir-help: The location of this application's configuration area. This directory can contain alternate descriptor files. If the alternate descriptor directory is a relative path, it is resolved relative to InstallDir if InstallDir is not null; otherwise, it is resolved relative to the domain root.
a-AltDescriptorPath-help: A path on the file system for the application descriptor for this application. If null, the usual location within the EAR is used (META-INF/application.xml).
a-AltIdTokenClaim-help: Specifies the token attribute used to get the alternate user ID from the token. The default value is "client_faId".
a-AltWLSDescriptorPath-help: A path on the file system for the WebLogic Server-specific application descriptor for this application. If null, the usual location within the EAR file is used.
f-SecurityConfiguration-a-AnonymousAdmin: Set to true if anonymous JNDI access for Admin MBean home is permitted. Deprecated in 12.2.1.0.0.
f-EmbeddedLDAP-a-AnonymousBindAllowed-he: Specifies whether the embedded LDAP server should allow anonymous connections.
a-AnyIdentityDomainEnabled-help: Specifies whether the provider enables support of any identity domain mappers. The default value is false.
f-any_COM-a-ApartmentThreaded-help: Controls the flag that is used to initialize COM in native mode.
a-AppDir-help: The application home directory for a new FMW Infrastructure domain.
a-AppKey-help: Specifies the type of AppKey plug-in used.  The allowed values are TpUsrFile, LDAP, and Custom.  TpUsrFile is the default plug-in and uses an imported Tuxedo TPUSR file to provide user security information. The LDAP plug-in utilizes an embedded LDAP server to provide user security information; the user record must define the Tuxedo UID and GID information in the description field. The Custom plug-in provides the ability to write your own AppKey generator class to provide the security information required by Tuxedo.
a-AppNameFilterHeaderName-help: Specifies the name of the HTTP header used to determine the application name applied when filtering the authentication and assertion requests to the Oracle Identity Cloud Service. When no value is supplied or can be determined, requests are not filtered by an application.
f-WTCServer_WTCResources-a-AppPassword-h: The application password as returned from the genpasswd utility. This Tuxedo application password is the encrypted password used to authenticate connections.
f-WTCServer_WTCResources-a-AppPasswordIv: The initialization vector used to encrypt the AppPassword. Note that this value is returned from the genpasswd utility with the AppPassword.
a-AppRolesTokenClaim-help: Specifies the token attribute ssed to get AppRoles from the token.
f-JoltConnectionPool-a-ApplicationPasswo: The application password for this Jolt connection pool. (This is required only when the security level in the Tuxedo domain is USER_AUTH, ACL or MANDATORY_ACL).
f-SelfTuning_WorkManager-a-ApplicationSc: Specifies whether this work manager should be scoped to an application. By default, work managers are scoped to an application. Set this value to false if the work manager is to be scoped to a domain.
a-ArchiveConfigurationCount-help: The number of archival versions of config.xml saved by the Administration Server each time the domain configuration is modified. The default value is 0.
f-Callout-a-Argument-help: Specifies the argument to pass to the class.
a-Arguments-itemHelp: Specify an argument to add to the list.
f-SystemComponent_SystemComponentStart-a: The arguments to use when starting this server. These are the first arguments appended immediately after java portion of the startup command. For example, you can set Java heap memory or specify any weblogic.nodemanager.server.provider.WeblogicCacheServer option.
f-any_ServerStart-a-Arguments-help: The arguments to use when starting this server. These are the first arguments appended immediately after java portion of the startup command.
f-StartupClass-a-Arguments-help: Arguments that a server uses to initialize the Startup class. Separate multiple arguments with a comma.
f-ShutdownClass-a-Arguments-help: Arguments that a server uses to initialize the Shutdown class. Separate multiple arguments with a comma.
f-any_SingleSignOnServices-a-ArtifactMax: The maximum size of the artifact cache. This cache contains the artifacts issued by the local site that are awaiting referencing by a partner. Specify '0' to indicate that the cache is unbounded. The default value is 10000.
f-any_SingleSignOnServices-a-ArtifactTim: The maximum timeout (in seconds) of artifacts stored in the local cache. This cache stores artifacts issued by the local site that are awaiting referencing by a partner. Artifacts that reach this maximum timeout duration are expired in the local cache even if no reference request has been received from the partner. If a reference request is subsequently received from the partner, the cache behaves as if the artifact had never been generated. The default value is 300.
f-any_SingleSignOnServices-a-AssertionEn: The keystore alias for the certificate and private key to be used to encrypt and decrypt SAML Assertions. The certificate is published in the SP metadata, which will be used by an external SP to encrypt SAML assertions. The private key is used to decrypt assertions. If the alias is not specified, the server's configured SSL identity alias is used by default. If this value is not set, and the server's KeyStores setting is DomainKeystores, then the default Domain Keystores signing/encryption alias is returned.
The passphrase used to retrieve the local site's Assertion key from the keystore.
Specifies whether to encrypt assertions. The default value is false.
a-AssertionSubjectSessionTimeoutCheckEna: Assertion Subject Session Timeout Check Enabled
f-any_SingleSignOnServices-a-AssertionSu: Indicates whether to use the session timeout timestamp from the assertion's subject as a condition to time out the local session.
f-MessagingBridge-a-AsyncEnabled-help: Specifies if a messaging bridge instance forwards in asynchronous messaging mode. AsyncEnabled only applies to messaging bridge instances whose source destination supports asynchronous receiving. Messaging bridges instances that forward in asynchronous mode are driven by the source destination. A messaging bridge instance listens for messages and forwards them as they arrive. When AsyncEnabled is not selected, a bridge instance is forced to work in synchronous mode, even if the source supports asynchronous receiving. For a messaging bridge instance with a QOS of Exactly-once to work in asynchronous mode, the source destination has to support the MDBTransaction interface. Otherwise, the bridge automatically switches to synchronous mode if it detects that MDBTransaction is not supported by the source destination.
f-Cluster-a-AsyncSessionQueueTimeout-hel: Specifies the interval in seconds until the producer thread will wait for the AsyncSessionQueue to become unblocked. Should be similar to the RequestTimeOut as that will determine the longest that the queue should remain full.
a-AttachJMSXUserId-help: Specifies whether WebLogic Server attaches the authenticated user name to sent messages. If enabled, the system will attach the authenticated username onto sent messages if the destination supports this behavior. The username is placed in the JMSXUserID user property. You should consult the JMSXUserID documentation in Programming WebLogic JMS before using this feature.
a-AttachSender-help: Specifies whether messages landing on this destination should attach the credential of the sending user. You should consult the JMSXUserID documentation in the Programming WebLogic JMS documentation before using this feature.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Template: Specifies whether messages landing on destinations that use this template should attach the credential of the sending user.
f-any_SNMPAttributeChange-a-AttributeMBe: The name of the MBean instance that you want to monitor. If you leave the name undefined, WebLogic Server monitors all instances of the MBean type that you specify in Monitored MBean Type.
The MBean type that defines the attribute you want to monitor. Do not include the MBean suffix. For example, specify Server to monitor a ServerMBean.
f-any_SNMPAttributeChange-a-AttributeNam: The name of the attribute that you want to monitor. This attribute must be in the WebLogic Server MIB.
a-AudienceEnabled-help: Specifies whether the audience from the access token is stored in the subject for later use by the application.
a-AuthCookieEnabled-help: Enables use of additional secure AuthCookie to make access to https pages with security constraints more secure. The session cookie will not be sufficient to gain access. The default value is true.
f-any_Realm-a-AuthMethods-help: The list of authentication methods that should be used when the Web application specifies "REALM" as its auth-method. The authentication methods will be applied in order in which they appear in the list.
f-NMProperties-a-AuthenticationEnabled-h: If set to true, Node Manager authenticates the credentials against the domain.
a-AuthenticationProtocol-help: The protocol that this SNMP agent uses to ensure that only authorized users can request or receive information about your WebLogic Server domain. Applicable only with SNMPv3. The protocol also ensures message integrity and prevents masquerading and reordered, delayed, or replayed messages. To use this protocol when receiving requests from SNMP managers, you must configure credential mapping in the WebLogic Server security realm. To use this protocol when sending responses or notifications, you must configure the security level of your trap destinations. If you do not choose an authentication protocol, then the SNMP agent does not authenticate incoming SNMPv3 requests; anyone can use SNMPv3 to retrieve information about your WebLogic Server domain.
f-any_SingleSignOnServices-a-AuthnReques: The maximum size of the authentication request cache. This cache stores documents issued by the local Service Provider that are awaiting response from a partner Identity Provider. Specify '0' to indicate that the cache is unbounded. The default value is 10000.

The maximum timeout (in seconds) of <AuthnRequest> documents stored in the local cache. This cache stores documents issued by the local Service provider that are awaiting response from a partner Identity Provider. Documents that reach this maximum timeout duration are expired from the local cache even if no response is received from the Identity Provider. If a response is subsequently returned by the Identity Provider, the cache behaves as if the <AuthnRequest> had never been generated. The default value is 300.
a-AutoMigrationEnabled-help: Specifies whether Node Manager can automatically restart this server and its services on another machine if the server fails.
a-AutoMigrationTableCreationDdlFile-labe: Auto Migration Table Creation DDL File
f-Cluster-a-AutoMigrationTableCreationDd: Specifies the absolute file path of a custom DDL file for creating the automatic migration database table. This setting applies only if the MigrationBasis attribute is set to database, the AutoMigrationTableCreationPolicy attribute is set to Always, and the table name specified by the AutoMigrationTableName attribute does not already exist in the database. If the above conditions apply, and this setting is set to the default, then the system will try to find a default DDL file for the creating the leasing database table in WL_HOME/server/db/DB_TYPE/leasing.ddl. Note that the system ignores (skips) any DROP commands in the DDL file, and substitutes the value configured in the AutoMigrationTableName attribute for all occurrences of the word ACTIVE in the file.
f-Cluster-a-AutoMigrationTableCreationPo: Specifies the automatic leasing table creation behavior. This setting applies only if the MigrationBasis attribute is set to database.
f-Cluster-a-AutoMigrationTableName-help: Specifies the name of the table to be used for server migration. This setting applies only if the MigrationBasis attribute is set to database. If the AutoMigrationTableCreationPolicy is set to Always, then the table name format must be specified in the form [[[mycatalog.]myschema.]mytablename; for example myschema.mytablename. Each period symbol format is significant, where schema generally corresponds to username in many databases. When no table name is specified, the table name is simply ACTIVE and the database implicitly determines the schema according to the JDBC data source user.
a-AutoRestart-help: Specifies whether the Node Manager can automatically restart this server if it crashes or otherwise goes down unexpectedly.
a-AutoRestartOnNonDynamicChanges-label: Auto Restart On Non Dynamic Changes
f-any_Realm-a-AutoRestartOnNonDynamicCha: Specifies whether the Realm will be auto-restarted if non-dynamic changes are made to the realm or providers within the realm.
f-EmbeddedLDAP-a-BackupCopies-help: The maximum number of backup copies that should be made for the embedded LDAP server. This value limits the number of zip files in the ldap/backup directory.
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource_Coheren: The backup directory for the default persistence environment. If no value is specified, the directory which will be used is the coherence/backup sub-directory under Domain Home directory.
f-EmbeddedLDAP-a-BackupHour-help: The hour at which the embedded LDAP server should be backed up. The Backup Hour value is used in conjunction with the Backup Minute value to determine the time at which the embedded LDAP server data files are backed up. At the specified time, WebLogic Server suspends writes to the embedded LDAP server, backs up the data files into a zip files in the ldap/backup directory, and then resumes writes.
f-EmbeddedLDAP-a-BackupMinute-help: The minute at which the embedded LDAP server should be backed up. The Backup Minute value is used in conjunction with the Back Up Hour value to determine the time at which the embedded LDAP server data files are backed up.
a-Base64DecodingRequired-help: Specifies whether the tokens that are passed to the Identity Assertion provider will be base64 decoded first. If false then the server will not base64 decode the token before passing it to the identity asserter. This defaults to true for backwards compatibility but most providers will probably want to set this to false.
a-Base64EncodingException-itemHelp: Specifies a token type that does not require Base64 decoding to add to the list.
f-any_DefaultIdentityAsserter-a-Base64En: Specifies the list of token types whose tokens do not need to be Base64 decoded.
a-BasePath-help: Specifies the URI base path used for the connection to the Oracle Identity Cloud Service.
a-BaseRetransmissionInterval-help: The interval of time that must pass before a message will be retransmitted to the RM destination (in the event a prior transmission failed). String value in "Duration" format. Defaults to "P0DT3S" (3 seconds). Set at sequence creation time, and cannot be reset.
f-any_SingleSignOnServices-a-BasicAuthPa: The password used to assign Basic Authentication credentials to outgoing HTTPS connections.
f-any_SingleSignOnServices-a-BasicAuthUs: The username that is used to assign Basic authentication credentials to outgoing HTTPS connections.
f-MessagingBridge-a-BatchInterval-help: The maximum amount of time, in milliseconds, that a messaging bridge instance waits before sending a batch of messages in one transaction, regardless of whether the Batch Size has been reached or not. Only applies to a messaging bridge instance forwarding messages in synchronous mode and has a QOS (quality of service) that requires two-phase transactions. The default value of -1 indicates that the bridge instance waits until the number of messages reaches the Batch Size before it completes a transaction.
a-BatchJobsDataSourceJndiName-label: Batch Jobs Data Source JNDI Name
a-BatchJobsDataSourceJndiName-help: Specifies the Batch DataSource jndi name. This jndi name will be used to lookup an instance of a DataSource that will be used to store the Batch jobs data.
a-BatchJobsExecutorServiceName-help: Specifies the name of the application-scoped ManagedExecutorService. This ManagedExecutorService instance will be used to run batch jobs that are submitted from applications deployed to the domain. The ManagedExecutorServiceTemplate by the same name must exist when a batch job is submitted in the domain. If this returns null, then the batch runtime will look to use the default Java EE ManagedExecutorService that is bound to the JNDI name: java:comp/DefaultManagedExecutorService.
f-MessagingBridge-a-BatchSize-help: The number of messages that are processed within one transaction. Batch Size only applies to a messaging bridge instance forwarding messages in synchronous mode and has a QOS (quality of service) that requires two-phase transactions.
a-BeforeCompletionIterationLimit-help: The maximum number of cycles that the transaction manager performs the beforeCompletion synchronization callback for this WebLogic Server domain. Nothing prevents a Synchronization object from registering another during beforeCompletion, even those whose beforeCompletions have already been called. For example, an EJB can call another in its ejbStore() method. To accommodate this, the transaction manager calls all Synchronization objects, then repeats the cycle if new ones have been registered. This count sets a limit to the number of cycles that synchronization occurs.
f-any_DefaultAuditor-a-BeginMarker-help: The marker that indicates the beginning of the audit record.
a-BindAnonymouslyOnReferrals-help: Specifies whether to anonymously bind when following referrals within the LDAP directory. If set to false, then the current Principal and Credential will be used.
f-FileStore-a-BlockSize-help: The smallest addressable block, in bytes, of a file. When a native wlfileio driver is available and the block size has not been configured by the user, the store selects the minimum OS specific value for unbuffered (direct) I/O, if it is within the range [512, 8192]. A file store's block size does not change once the file store creates its files. Changes to block size only take effect for new file stores or after the current files have been deleted. See "Tuning the Persistent Store" in Tuning Performance of Oracle WebLogic Server.
f-any_DefaultFileStore-a-BlockSize-help: The smallest addressable block, in bytes, of a file. When a native wlfileio driver is available and the block size has not been configured by the user, the store selects the minimum OS specific value for unbuffered (direct) I/O, if it is within the range [512, 8192]. A file store's block size does not change once the file store creates its files. Changes to block size only take effect for new file stores or after the current files have been deleted. See "Tuning the Persistent Store" in Tuning Performance of Oracle WebLogic Server.
f-WTCServer_WTCLocalTuxDom-a-BlockTime-h: The maximum number of seconds this local Tuxedo access point allows for a blocking call. Must be between 0 and 2147483647, with the default value being 60.
f-JMSServer-a-BlockingSendPolicy-help: Determines whether the JMS server delivers smaller messages before larger ones when a destination has exceeded its maximum number of messages. FIFO prevents the JMS server from delivering smaller messages when larger ones are already waiting for space. Preemptive allows smaller send requests to preempt previous larger ones when there is sufficient space for smaller messages on the destination. This policy is defined only for the JMS server; it cannot be set on individual destinations.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_WatchN: The body for the mail message. If the body is not specified, a body is created from the action information.
f-SecurityConfiguration-a-BootAuthentica: The maximum length of time, in milliseconds, the boot process will wait before retrying the authentication after a login server not available exception. The boot process will use a backoff algorithm starting at 100 milliseconds increasing on each failure until the delay time reaches the MaxRetryDelay value.

The maximum number of times the boot process will try to authenticate the boot user with the authentication providers. The authentication will be retried only if a failure occurs that indicates the login server is not available.
a-BufferSizeKb-help: Specifies the underlying log buffer size in kilobytes. The default value is 8.
f-JMSServer_JmsMessageLogFile-a-BufferSi: Sets the underlying log buffer size in kilobytes.
f-SAFAgent_JmssafMessageLogFile-a-Buffer: Sets the underlying log buffer size in kilobytes.
a-BytesHigh-help: The upper threshold (total number of bytes in this destination) that triggers logging or flow control events. The value of java.lang.Long.MAX_VALUE disables logging and flow control events for the destination.
a-BytesLow-help: The lower threshold (total number of bytes in this destination) that triggers logging or flow control events. The value of java.lang.Long.MAX_VALUE disables logging and flow control events for the destination.
f-JMSServer-a-BytesMaximum-help: The maximum number of bytes that can be stored in this JMS server. A value of -1 removes any WebLogic Server limits.
f-SAFAgent-a-BytesMaximum-help: The maximum bytes quota (total amount of bytes) that can be stored in this SAF agent. The default value of -1 specifies that there is no WebLogic-imposed limit on the number of bytes that can be stored. However, excessive bytes volume can cause memory saturation, so this value should correspond to the total amount of available system memory relative to the rest of your application load.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Quota-a-: The total number of bytes that can be stored in a destination that uses this quota. A value of zero means that no messages can be placed on a destination without exceeding the quota. A value of -1 prevents WebLogic Server from imposing a limit.
f-JMSServer-a-BytesThresholdHigh-help: The upper threshold (number of bytes stored in this JMS server) that triggers flow control and logging events. A value of -1 disables the events for this JMS server.
f-SAFAgent-a-BytesThresholdHigh-help: The upper threshold value that triggers events based on the number of bytes stored in the SAF agent. The default value of -1 disables the events for this SAF agent.
f-JMSServer-a-BytesThresholdLow-help: The lower threshold (number of bytes stored in this JMS server) that triggers flow control and logging events. A value of -1 disables the events for this JMS server.
f-SAFAgent-a-BytesThresholdLow-help: The lower threshold that triggers events based on the number of bytes stored in the SAF agent. The default value of -1 disables the events for this SAF agent.
a-COMEnabled-help: Specifies whether COM support is enabled on the regular (non-SSL) port. COM is not supported on the SSL port.  Deprecated in 12.2.1.2
a-CacheConfigurationFile-help: The cache configuration file being used by this CoherenceCacheConfigMBean.
f-FileStore-a-CacheDirectory-help: The location of the cache directory for Direct-Write-With-Cache, ignored for other policies. When Direct-Write-With-Cache is specified as the SynchronousWritePolicy, cache files are created in addition to primary files (see Directory for the location of primary files). If a cache directory location is specified, the cache file path is CacheDirectory/WLStoreCache/StoreNameFileNum.DAT.cache. When specified, Oracle recommends using absolute paths, but if the directory location is a relative path, then CacheDirectory is created relative to the WebLogic Server instance's home directory. If "" or Null is specified, the Cache Directory is located in the current operating system temp directory as determined by the java.io.tmpdir Java System property (JDK's default: /tmp on UNIX, %TEMP% on Windows) and is TempDirectory/WLStoreCache/DomainName/unique-id/ StoreNameFileNum.DAT.cache. The value of java.io.tmpdir varies between operating systems and configurations, and can be overridden by passing -Djava.io.tmpdir=My_path on the JVM command line.
f-any_DefaultFileStore-a-CacheDirectory-: The location of the cache directory for Direct-Write-With-Cache, ignored for other policies. When Direct-Write-With-Cache is specified as the SynchronousWritePolicy, cache files are created in addition to primary files (see Directory for the location of primary files). If a cache directory location is specified, the cache file path is CacheDirectory/WLStoreCache/StoreNameFileNum.DAT.cache. When specified, Oracle recommends using absolute paths, but if the directory location is a relative path, then CacheDirectory is created relative to the WebLogic Server instance's home directory. If "" or Null is specified, the Cache Directory is located in the current operating system temp directory as determined by the java.io.tmpdir Java System property (JDK's default: /tmp on UNIX, %TEMP% on Windows) and is TempDirectory/WLStoreCache/DomainName/unique-id/ StoreNameFileNum.DAT.cache. The value of java.io.tmpdir varies between operating systems and configurations, and can be overridden by passing -Djava.io.tmpdir=My_path on the JVM command line.
a-CacheDiskSize-help: The disk size, in MB, of the persistent disk cache. The default value is 5 MB.
f-EmbeddedLDAP-a-CacheEnabled-help: Specifies whether a cache is used with the embedded LDAP server. This cache is used when a managed server is reading or writing to the master embedded LDAP server that is running on the Administration server.
f-any_ActiveDirectoryAuthenticator-a-Cac: Specifies whether to cache LDAP requests with the LDAP server.
f-any_IPlanetAuthenticator-a-CacheEnable: Specifies whether to cache LDAP requests with the LDAP server.
f-any_LDAPAuthenticator-a-CacheEnabled-h: Specifies whether to cache LDAP requests with the LDAP server.
f-any_LDAPX509IdentityAsserter-a-CacheEn: Specifies whether to cache LDAP requests with the LDAP server.
f-any_NovellAuthenticator-a-CacheEnabled: Specifies whether to cache LDAP requests with the LDAP server.
f-any_OpenLDAPAuthenticator-a-CacheEnabl: Specifies whether to cache LDAP requests with the LDAP server.
f-any_OracleInternetDirectoryAuthenticat: Specifies whether to cache LDAP requests with the LDAP server.
f-any_OracleUnifiedDirectoryAuthenticato: Specifies whether to cache LDAP requests with the LDAP server.
f-any_OracleVirtualDirectoryAuthenticato: Specifies whether to cache LDAP requests with the LDAP server.
f-any_weblogic.security.providers.authen: Specifies whether to cache the Oracle Identity Cloud Service user's information.
a-CacheLocation-help: Provides the path name for the persistent cache files. The default value is "xmlcache".
a-CacheMemorySize-help: The memory size, in KB, of the cache. The default value is 500 KB.
f-EmbeddedLDAP-a-CacheSize-help: Specifies the size of the cache (in kilobytes) that is used with the embedded LDAP server.
f-any_ActiveDirectoryAuthenticator-a-Cac: Specifies the size of the cache in KBs. The default value is 32.
f-any_IPlanetAuthenticator-a-CacheSize-h: Specifies the size of the cache in KBs. The default value is 32.
f-any_LDAPAuthenticator-a-CacheSize-help: Specifies the size of the cache in KBs. The default value is 32.
f-any_LDAPX509IdentityAsserter-a-CacheSi: Specifies the size of the cache in KBs. The default value is 32.
f-any_NovellAuthenticator-a-CacheSize-he: Specifies the size of the cache in KBs. The default value is 32.
f-any_OpenLDAPAuthenticator-a-CacheSize-: Specifies the size of the cache in KBs. The default value is 32.
f-any_OracleInternetDirectoryAuthenticat: Specifies the size of the cache in KBs. The default value is 32.
f-any_OracleUnifiedDirectoryAuthenticato: Specifies the size of the cache in KBs. The default value is 32.
f-any_OracleVirtualDirectoryAuthenticato: Specifies the size of the cache in KBs. The default value is 32.
f-any_weblogic.security.providers.authen: Specifies the maximum number of entries to cache. The default value is 500.
f-EmbeddedLDAP-a-CacheTTL-help: The time-to-live of the cache (in seconds) that is used with the embedded LDAP server.
a-CacheTimeoutInterval-help: The default timeout interval, in seconds, for the cache. The default value is 120 seconds.
f-any_XMLEntitySpecRegistryEntry-a-Cache: Specifies the default timeout interval (in seconds) of the external entity cache. A value of -1 means that the entity cache timeout interval defers to the one specified for the XML registry of which this Entity Spec entry is a part. The default value is -1.
f-any_ActiveDirectoryAuthenticator-a-Cac: Specifies the time-to-live (TTL) of the cache in seconds. The default value is 60.
f-any_IPlanetAuthenticator-a-CacheTtl-he: Specifies the time-to-live (TTL) of the cache in seconds. The default value is 60.
f-any_LDAPAuthenticator-a-CacheTtl-help: Specifies the time-to-live (TTL) of the cache in seconds. The default value is 60.
f-any_LDAPX509IdentityAsserter-a-CacheTt: Specifies the time-to-live (TTL) of the cache in seconds. The default value is 60.
f-any_NovellAuthenticator-a-CacheTtl-hel: Specifies the time-to-live (TTL) of the cache in seconds. The default value is 60.
f-any_OpenLDAPAuthenticator-a-CacheTtl-h: Specifies the time-to-live (TTL) of the cache in seconds. The default value is 60.
f-any_OracleInternetDirectoryAuthenticat: Specifies the time-to-live (TTL) of the cache in seconds. The default value is 60.
f-any_OracleUnifiedDirectoryAuthenticato: Specifies the time-to-live (TTL) of the cache in seconds. The default value is 60.
f-any_OracleVirtualDirectoryAuthenticato: Specifies the time-to-live (TTL) of the cache in seconds. The default value is 60.
f-any_weblogic.security.providers.authen: Specifies the time-to-live (TTL) of the Oracle Identity Cloud Service user cache, in seconds. The default value is 300.
f-any_HealthScore-a-CalculateIntervalSec: The interval time (in seconds) that WebLogic Server will call the health score plugin for calculating the server's health score.
f-Cluster_DynamicServers-a-CalculatedLis: Specifies whether listen ports are calculated.
f-Cluster_DynamicServers-a-CalculatedMac: Controls how server instances in a dynamic cluster are assigned to a machine. If the attribute is not set, then the dynamic servers will not be assigned to a machine. If the attribute is set, then the MachineNameMatchExpression attribute is used to select the set of machines to use for the dynamic servers.
a-CallbackQueue-help: For use only with the JAX-RPC stack. For JAX-WS, use WebServiceBufferingMBean instead. The default value is "weblogic.wsee.DefaultCallbackQueue".
a-CallbackQueueMdbRunAsPrincipalName-lab: Callback Queue MDB Run As Principal Name
a-CallbackQueueMdbRunAsPrincipalName-hel: For use only with the JAX-RPC stack. For JAX-WS, use WebServiceBufferingMBean instead.
a-CandidateMachine-help: Limits the list of candidate machines that the cluster specifies. (Requires you to enable this server for automatic migration and to configure the cluster with a set of candidate machines.) If this server fails and if it is enabled for automatic migration, Node Manager automatically restarts it. By default, Node Manager restarts the server on any of the candidate machines that the cluster specifies (in order of preference that you configured in the cluster). To change the default, you use this server's list of candidate machines to create a subset of the cluster-wide candidates. You can also change the order of preference.
a-CandidateMachinesForMigratableServer-i: Specify a candidate machine opn which a node manager can restart failed servers.
f-Cluster-a-CandidateMachinesForMigratab: Specifies the set of machines (and order of preference) on which Node Manager will restart failed servers. (Requires you to enable each server for automatic migration.) Each server can specify a subset of these cluster-wide candidates, which limits the machines on which the server can be restarted. Servers can also specify their own order of preference.
f-SelfTuning_WorkManager-a-Capacity-help: CapacityMBean defines the maximum number of requests that can be enqueued by all the work managers that share it. The server starts rejecting requests once the capacity threshold is reached. Note that the capacity includes all requests, queued or executing, from the constrained work set.
f-any_Realm-a-CertPathBuilder-help: The CertPath Builder provider in this security realm that will be used by the security system to build certification paths. The provider must be one of this security realm's CertPathProviders.
f-any_LDAPX509IdentityAsserter-a-Certifi: Specifies the name of the LDAP attribute representing the user's identity.
f-any_CertificateManagement-a-Certificat: Returns the validity period (certificate lifetime) that the Domain Certificates Issuer should set when generating a new Certificate Authority certificate. The validity period is expressed in days.
Specifies how often the Certificate Management Service should check for/refresh expiring certificates (in days).
f-any_LDAPX509IdentityAsserter-a-Certifi: Specifies the mapping of certificate attributes to directory attributes.
f-any_CertificateManagement-a-Certificat: The Certificate Management Service will refresh an expiring certificate when its remaining lifetime is less than this number of days.
a-CertificateRequestProperties-keyHelp: Specifies the certificate request property name.
a-CertificateRequestProperties-valueHelp: Specifies the certificate request property value.
f-any_CertificateIssuerPlugin-a-Certific: Returns the properties to be passed to the issuer when the Certificate Service requests a certificate.
f-any_CertificateManagement-a-Certificat: The validity period (certificate lifetime) that the Domain Certificates Issuer should set when generating a new certificate, specified in days.
f-WebAppContainer-a-ChangeSessionIDOnAut: Global property to determine if we need to generate a new SessionID after authentication. When this property is set to "false", the previous sessionID will be retained even after authorization.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-ChannelIdenti: Whether or not the channel's custom identity should be used. This setting only has an effect if the server is using a customized keystore. By default the channel's identity is inherited from the server's identity.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-ChannelWeight: A weight to give this channel when creating server-to-server connections. The default value is 50.
a-CharacterLimit-help: The character limit for Coherence logs.
a-Charsets-keyHelp: Specifies the name of the Internet character set to map.
a-Charsets-valueHelp: Specifies the name of the Java character set to which to map.
a-Charsets-help: Provides user defined mapping between internet and Java charset names.
f-SecurityConfiguration-a-CheckCertifica: Specifies the number of days before certificate expiration that warnings should be issued.
Specifies the interval between checks for certificate expiration.
f-SecurityConfiguration-a-CheckIdentityC: Specifies whether identity certificates should be checked periodically for expiration.
f-SecurityConfiguration-a-CheckTrustCert: Specifies whether trust certificates should be checked periodically for expiration.
f-any_OracleInternetDirectoryAuthenticat: Specifies whether to check if the user is enabled, e.g. check the OrclIsEnabled attribute value from the Oracle Internet Directory LDAP server. The default value is false.
f-any_CertRevocCa-a-CheckingDisabled-hel: For this CA, determines whether certificate revocation checking is disabled.
f-any_CertRevoc-a-CheckingEnabled-help: Determines whether certificate revocation checking is enabled.
a-CheckpointIntervalSeconds-help: The interval at which the transaction manager creates a new transaction log file and checks all old transaction log files to see if they are ready to be deleted.
a-ChunkedTransferDisabled-help: Indicates whether the use of Chunk Transfer-Encoding in HTTP/1.1 is enabled.
f-NMProperties-a-CipherSuites-help: Specifies the name of the cipher suites to use with the node manager's SSL listener. You can specify multiple cipher suite values separated by a comma, for example: CipherSuites=SUITE_A,SUITE_B,SUITE_C. The strongest negotiated cipher suite is chosen during the SSL handshake. The set of cipher suites used by default by JSSE depends on the specific JDK version with which node manager is configured.
a-Ciphersuite-itemHelp: Specify a cipher suite to add to the list.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-Ciphersuite-h: Indicates the cipher suites being used on a particular WebLogic Server channel. The strongest negotiated cipher suite is chosen during the SSL handshake. The set of cipher suites used by default by JSSE depends on the specific JDK version with which WebLogic Server is configured.
f-any_SSL-a-Ciphersuite-help: Indicates the cipher suites being used on a particular WebLogic Server. The strongest negotiated cipher suite is chosen during the SSL handshake. The set of cipher suites used by default by JSSE depends on the specific JDK version with which WebLogic Server is configured.
f-ShutdownClass-a-ClassName-help: The fully qualified name of the Shutdown class to load and run. The class must be on the server's classpath.
f-StartupClass-a-ClassName-help: The fully qualified name of the Startup class to load and run. The class must be on the server's classpath.
f-SingletonService-a-ClassName-help: The fully qualified name of a SingletonServices class to load and run. The class must be on the server's classpath.
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource_Coheren: The class that implements com.tangosol.net.security.IdentityAsserter. If className is empty, no IdentityAsserter will be configured.
f-Callout-a-ClassName-help: Specifies the fully qualified name of a class to load and run.
f-WebserviceSecurity_WebserviceCredentia: The fully qualified name of the class that implements a particular credential provider or token handler.
f-WebserviceSecurity_WebserviceSecurityT: The fully qualified name of the class that implements a particular credential provider or token handler.
f-WebserviceSecurity_WebserviceTokenHand: The fully qualified name of the class that implements a particular credential provider or token handler.
a-ClassPath-itemHelp: Specify the file or directory to add to the class path.
f-SystemComponent_SystemComponentStart-a: The classpath (path on the machine running Node Manager) to use when starting this server. If you need to add user classes to the classpath, in addition you will need to add the following: FEATURES_HOME/weblogic.server.modules.coherence.integration.jar:COHERENCE_HOME/lib/coherence.jar where FEATURES_HOME is the features directory (typically $WL_HOME/modules/features) and COHERENCE_HOME the coherence directory (typically $ORACLE_HOME/coherence) on the Node Manager machine. If you do not specify a classpath the above will be used automatically. The operating system determines which character separates path elements. On Windows, use a semicolon (;). On UNIX a colon (:).
f-any_ServerStart-a-ClassPath-help: The classpath (on the machine running Node Manager) to use when starting this server.
a-ClasspathServletDisabled-help: The ClasspathServlet will serve any class file in the classpath and is registered by default in every Web application (including management). It does not need to be turned on for many applications though, and represents a security hole if unchecked while the ClassPathServletSecureModeEnabled is also set to false. WLS components such as JDBC and JMS rely on the ClasspathServlet. If the servlet can not be disabled, then set the ClassPathServletSecureModeEnabled to true. The default value is false except in secure production mode.
a-ClasspathServletSecureModeEnabled-help: If secure mode is enabled, the ClasspathServlet will serve only class files from well-known packages required for JDBC and JMS functionality. If secure mode is disabled, it represents a security hole if unchecked as the ClassPatchServlet will serve any class in the classpath and is registered by default in every Web application (including management). If set to true, the ClasspathServlet will not be disabled by the DefaultInternalServletsDisabled value of true. The default value is false except in secure production mode.
a-CleanerInterval-help: Specifies the interval at which the persistent store will be cleaned. The default value is "PT10M" (10 minutes).
a-CleanupOrphanedSessionsEnabled-help: Indicates if replication service should cleanup orphaned http and ejb sessions. Orphaned sessions are http and ejb session instances that are not referenced by the replication service. The default value is false.
f-SecurityConfiguration-a-ClearTextCrede: Specifies whether to allow access to credential in clear text.
a-ClientAsUserPrincipalEnabled-help: Specifies whether the client name from the access token is stored in the subject as the username for later use by the application.
f-any_SSL-a-ClientCertAlias-help: Determines the alias of the client SSL certificate to be used as identity for outbound SSL connections. The certificate is assumed to be stored in the server configured keystore. Note that to use the client SSL certificate, UseClientCertForOutbound must be enabled.
f-any_SSL-a-ClientCertPrivateKeyPassPhra: The passphrase used to retrieve the private key for the client SSL certificate specified in ClientCertAlias from the server configured keystore. This passphrase is assigned to the private key when the private key is generated. Note that this attribute is usually used when outbound SSL connections specify a client SSL certificate identity.
a-ClientCertProxyEnabled-help: Specifies whether or not to honor the WL-Proxy-Client-Cert header coming with the request.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-ClientCertifi: Specifies whether clients must present digital certificates from a trusted certificate authority to WebLogic Server on this channel. The default value is true.
f-any_SSL-a-ClientCertificateEnforced-he: ndicates whether or not clients must present digital certificates from a trusted certificate authority to WebLogic Server. The default value is true.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Connecti: An optional Client ID for applications that use this JMS connection factory. If the Client ID Policy is set to Restricted (the default), then configuring a Client ID on the connection factory prevents more than one JMS client from using a connection from this factory.
f-any_weblogic.security.providers.authen: Specifies the Client Id used when retrieving tokens from the Oracle Identity Cloud Service.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Connecti: The Client ID Policy indicates whether more than one JMS connection can use the same Client ID.
a-ClientIdResourceAttribute-help: Specifies the attribute used for Client ID App Assertion. The default value results in the use of the attribute configured by the Oracle Identity Cloud Service.
a-ClientIdTokenClaim-help: Specifies the token attribute used to get the client Id (GUID) from the access token. The default value is "client_id".
a-ClientInitSecureRenegotiationAccepted-: Indicate whether TLS client-initiated secure renegotiation is accepted. The default value is false. Deprecated in 14.1.2.0.0; use the the JDK RFC 5746: TLS Renegotiation Extension instead.
a-ClientNameTokenClaim-help: Specifies the token attribute used to get the client name from the access token. The default value is "client_name".
a-ClientSecretEncrypted-help: Specifies the Client secret used when retrieving tokens from the Oracle Identity Cloud Service.
a-ClientTenant-help: Specifies the tenant in which the Client Id resides from the Oracle Identity Cloud Service. When no client tenant name is configured, the tenant configured for the provider is used.
a-ClientTenantTokenClaim-help: Specifies the token attribute used to get the Identity Domain for the client from the access token. The default value is "client_tenantname".
f-WebserviceSecurity_WebserviceTimestamp: If clocks are synchronized, this attribute describes the accuracy of the synchronization between two clocks: the client and the server. ClockSkew is expressed in milliseconds. Clock skew is enforced by rendering all times into milliseconds since a common time 0 and using these times for comparisons. For example, if your clocks are accurate to within 1 minute of each other, you would set your skew to 1 minute * 60 seconds * 1000 milliseconds or 60000.

Specifies whether the Web Service assumes synchronized clocks. If the clockSynchronized attribute is false, the Web Service rejects all inbound messages with that contain expirations, because this is the only safe way to ensure that the message hasn't already expired. In this case, the Web Service also does not enforce a freshness policy. If this attribute is set to true, then the Web Service enforces expirations on inbound messages to the best of its ability and enforces an optional freshness policy (via maxProcessingDelay). The default value of this attribute is true.
f-SingletonService-a-Cluster-help: The cluster to which this SingletonService is assigned.
f-MigratableTarget-a-Cluster-help: The cluster to which this MigratableTarget is assigned.
f-Server-a-Cluster-help: The cluster to which this Server is assigned.
f-ServerTemplate-a-Cluster-help: The cluster to which servers created from this ServerTemplate are assigned.
f-any_JTAMigratableTarget-a-Cluster-help: The cluster to which this JTAMigratableTarget is assigned.
f-Cluster-a-ClusterAddress-help: Specifies the address that forms a portion of the URL a client uses to connect to this cluster, and that is used for generating EJB handles and entity EJB failover addresses. (This address may be either a DNS host name that maps to multiple IP addresses or a comma-separated list of single address host names or IP addresses.) Defines the address to be used by clients to connect to this cluster. This address may be either a DNS host name that maps to multiple IP addresses or a comma separated list of single address host names or IP addresses. If network channels are configured, it is possible to set the cluster address on a per channel basis.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-ClusterAddres: The address this network channel uses to generate EJB handles and failover addresses for use in a cluster. This value is determined according to the following order of precedence: 1.) If the cluster address is specified via the NAPMBean, then that value is used. 2.) If this value is not specified, the value of PublicAddress is used. 3.) If PublicAddress is not set, this value is derive from the ClusterAddress attribute of the ClusterMBean. 4.) If ClusterMBean.clusterAddress is not set, this value is derive from the listen address of the NAPMBean.
f-Cluster-a-ClusterBroadcastChannel-help: Specifies the channel used to handle communications within a cluster. If no channel is specified then the servers in the cluster will use the default secure channel (SSL Listen Port), if SecureClusterBroadcastEnabled attribute is true. If SecureClusterBroadcastEnabled attribute is false then servers in the cluster will use the default channel (Plain Listen Port). ClusterBroadcastChannel is only supported if the unicast messaging type is used.
a-ClusterConstraintsEnabled-help: Specifies that deployments targeted to a cluster succeed only if all servers in the cluster are running. By default, cluster constraints are disabled and deployment is attempted only on the servers that are reachable at the time of deployment from the Administration Server. Any servers that have been shut down or are temporarily partitioned from the Administration Server will retrieve the deployment during server startup or shortly after the network partition is resolved.
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource_Coheren: The cluster listen port used by Coherence; Coherence cluster members use this port to discover and join, or create the cluster.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_WatchN: Indicates the name of the cluster on which to perform the scaling action.
Indicates the name of the cluster on which to perform the scaling action.
f-Cluster-a-ClusterType-help: Optimizes cross-cluster replication for the type of network that servers in the clusters use for administrative communication. To enhance the reliability of HTTP sessions, you can configure servers in one cluster to replicate the session data to servers in a different cluster. The default value is none.
a-ClusterWeight-help: The proportion of the load that this server will bear, relative to other servers in a cluster. If all servers have the default weight or the same weight, each bears an equal proportion of the load. If one server has weight 50 and all other servers have weight 100, the 50-weight server will bear half as much load as any other server. The default value is 100.
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource_Coheren: Specifies a clustering mode of either Unicast (default) or Multicast. If multicast is undesirable or unavailable in an environment, or when an environment is not properly configured to support multicast, then setting up the Well-Known Addresses (WKA) feature is required. All cluster multicast communication is disabled if any of WKA, SSL, and/or secured production mode is/are enabled.
a-ClusterwideRecoveryEnabled-help: Indicates that cluster-wide recovery is used for distributed transactions. When enabled, recovery operations for a distributed transaction are applied to all the servers of the cluster hosting a InterposedTransactionManager rather than just the server hosting the InterposedTransactionManager.
f-WTCServer_WTCLocalTuxDom-a-CmpLimit-he: The compression threshold this local Tuxedo access point uses when sending data to a remote Tuxedo access point. Application buffers larger than this size are compressed. Must be between 0 and 2147483647, where 2147483647 is the default value if not specified
f-WTCServer_WTCRemoteTuxDom-a-CmpLimit-h: The compression threshold this remote Tuxedo access point uses when sending data to a local Tuxedo access point. Application buffers larger than this size are compressed. Must be between 0 and 2147483647, where 2147483647 is the default value if not specified
f-AllowList-a-CoherenceClassesAlwaysBloc: Specifies whether the domain will run with blocking all the coherence classes if the CoherenceClusterSystemResourceMBean is not used in the domain.
a-CoherenceClientAuth-help: The client authentication mode to use.
a-CoherenceClusterSystemResource-help: The system-level Coherence cluster resource associated with this server.
a-CoherenceIdentityAlias-help: The string alias used to store and retrieve the Coherence Identity private key in the keystore. This private key is associated with the Coherence Identity digital certificate. If this alias is null, the Server SSL identity alias will be used.
a-CoherenceKeyRefreshPeriod-help: he period to use to attempt to refresh keys and certs. This is used in cases where keys or certs have a short lifetime and need to be refreshed at runtime. If this element is omitted or is set to a value less than or equal to zero, then keys and certs will not be refreshed.
a-CoherencePrivateKeyPassPhraseEncrypted: The passphrase used to retrieve the private key for the Coherence Identity specified in the server configured keystore. This passphrase is assigned to the private key when the private key is generated.
a-CoherenceWebFederatedStorageEnabled-he: Specifies whether Federated Cache Storage is enabled for the Coherence Web cluster member.
a-CoherenceWebLocalStorageEnabled-help: Specifies whether Local Storage is enabled for the Coherence Web cluster tier.
f-any_CoherenceMemberConfig-a-CoherenceW: Specifies whether Local Storage is enabled for the Coherence Web cluster member.
f-any_Realm-a-CombinedRoleMappingEnabled: Determines how the role mappings in the Enterprise Application, Web application, and EJB containers interact. This setting is valid only for Web applications and EJBs that use the Advanced security model and that initialize roles from deployment descriptors.
f-any_SNMPProxy-a-Community-help: The community name to be passed on for all SNMPv1 requests to this proxied SNMP agent. If you specify a security name for this proxied agent, the WebLogic SNMP agent ignores this community name. Instead, the agent encodes the security name in an SNMPv3 request and forwards the SNMPv3 request to this proxied agent.
f-any_SNMPTrapDestination-a-Community-he: The password (community name) that a WebLogic Server SNMP agent sends to the SNMP manager when the agent generates SNMPv1 or SNMPv2 notifications. The community name that you enter in this trap destination must match the name that the SNMP manager defines.
a-CommunityBasedAccessEnabled-help: Specifies whether this SNMP agent supports SNMPv1 and v2. SNMPv1 and v2 use community strings for authentication. If you disable community strings for this SNMP agent, the agent will process only SNMPv3 requests. If an SNMP manager sends a v1 or v2 message, the agent discards the message and returns an error code to the manager.
a-CommunityPrefix-help: The password (community name) that you want this SNMP agent to use to secure SNMPv1 or v2 communication with SNMP managers. Requires you to enable community based access for this agent. SNMPv3 does not use community names. Instead, it encrypts user names and passwords in its PDUs.
f-SecurityConfiguration-a-CompatibilityC: Specifies whether this WebLogic Server domain enables compatiblity with previous connection filters. This attribute changes the protocols names used when filtering needs to be performed.
f-JMX-a-CompatibilityMBeanServerEnabled-: Enables JMX clients to use the deprecated MBeanHome interface. Prior to 9.0, WebLogic Server supported a typed API layer over its JMX layer. Your JMX application classes could import type-safe interfaces for WebLogic Server MBeans, retrieve a reference to the MBeans through the weblogic.management.MBeanHome interface, and invoke the MBean methods directly.
a-CompatibilityName-help: This is only set for beans created as a result of conversion from an 8.1 application configured using ApplicationMBean and ComponentMBean. Standalone modules in 8.1 have both an ApplicationMBean name and ComponentMBean name. This attribute stores the name of the latter, to be used when the server creates the transient ComponentMBean for backward compatibility.
f-WebserviceSecurity-a-CompatibilityOrde: Specifies the value of the compatibilityOrderingPreference attribute.
f-WebserviceSecurity-a-CompatibilityPref: Specifies the value of the compatibilityPreference attribute.
a-CompleteMessageTimeout-help: Specifies the maximum number of seconds that this server waits for a complete message to be received. If you configure network channels for this server, each channel can override this message timeout. This timeout helps guard against a denial of service attack in which a caller indicates that it will be sending a message of a certain size which it never finishes sending. CompleteMessageTimeout affects the HTTP Response, such that if WebLogic Server discovers sockets inactive for longer than the CompleteMessageTimeout, the server will close these sockets. The default value is 60.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-CompleteMessa: The maximum amount of time this network channel waits for a complete message to be received. A value of 0 disables network channel complete message timeout. A value of -1 indicates that the network channel obtains this timeout value from the ServerTemplateMBean. This timeout helps guard against denial of service attacks in which a caller indicates that they will be sending a message of a certain size which they never finish sending.
a-CompleteWriteTimeout-help: Specifies the maximum number of seconds that this server waits for a complete HTTP response to be sent. A value of 0 disables the complete write timeout. The default value is derived from the CompleteHTTPMessageTimeout. If it is -1, then the CompleteMessageTimeout value is used for the default value.
a-CompletionTimeoutSeconds-help: Specifies the maximum amount of time, in seconds, a transaction manager waits for all resource managers to respond and indicate if the transaction can be committed or rolled back. The default value is 0, which sets the value to approximately twice the default transaction-timeout value with a maximum value of 120 seconds. This value provides backward compatibility for prior releases without this setting. nIf the specified value is -1, the maximum value supported by this attribute is used. If the specified value exceeds the value set for abandon-timeout-seconds, the value of abandon-timeout-seconds is used.
f-SystemComponent-a-ComponentType-help: The system component type Examples of types may include "OHS", "Coherence". New System Components may be added in the future so the list of types is not static.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_SAFRemot: The number of bytes for a serialized message body so that any message that exceeds this limit triggers message compression when the message is about to be sent across a SAF agent's JVM boundary. The compression will occur on the sending-side SAF agent's JVM if the message body size exceeds the threshold limit.
f-Cluster-a-ConcurrentSingletonActivatio: Specifies whether to allow the concurrent activation, deactivation, or restart of two or more singleton services.
a-ConfigBackupEnabled-help: If true, then backups of the configuration will be made during server boot. The default value is false.
a-ConfigurationAuditType-help: Specifies the criteria used for auditing configuration events (configuration changes and other operations). The default value is none except in secure production mode, where the value defaults to audit.
f-WTCServer_WTCLocalTuxDom-a-ConnPrincip: The principal name used to verify the identity of this domain when establishing a connection to another domain. Note that this parameter only applies to domains of type TDOMAIN that are running Oracle Tuxedo 7.1 or later software. If not specified, the connection principal name defaults to the AccessPointID for this domain.ConnPrincipalName.
f-WTCServer_WTCRemoteTuxDom-a-ConnPrinci: The principal name used to verify the identity of this remote Tuxedo access point when it establishes a session connection with a local Tuxedo access point. If not specified, the connection principal name defaults to the AccessPointID for this access point. Note that this parameter only applies to domains of type TDOMAIN that are running Oracle Tuxedo 7.1 or later software.
f-any_ActiveDirectoryAuthenticator-a-Con: Specifies the maximum number of seconds to wait for the LDAP connection to be established.
f-any_IPlanetAuthenticator-a-ConnectTime: Specifies the maximum number of seconds to wait for the LDAP connection to be established.
f-any_LDAPAuthenticator-a-ConnectTimeout: Specifies the maximum number of seconds to wait for the LDAP connection to be established.
f-any_LDAPX509IdentityAsserter-a-Connect: Specifies the maximum number of seconds to wait for the LDAP connection to be established.
f-any_NovellAuthenticator-a-ConnectTimeo: Specifies the maximum number of seconds to wait for the LDAP connection to be established.
f-any_OpenLDAPAuthenticator-a-ConnectTim: Specifies the maximum number of seconds to wait for the LDAP connection to be established.
f-any_OracleInternetDirectoryAuthenticat: Specifies the maximum number of seconds to wait for the LDAP connection to be established.
f-any_OracleUnifiedDirectoryAuthenticato: Specifies the maximum number of seconds to wait for the LDAP connection to be established.
f-any_OracleVirtualDirectoryAuthenticato: Specifies the maximum number of seconds to wait for the LDAP connection to be established.
f-any_weblogic.security.providers.authen: Specifies the maximum time to wait, in seconds, for the connection to the Oracle Identity Cloud Service to be established. The default value is 60.
