f-Server-a-ConnectTimeout-help: Specifies the amount of time that this server should wait to establish an outbound socket connection before timing out. A value of 0 disables server connect timeout.
f-ServerTemplate-a-ConnectTimeout-help: Specifies the amount of time that this server should wait to establish an outbound socket connection before timing out. A value of 0 disables server connect timeout.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-ConnectTimeou: The amount of time that this network channel should wait to establish an outbound socket connection before timing out. A value of 0 disables network channel connect timeout.
a-ConnectionCachingPolicy-help: For advanced use only: sets the connection caching policy for the JDBC store. The default value is "DEFAULT".
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: The number of seconds between attempts to establish connections to the database. If you do not set this value, data source creation fails if the database is unavailable. If set and if the database is unavailable when the data source is created, WebLogic Server will attempt to create connections in the pool again after the number of seconds you specify, and will continue to attempt to create the connections until it succeeds. When set to 0, connection retry is disabled.
a-ConnectionFactoryJndiName-help: The JNDI name of the connection factory to use when buffering messages onto this queue. Defaults to the 'default' JMS connection factory.
f-JMSBridgeDestination-a-ConnectionFacto: The connection factory's JNDI name for this JMS bridge destination.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_WatchN: The JNDI name of the JMS connection factory. If a name has not been specified, the default JMS connection factory is used.
f-SecurityConfiguration-a-ConnectionFilt: The name of the Java class that implements a connection filter (that is, the weblogic.security.net.ConnectionFilter interface). If no class name is specified, no connection filter will be used.
a-ConnectionFilterIgnoreRuleErrorsEnable: Connection Filter Ignore Rule Errors Enabled
f-SecurityConfiguration-a-ConnectionFilt: Specifies whether the WebLogic Server should ignore filter rule errors during server startup.
a-ConnectionFilterRule-itemHelp: Specify a rule to use for connection filters. The default implementation rules are in the format: target localAddress localPort action protocols.
f-SecurityConfiguration-a-ConnectionFilt: The rules used by any connection filter that implements the ConnectionFilterRulesListener interface. When using the default implementation and when no rules are specified, all connections are accepted. The default implementation rules are in the format: target localAddress localPort action protocols.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: The maximum number of connections that may be harvested when the connection harvesting occurs. The range of valid values is 1 to MaxCapacity.

Specifies the number of available connections (trigger value) used to determine when connection harvesting occurs. The range of valid values is -1 to MaxCapacity. The default value is -1, which disables connection harvesting.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_ForeignS: Controls connection health checking for JMS resource reference pools that access this JMS foreign connection factory mapping. The default value is Enabled.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCOr: The name of the Connection Initialization Callback class. This name is automatically passed to registerConnectionInitializationCallback when a data source is created. The class must implement oracle.ucp.jdbc.ConnectionInitializationCallback.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: The class name of the connection labeling callback. This is automatically passed to registerConnectionLabelingCallback when the datasource is created. The class must implement oracle.ucp.ConnectionLabelingCallback.
f-SecurityConfiguration-a-ConnectionLogg: Specifies whether this WebLogic Server domain should log accepted connections. This attribute can be used by a system administrator to dynamically check the incoming connections in the log file to determine if filtering needs to be performed.
f-WTCServer_WTCLocalTuxDom-a-ConnectionP: The conditions under which this local Tuxedo access point establishes a session connection with a remote Tuxedo access point. ON_DEMAND means that a connection is attempted only when requested by either a client request to a remote service or an administrative connect command. ON_STARTUP means that a domain gateway attempts to establish a connection with its remote Tuxedo access points at gateway server initialization time. Remote services (services advertised in JNDI by the domain gateway for this local access point) are advertised only if a connection is successfully established to that remote Tuxedo access point. If there is no active connection to a remote Tuxedo access point, then the remote services are suspended. By default, this connection policy retries failed connections every 60 seconds. Use the MaxRetry and RetryInterval values to specify application specific values. INCOMING_ONLY means that a domain gateway does not attempt an initial connection to remote Tuxedo access points at startup and remote services are initially suspended. The domain gateway is available for incoming connections from remote Tuxedo access points and remote services are advertised when the domain gateway for this local Tuxedo access point receives an incoming connection. Connection retry processing is not allowed.
f-WTCServer_WTCRemoteTuxDom-a-Connection: The conditions under which this remote Tuxedo access point establishes a session connection with a local Tuxedo access point. ON_DEMAND means that a connection is attempted only when requested by either a client request to a remote service or an administrative connect command. ON_STARTUP means that a domain gateway attempts to establish a connection with its remote Tuxedo access points at gateway server initialization time. Remote services (services advertised in JNDI by the domain gateway for this local Tuxedo access point) are advertised only if a connection is successfully established to that remote Tuxedo access point. If there is no active connection to a remote Tuxedo access point, then the remote services are suspended. By default, this connection policy retries failed connections every 60 seconds. Use the MaxRetry and RetryInterval attributes to specify application specific values. INCOMING_ONLY means that a domain gateway does not attempt an initial connection to remote Tuxedo access points at startup and remote services are initially suspended. The domain gateway is available for incoming connections from remote Tuxedo access points and remote services are advertised when the domain gateway for this local Tuxedo access point receives an incoming connection. Connection retry processing is not allowed. LOCAL specifies that the remote domain connection policy is explicitly defaulted to the local domain ConnectionPolicy attribute value.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCDa: The name of the application class to handle the callback sent when a multi data source is ready to failover or fail back connection requests to another data source within the multi data source. The name must be the absolute name of an application class that implements the weblogic.jdbc.extensions.ConnectionPoolFailoverCallback interface.
f-SelfTuning_MaxThreadsConstraint-a-Conn: Name of the connection pool whose size is taken as the max constraint. This can be the name of a JDBC data source. The max capacity of the data source is used as the constraint.
f-any_ActiveDirectoryAuthenticator-a-Con: Specifies the LDAP connection pool size. The default value is 6.
f-any_IPlanetAuthenticator-a-ConnectionP: Specifies the LDAP connection pool size. The default value is 6.
f-any_LDAPAuthenticator-a-ConnectionPool: Specifies the LDAP connection pool size. The default value is 6.
f-any_LDAPX509IdentityAsserter-a-Connect: Specifies the LDAP connection pool size. The default value is 6.
f-any_NovellAuthenticator-a-ConnectionPo: Specifies the LDAP connection pool size. The default value is 6.
f-any_OpenLDAPAuthenticator-a-Connection: Specifies the LDAP connection pool size. The default value is 6.
f-any_OracleInternetDirectoryAuthenticat: Specifies the LDAP connection pool size. The default value is 6.
f-any_OracleUnifiedDirectoryAuthenticato: Specifies the LDAP connection pool size. The default value is 6.
f-any_OracleVirtualDirectoryAuthenticato: Specifies the LDAP connection pool size. The default value is 6.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: The number of seconds after which a call to reserve a connection from the connection pool will timeout. When set to 0, a call will never timeout. When set to -1, a call will timeout immediately.
f-any_ActiveDirectoryAuthenticator-a-Con: Specifies the number of times to attempt to connect to the LDAP server if the initial connection failed.
f-any_IPlanetAuthenticator-a-ConnectionR: Specifies the number of times to attempt to connect to the LDAP server if the initial connection failed.
f-any_LDAPAuthenticator-a-ConnectionRetr: Specifies the number of times to attempt to connect to the LDAP server if the initial connection failed.
f-any_LDAPX509IdentityAsserter-a-Connect: Specifies the number of times to attempt to connect to the LDAP server if the initial connection failed.
f-any_NovellAuthenticator-a-ConnectionRe: Specifies the number of times to attempt to connect to the LDAP server if the initial connection failed.
f-any_OpenLDAPAuthenticator-a-Connection: Specifies the number of times to attempt to connect to the LDAP server if the initial connection failed.
f-any_OracleInternetDirectoryAuthenticat: Specifies the number of times to attempt to connect to the LDAP server if the initial connection failed.
f-any_OracleUnifiedDirectoryAuthenticato: Specifies the number of times to attempt to connect to the LDAP server if the initial connection failed.
f-any_OracleVirtualDirectoryAuthenticato: Specifies the number of times to attempt to connect to the LDAP server if the initial connection failed.
f-JMSBridgeDestination-a-ConnectionURL-h: The connection URL for this JMS bridge destination.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_ForeignS: The URL that WebLogic Server will use to contact the JNDI provider. The syntax of this URL depends on which JNDI provider is being used. For WebLogic JMS, leave this field blank if you are referencing WebLogic JMS objects within the same cluster. This value corresponds to the standard JNDI property, java.naming.provider.url. Note: If this value is not specified, look-ups will be performed on the JNDI server within the WebLogic Server instance where this connection factory is deployed.
f-Cluster-a-ConsensusParticipants-help: Controls the number of cluster participants in determining consensus.
a-ConsoleContextPath-help: The context path that you want to use in URLs that specify the Administration Console. Deprecated in 14.1.2. The default value is "console".
a-ConsoleEnabled-help: Specifies whether the Administration Server automatically deploys the Administration Console in the current domain. If the Administration Console is not deployed, you can still use the WebLogic Scripting Tool or the management APIs to configure and monitor the domain. Deprecated in 14.1.2.
a-ConsoleExtensionDirectory-help: Specifies the directory path from which console extensions are loaded. Deprecated. 14.1.2. The default value is "console-ext".
f-SecurityConfiguration-a-ConsoleFullDel: Indicates whether the console is enabled for fully delegate authorization. Deprecated in 14.1.2.0.0
a-ConstrainedCandidateServer-itemHelp: Add a server that can host a migratable service.
a-ConstrainedCandidateServer-help: The (user-restricted) list of servers that can host the migratable services deployed to this migratable target. The migratable service will not be allowed to migrate to a server that is not in the returned list of servers. For example, this feature may be used to configure two servers that have access to a dual-ported ported disk. All servers in this list must be part of the cluster that is associated with the migratable target.
a-ConsumptionPausedAtStartup-help: Specifies whether consumption is paused on a destination at startup.
f-JMSServer-a-ConsumptionPausedAtStartup: Indicates whether consumption is paused at startup on destinations targeted to this JMS server at startup. A destination cannot receive any new messages while it is paused. When the value is set to true, then immediately after the host server instance is booted, then this JMS server and its targeted destinations are modified such that they are in a "consumption paused" state, which prevents any message consuming activity on those destinations. To allow normal message consumption on the destinations, later you will have to change the state of this JMS server to a "consumption enabled" state by setting this value to false, and then either redeploy the JMS server or reboot the hosting server instance.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Template: Specifies whether message consumption is paused on destinations that use this template at server startup.
f-RemoteConsoleHelper-a-ContextPath-help: The context path used in URLs that specify the Remote Console Helper.
f-SelfTuning_WorkManager-a-ContextReques: The name of the ContextRequestClass that defines the mapping between the current context (security principal, group) and the request class to use. ContextRequestClass provides a mapping between security names/groups and request classes. During work schedule, the exact request class is determined by looking at the security information of the caller. ContextRequestClass is not a request class by itself and is used to hold the mapping of request classes.
f-WebAppContainer_Http2Config-a-Continua: The number of CONTINUATION frames allowed per stream.
a-ControlFlag-help: Specifies how the login sequence uses the Authentication provider.
f-SAFAgent-a-ConversationIdleTimeMaximum: The maximum amount of time allowed, in milliseconds, before a sending side releases the resources used by a conversation. A value of 0 specifies that resources for a conversation are not released unless the application explicitly closes the conversation.
f-AdminConsole-a-CookieName-help: Specifies the Cookie Name used by the Administration Console.
f-RemoteConsoleHelper-a-CookieName-help: The cookie name used by the Remote Console Helper.
a-CorsAllowedCredentials-help: Determines if credentials are allowed for CORS requests. When the value is false, the response will not include the corresponding CORS HTTP header.
a-CorsAllowedHeaders-itemHelp: Specify an HTTP header that is allowed for CORS requests.
a-CorsAllowedHeaders-help: Determines the value of allowed HTTP headers for CORS requests. The allowed headers value is a string that contains a comma separated list of HTTP header names. The default setting allows all headers. When the value is empty or not specified, the response will not include the corresponding CORS HTTP header.
a-CorsAllowedMethods-itemHelp: Specify an HTTP method that should be allowed for CORS requests.
a-CorsAllowedMethods-help: Determines the value of allowed HTTP methods for CORS requests. The allowed methods value is a string that contains a comma separated list of HTTP method names. The default setting allows all methods. When the value is empty or not specified, the response will not include the corresponding CORS HTTP header.
a-CorsAllowedOrigin-itemHelp: Specifies an allowed origin for CORS requests.
a-CorsAllowedOrigin-help: Determines the list of allowed origins for CORS requests. When the list is empty or not specified and CORS support is enabled then all origins are accepted. When specified the HTTP Origin header must match exactly one of the values configured as allowed. CORS origin values include protocol and domain name, they may also contain port numbers. Multiple variants of the allowed origin may need to be specified based on the origin used by the browser.
f-RestfulManagementServices-a-CorsEnable: Enables the support of CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing) processing in the RESTful Management Services Web application.
a-CorsExposedHeaders-itemHelp: Specify an HTTP header that should be exposed for CORS requests.
a-CorsExposedHeaders-help: Determines the value of exposed HTTP headers for CORS requests. The exposed headers value is a string that contains a comma separated list of HTTP header names. The default setting does not specify any specific headers. When the value is empty or not specified, the response will not include the corresponding CORS HTTP header.
a-CorsMaxAge-help: Determines the number of seconds for a browser cache of CORS preflight requests. The max age value is a string that contains a numeric value with the number of seconds used for the browser cache. The default setting does not specify any value. When the value is empty or not specified, the response will not include the corresponding CORS HTTP header.
f-SelfTuning_Capacity-a-Count-help: Total number of requests that can be accepted.  This included both requests already executing as well as those stilling in the execute queue.
f-SelfTuning_MaxThreadsConstraint-a-Coun: Maximum number of concurrent threads that can execute requests sharing this constraint. A count of 0 or -1 is treated as if the constraint is not present. This means that no constraint is enforced for these two values. A count > 0 can be dynamically changed to 0 to indicate that constraint enforcement is no longer needed.
f-SelfTuning_MinThreadsConstraint-a-Coun: Minimum number of threads available for executing concurrent requests that share this constraint. A count of 0 or -1 is treated as if the constraint is not present. This means that the constraint is ignored for these two values. A count > 0 can be dynamically changed to 0 to indicate that constraint enforcement is no longer needed.
a-CountOfRefreshFailuresTillDisable-labe: Count Of Refresh Failures Till Disable
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: Specifies the number of reconnect failures allowed before WebLogic Server disables a connection pool to minimize the delay in handling the connection request caused by a database failure. Zero means it is disabled.
a-CountOfTestFailuresTillFlush-label: Count Of Test Failures Till Flush
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: Specifies the number of test failures allowed before WebLogic Server closes all unused connections in a connection pool to minimize the delay caused by further database testing. Zero means it is disabled.
f-NMProperties-a-CrashRecoveryEnabled-he: Specifies whether the node manager is allowed to restart a failed server while the node manager was not running.
a-CreateTableDDLFile-help: Specifies the DDL (Data Definition Language) file to use for creating the JDBC store's backing table. This field is ignored when the JDBC store's backing table, WLStore, already exists.
a-CredCacheMinViableTtl-help: Specifies the minimum time, in seconds, that assertion credentials must be viable before it is eligible to be cached. If an entry in the cache has less time to live than this value, the corresponding assertion will not be used. Instead, a new assertion will be generated. Default value is 20. This attribute avoids the situation where an assertion is returned from the cache but expires before it can be evaluated at its destination. If the cached assertion's remaining time-to-live is too short, it will not be used.
a-CredCacheSize-help: Specifies the size of the cache used to store assertion credentials. If the value is not specified or not a positive number, the cache will have unlimited size. Default value is 0. The cache stores assertion credentials so that requests for the same assertion may return a result from cache, rather than generate a new assertion. This can improve performance in cases where an application may make multiple requests for the same assertion, for the same user, within a short period of time.
f-SecurityConfiguration-a-CredentialEncr: The password for the domain. In WebLogic Server version 6.0, this attribute was the password of the system user. In WebLogic Server version 7.0, this attribute can be any string. For the two domains to interoperate with Global Trust, the string must be the same for both domains.
f-EmbeddedLDAP-a-CredentialEncrypted-hel: The credential (usually a password) used to connect to the embedded LDAP server. If this credential has not been set, WebLogic Server generates a password at startup, initializes the attribute, and saves the configuration to the config.xml file. If you want to connect to the embedded LDAP server using an external LDAP browser and the embedded LDAP administrator account (cn=Admin), change this attribute from the generated value.
f-any_ActiveDirectoryAuthenticator-a-Cre: The credential (generally a password) used to authenticate the LDAP user that is defined in the Principal attribute.
f-any_IPlanetAuthenticator-a-CredentialE: The credential (generally a password) used to authenticate the LDAP user that is defined in the Principal attribute.
f-any_LDAPAuthenticator-a-CredentialEncr: The credential (generally a password) used to authenticate the LDAP user that is defined in the Principal attribute.
f-any_LDAPX509IdentityAsserter-a-Credent: The credential (generally a password) used to authenticate the LDAP user that is defined in the Principal attribute.
f-any_NovellAuthenticator-a-CredentialEn: The credential (generally a password) used to authenticate the LDAP user that is defined in the Principal attribute.
f-any_OpenLDAPAuthenticator-a-Credential: The credential (generally a password) used to authenticate the LDAP user that is defined in the Principal attribute.
f-any_OracleInternetDirectoryAuthenticat: The credential (generally a password) used to authenticate the LDAP user that is defined in the Principal attribute.
f-any_OracleUnifiedDirectoryAuthenticato: The credential (generally a password) used to authenticate the LDAP user that is defined in the Principal attribute.
f-any_OracleVirtualDirectoryAuthenticato: The credential (generally a password) used to authenticate the LDAP user that is defined in the Principal attribute.
a-CredentialMappingDeploymentEnabled-hel: Specifies whether this Credential Mapping provider stores stores credential maps created when deploying a resource adapter. The default value is true.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: Enables Set Client ID on connection for the data source. When an application requests a database connection, WebLogic Server sets a light-weight client ID on the database connection. By default, it uses the credential mapping to map WebLogic Server user IDs to database user IDs. However, if use-database-credentials is set to true, then the credential mapping is not done and the ID is used directly as a database user ID. It is currently supported for IBM DB2 driver and Oracle thin driver. Support for this feature will be dropped in a future Oracle thin driver release. Oracle recommends using proxy authentication instead of this feature.
f-WTCServer_WTCRemoteTuxDom-a-Credential: he outbound access control list (ACL) policy toward requests to a remote Tuxedo access point.  Local means that the remote Tuxedo access point controls the identity of service requests received from the local Tuxedo access point to the principal name specified in the local principal name for this remote Tuxedo access point. GLOBAL means that the remote Tuxedo access point passes the service request with no change. Note that if Interoperate is set to Yes, CredentialPolicy is ignored.
f-any_CertificateIssuerPlugin-a-Credenti: The credential set for this plugin configuration.
a-Critical-help: Specifies whether the MigratableTarget is critical to the overall health of the WLS Server.
f-any_CertRevoc-a-CrlCacheRefreshPeriodP: Determines the refresh period for the CRL local cache, expressed as a percentage of the validity period of the CRL. For example, for a validity period of 10 hours, a value of 10% specifies a refresh every 1 hour. The validity period is determined by the CRL, and is calculated as the (next reported update time) - (this update time). The valid range is 1 through 100.
f-any_CertRevoc-a-CrlCacheType-help: Determines the type of CRL cache, related to the physical storage of the CRLs. The LDAP CRL cache type can be specified, but is not currently supported.
f-any_CertRevoc-a-CrlCacheTypeLdapHostna: Determines the remote hostname for the LDAP server containing CRLs.
f-any_CertRevoc-a-CrlCacheTypeLdapPort-h: Determines the remote port for the LDAP server containing CRLs.
a-CrlCacheTypeLdapSearchTimeout-label: CRL Cache Type LDAP Search Timeout
f-any_CertRevoc-a-CrlCacheTypeLdapSearch: Determines how long to wait for CRL search results from the LDAP server.
a-CrlDpBackgroundDownloadEnabled-label: CRL Distribution Point Background Download Enabled
f-any_CertRevoc-a-CrlDpBackgroundDownloa: Determines whether the CRL Distribution Point background downloading, to automatically update the local CRL cache, is enabled.
f-any_CertRevocCa-a-CrlDpBackgroundDownl: For this CA, determines whether the CRL Distribution Point background downloading, to automatically update the local CRL cache, is enabled.
f-any_CertRevoc-a-CrlDpDownloadTimeout-h: Determines the overall timeout for the Distribution Point CRL download, expressed in seconds.
f-any_CertRevocCa-a-CrlDpDownloadTimeout: For this CA, determines the overall timeout for the Distribution Point CRL download, expressed in seconds.
f-any_CertRevoc-a-CrlDpEnabled-help: Determines whether the CRL Distribution Point processing to update the local CRL cache is enabled.
f-any_CertRevocCa-a-CrlDpEnabled-help: For this CA, determines whether the CRL Distribution Point processing to update the local CRL cache is enabled.
f-any_CertRevocCa-a-CrlDpUrl-help: For this CA, determines the CRL Distribution Point URL to use as failover or override for the URL found in the CRLDistributionPoints extension in the certificate.
f-any_CertRevocCa-a-CrlDpUrlUsage-help: For this CA, determines how getCrlDpUrl is used: as failover in case the URL in the certificate CRLDistributionPoints extension is invalid or not found, or as a value overriding the URL found in the certificate CRLDistributionPoints extension.
a-CrossDomainRecoveryRetryInterval-help: The interval at which a store lock for a given server in a recovery domain will be checked for takeover eligibility. Deprecated in 12.2.1.1.0.
f-SecurityConfiguration-a-CrossDomainSec: Specifies whether the Cross Domain Security subject cache is enabled.
Specifies the time-to-live (TTL), in seconds, of the Cross Domain Security subject cache. This value is used only if CrossDomainSecurityCacheEnabled is set to true.
Specifies whether cross-domain security is enabled.
a-CrossSiteRecoveryLeaseExpiration-help: The time in seconds after which a lease expires making it eligible for recovery by another site. Deprecated in 12.2.1.4.
a-CrossSiteRecoveryLeaseUpdate-help: The time in seconds in which to update a lease timestamp. Deprecated in 12.2.1.4.
a-CrossSiteRecoveryRetryInterval-help: The interval at which a lease for a given server in a recovery domain will be checked for takeover eligibility. Deprecated in 12.2.1.4.
f-WTCServer_WTCRemoteTuxDom-a-CustomAppK: The full pathname to the custom AppKey generator class. This class is only relevant if you specify Custom as the AppKey Generator. This class is loaded at runtime if the Custom AppKey generator plug-in is selected.
The optional parameters to be used by the custom AppKey class at the class initialization time. This class is only relevant if you specify Custom as the AppKey Generator Plug-in.
a-CustomClusterConfigurationFileLastUpda: Custom Cluster Configuration File Last Updated Timestamp
a-CustomClusterConfigurationFileName-hel: The name of the external custom Coherence operational configuration override file. The user must make sure the file exist and is located in either the WDT archive file or in the domain home under the config/coherence/$CoherenceClusterName directory
a-CustomConfigFileLastUpdatedTime-label: Custom Config File Last Updated Time
f-NMProperties-a-CustomIdentityAlias-hel: Specifies the alias when loading the private key into the keystore. This property is required when the Keystores property is set as CustomIdentityAndCustomTrust or CustomIdentityAndJavaStandardTrust.
a-CustomIdentityKeyStoreFileName-help: Specifies the source of the identity keystore. For a JKS or PKCS12 keystore, the source is the path and file name, which must be resolvable from directory in which the server was booted. For an Oracle KeyStore Service (KSS) keystore, the source is the KSS URI, which takes the form of kss://system/keystorename where keystorename is the name of the keystore registered in KSS.
f-NMProperties-a-CustomIdentityKeyStoreF: Specifies the file location and name of the identity keystore (meaning the keystore that contains the certificate and private key for the Node Manager). This property is required when the Keystores property is set as CustomIdentityAndCustomTrust or CustomIdentityAndJavaStandardTrust.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-CustomIdentit: Specifies the source of the identity keystore. For a JKS or PKCS12 keystore, the source is the path and file name, which must be resolvable from directory in which the server was booted. For an Oracle KeyStore Service (KSS) keystore, the source is the KSS URI, which takes the form of kss://system/keystorename where keystorename is the name of the keystore registered in KSS. The value in this attribute is only used if ServerMBean.KeyStores is CUSTOM_IDENTITY_AND_JAVA_STANDARD_TRUST, CUSTOM_IDENTITY_AND_CUSTOM_TRUST or CUSTOM_IDENTITY_AND_COMMAND_LINE_TRUST.
f-NMProperties-a-CustomIdentityKeyStoreP: Specifies the password defined when creating the Identity keystore. This field is optional or required depending on the type of keystore. All keystores require the passphrase to write to the keystore. However, some keystores do not require the passphrase to read from the keystore. Oracle WebLogic Server reads only from the keystore. So, whether or not you define this property depends on the requirements of the keystore.
a-CustomIdentityKeyStorePassPhraseEncryp: Specifies the custom identity keystore's passphrase. If empty or null, then the keystore will be opened without a passphrase.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-CustomIdentit: Specifies the custom identity keystore's passphrase. If empty or null, then the keystore will be opened without a passphrase. This attribute is only used if ServerMBean.KeyStores is CUSTOM_IDENTITY_AND_JAVA_STANDARD_TRUST, CUSTOM_IDENTITY_AND_CUSTOM_TRUST or CUSTOM_IDENTITY_AND_COMMAND_LINE_TRUST.
a-CustomIdentityKeyStoreType-help: Specifies the type of the keystore. Generally, this is JKS or PKCS12. If using the Oracle KeyStore Service, this is KSS. If empty or null, then the JDK's default keystore type (specified in java.security) is used.
f-NMProperties-a-CustomIdentityKeyStoreT: Specifies the type of the identity keystore. Generally, this is JKS or PKCS12. This property is optional. If not specified, the JDK default keystore type in the java.security file is used.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-CustomIdentit: Specifies the type of the keystore. Generally, this is JKS or PKCS12. If using the Oracle KeyStore Service, this is KSS. If empty or null, then the JDK's default keystore type (specified in java.security) is used. The custom identity keystore type is only used if ServerMBean.KeyStores is CUSTOM_IDENTITY_AND_JAVA_STANDARD_TRUST, CUSTOM_IDENTITY_AND_CUSTOM_TRUST or CUSTOM_IDENTITY_AND_COMMAND_LINE_TRUST.
f-NMProperties-a-CustomIdentityPrivateKe: Specifies the password used to retrieve the private key for Oracle WebLogic Server from the Identity keystore. This property is required when the Keystores property is set as CustomIdentityAndCustomTrust or CustomIdentityAndJavaStandardTrust.
a-CustomNotificationProperties-keyHelp: Specify a property name to add to the JSON object.
a-CustomNotificationProperties-valueHelp: Specify the property's value to add to the JSON object.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_WatchN: Allows customizing the JSON object delivered to the REST endpoint.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-CustomPrivate: The string alias used to store and retrieve the channel's private key in the keystore. This private key is associated with the server's digital certificate. A value of null indicates that the network channel uses the alias specified in the server's SSL configuration.

The passphrase used to retrieve the server's private key from the keystore. This passphrase is assigned to the private key when it is generated. A value of null indicates that the network channel uses the passphrase specified in the server's SSL configuration.
a-CustomTrustKeyStoreFileName-help: Specifies the source of the trust keystore. For a JKS or PKCS12 keystore, the source is the path and file name, which must be resolvable from directory in which the server was booted. For an Oracle KeyStore Service (KSS) keystore, the source is the KSS URI, which takes the form of kss://system/keystorename where keystorename is the name of the keystore registered in KSS.
a-CustomTrustKeyStorePassPhrase-help: Sets the custom trust keystore's passphrase. If empty or null, then the keystore will be opened without a passphrase.
a-CustomTrustKeyStoreType-help: The type of the keystore. Generally, this is JKS or PKCS12. If using the Oracle KeyStore Service, this is KSS.
a-DGCIdlePeriodsUntilTimeout-help: The number of idle periods allowed before the object is garbage collected. The default value is 5.
f-any_SingleSignOnServices-a-DataEncrypt: Specifies the preferred data encryption algorithm for SAML assertion encryption. This algorithm is used if it is found in the Service Provider's metadata or if the Service Partner's metadata does not include any data encryption algorithm.
f-any_ServerDiagnosticConfig-a-DataRetir: Controls if configuration-based data retirement functionality is enabled on the server. If disabled, all retirement policies will be disabled. The default value is true.
a-DataSource-help: The JDBC data source used by this JDBC store to access its backing table. The specified data source must use a non-XA JDBC driver since connection pools for XA JDBC drivers are not supported.
f-Cluster-a-DataSourceForAutomaticMigrat: Specifies the data source used by servers in the cluster during migration. (You must configure each Migratable Server within the cluster to use this data source.) This setting applies only if the MigrationBasis attribute is set to database.
f-Cluster-a-DataSourceForJobScheduler-he: Specifies the data source required to support persistence of jobs scheduled with the job scheduler.
f-Cluster-a-DataSourceForSessionPersiste: To support HTTP Session failover across data centers, a datasource is required to dump session state on disk.
a-DataSourceList-itemHelp: Specify a data source to add to the multi data source.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCDa: The list of data sources to which the multi data source will route connection requests. The order of data sources in the list determines the failover order.
f-any_CustomDBMSAuthenticator-a-DataSour: Specifies the name of the JDBC data source used for database access.
f-any_ReadOnlySQLAuthenticator-a-DataSou: Specifies the name of the JDBC data source used for database access.
f-any_SQLAuthenticator-a-DataSourceName-: Specifies the name of the JDBC data source used for database access.
a-DatabaseLeasingBasisConnectionRetryCou: Database Leasing Basis Connection Retry Count
f-Cluster-a-DatabaseLeasingBasisConnecti: Specifies the maximum number of times Database Leasing will try to obtain a valid connection from the Data Source. The default value is 1.
a-DatabaseLeasingBasisConnectionRetryDel: Database Leasing Basis Connection Retry Delay
f-Cluster-a-DatabaseLeasingBasisConnecti: Specifies the length of time, in milliseconds,Database Leasing will wait before attempting to obtain a new connection from the Data Source when a connection has failed. The default value is 1000.
a-DateFormatPattern-help: The date format pattern used for rendering dates in the log. The DateFormatPattern string conforms to the specification of the java.text.SimpleDateFormat class.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_WatchN: Indicates the day of the month for the schedule. Defaults to "*" (every day).
Indicates the day of the week for the schedule. Defaults to "*" (every day).
a-DbPassiveMode-help: Specifies whether the domain should enter database passive mode. Deprecated in 14.1.2. The default value is false.
a-DbPassiveModeGracePeriodSeconds-label: DB Passive Mode Grace Period Seconds
a-DbPassiveModeGracePeriodSeconds-help: Specifies the maximum amount of time, in seconds, that is allowed for in-progress work to complete before entering database passive mode. Deprecated in 14.1.2. The default value is 30.
f-Cluster-a-DeathDetectorHeartbeatPeriod: Sets the Server DeathDetector HeartbeatPeriod value in seconds. The DeathDetector monitor sends a heartbeat every period seconds to ascertain the health of a member. Members monitor this heartbeat in order to ascertain the health of the server hosting the DeathDetector. In this case, the ClusterMaster.
a-DebugBeanTreeHarvesterDataCollection-l: Debug Bean Tree Harvester Data Collection
a-DebugConcurrentMses-label: Debug Concurrent Managed Scheduled Executor Services
a-DebugDRSStateTransitions-label: Debug Data Replication Service State Transitions
a-DebugDRSUpdateStatus-label: Debug Data Replication Service Update Status
a-DebugDiagnosticsHarvesterTreeBeanPlugi: Debug Diagnostics Harvester Tree Bean Plug-in
a-DebugDiagnosticsMBeanElResolver-label: Debug Diagnostics MBean Expression Language Resolver
a-DebugDiagnosticsValueTracingElResolver: Debug Diagnostics Value Tracing Expression Language Resolver
a-DebugEjbMdbAqMessageRecovery-label: Debug EJB MDB AQ Message Recovery
a-DebugEmbeddedLDAPLogToConsole-label: Debug Embedded LDAP Log To Console
a-DebugEmbeddedLDAPWriteOverrideProps-la: Debug Embedded LDAP Write Override Props
f-any_NodeManager-a-DebugEnabled-help: Specifies whether communication with this Node Manager needs to be debugged. When enabled, connections to the NodeManager from the server or clients on the server will result in more information sent to the server log.
a-DebugJMSJDBCScavengeOnFlush-label: Debug JMS JDBC Scavenge On Flush
a-DebugJmscicHelper-label: Debug JMS Component Invocation Context Helper
a-DebugJtacdi-label: Debug JTA Contexts and Dependency Injection (CDI),
a-DebugMBeanTypeUtilQueuePriority-label: Debug MBean Type Utility Queue Priority
a-DebugMaskCriteria-itemHelp: Specify the dye mack criterion to add to the list.
a-DebugMaskCriteria-help: Dye mask criteria used to determine whether debug will be emitted for a request. Specifies the names of the Dye flags that will be inspected at runtime to determine whether debug needs to be emitted for a request.
a-DebugMessagingBridgeDumpToConsole-labe: Debug Messaging Bridge Dump To Console
a-DebugMessagingBridgeDumpToLog-label: Debug Messaging Bridge Dump To Log
a-DebugParameters-keyHelp: Specify name of the parameter to add to the list. The parameter name is prefixed with the name of the debug flag.
a-DebugParameters-help: Parameters for debug logging defined as name-value pairs. The parameters are prefixed with the name of the debug flag. The parameter names supported for a debug flag is specific to the implementation of the debug output.
a-DebugStoreRcm-label: Debug Store Replication and Consistency Manager (RCM)
a-DebugStoreRcmVerbose-label: Debug Store Replication and Consistency Manager (RCM) Verbose
a-DebugVerboseRcm-label: Debug Verbose Replication and Consistency Manager (RCM)
a-DebugXMLEntityCacheDebugLevel-label: Debug XML Entity Cache Debug Level
a-DebugXMLEntityCacheDebugName-label: Debug XML Entity Cache Debug Name
a-DebugXMLEntityCacheIncludeClass-label: Debug XML Entity Cache Include Class
a-DebugXMLEntityCacheIncludeLocation-lab: Debug XML Entity Cache Include Location
a-DebugXMLEntityCacheIncludeName-label: Debug XML Entity Cache Include Name
a-DebugXMLEntityCacheIncludeTime-label: Debug XML Entity Cache Include Time
a-DebugXMLEntityCacheOutputStream-label: Debug XML Entity Cache Output Stream
a-DebugXMLEntityCacheUseShortClass-label: Debug XML Entity Cache Use Short Class
a-DebugXMLRegistryUseShortClass-label: Debug XML Registry Use Short Class
a-DefaultAppKey-help: The default AppKey value to be used by the anonymous user and other users who are not defined in the user database if the plug-in allows them to access Tuxedo. Note that the TpUsrFile and LDAP plug-ins do not allow users that are not defined in user database to access Tuxedo unless Allow Anonymous is enabled.
a-DefaultCharCodeset-help: The standard character code set that this server will publish as its native code set. Older ORBs may have trouble interoperating with anything other than the default, which is US-ASCII.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Connecti: The number of bytes for the serialized message body so any message exceeds this limit will trigger message compression when the message is sent or received by the JMS message producer or consumer.
a-DefaultCredentialProviderStsuri-label: Default WS-Trust Credential Provider STS URL
f-WebserviceSecurity-a-DefaultCredential: Specifies the default STS endpoint URL for all WS-Trust enabled credential providers of this Web Service security configuration.
a-DefaultDatasource-help: The JNDI name of a system resource data source used to override the default datasource.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Connecti: The default delivery mode used for messages when a delivery mode is not explicitly defined.
a-DefaultIIOPPasswordEncrypted-help: Specifies the password for the default IIOP user.
a-DefaultIIOPUser-help: Specifies the user name of the default IIOP user.
a-DefaultInternalServletsDisabled-help: Specifies whether all default servlets in the servlet engine are disabled. This includes: weblogic.servlet.ClasspathServlet weblogic.servlet.utils.iiop.GetIORServlet weblogic.rjvm.http.TunnelSendServlet weblogic.rjvm.http.TunnelRecvServlet weblogic.rjvm.http.TunnelLoginServlet weblogic.rjvm.http.TunnelCloseServlet. If set to true, this property overrides the ClasspathServletDisabled property.
f-JPA-a-DefaultJPAProvider-help: The configured default JPA provider for the domain. The default value is org.eclipse.persistence.jpa.PersistenceProvider
f-Cluster-a-DefaultLoadAlgorithm-help: Defines the algorithm to be used for load-balancing between replicated services if none is specified for a particular service. The round-robin algorithm cycles through a list of WebLogic Server instances in order. Weight-based load balancing improves on the round-robin algorithm by taking into account a pre-assigned weight for each server. In random load balancing, requests are routed to servers at random.
a-DefaultLogicalStoreName-help: Specifies the name of the logical store to use, by default, for all web services persistent state in this server. The default value is "WseeStore".
a-DefaultMaximumObjectLifetime-help: Specifies the default max time an object can remain in the store. This can be overridden on individual objects placed in the store. The default value is "P1D" (1 day).
a-DefaultMinorVersion-help: The default GIOP (General Inter-ORB Protocol) version that this server will negotiate for incoming connections. You may have to modify the default to work with other vendor's ORBs. This attribute is useful for client orbs with broken GIOP 1.2 implementations. The default value is 2.
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource_Coheren: The default persistence mode.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Connecti: The default priority used for messages when a priority is not explicitly defined. All messages with a DefaultPriority of -1 that are produced on a connection created with this factory will receive this value.
a-DefaultProtocol-help: The protocol to use for connections when none is specified.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Connecti: The delay time, in milliseconds, before rolled back or recovered messages are redelivered. All messages consumed by a consumer created with this factory that have a DefaultRedeliveryDelay of -1 will use this value.
f-WTCServer_WTCtBridgeGlobal-a-DefaultRe: The reply delivery mode to associate with a message when placing messages onto the target location.
f-WSReliableDeliveryPolicy-a-DefaultRetr: The default maximum number of times that the sender runtime should attempt to redeliver a message that the receiver WebLogic Server has not yet acknowledged. The default maximum number of times that the sender should attempt to redeliver a message that the receiver WebLogic Web service has not yet acknowledged.
f-SAFAgent-a-DefaultRetryDelayBase-help: The amount of time, in milliseconds, between the original delivery attempt and the first retry. If RetryDelayMultiplier is set to 1, this defines the interval between any two successive retry attempts.
f-SAFAgent-a-DefaultRetryDelayMaximum-he: The maximum amount of time, in milliseconds, between two successive delivery retry attempts.
f-SAFAgent-a-DefaultRetryDelayMultiplier: The factor used to multiply the previous delay time to calculate the next delay time to be used.  The default value is 1.0
f-WSReliableDeliveryPolicy-a-DefaultRetr: The default minimum number of seconds that the sender runtime should wait between retries if the receiver does not send an acknowledgement of receiving the message, or if the sender runtime detects a communications error while attempting to send a message. The default minimum number of seconds that the sender should wait between retries if the receiver does not send an acknowledgement of receiving the message, or if the sender detects a communications error while attempting to send a message.
a-DefaultSecureProtocol-help: The protocol to use for secure connections when none is specified.
a-DefaultTGIOPPasswordEncrypted-help: The password for the default user associated with the Tuxedo GIOP (TGIOP) protocol. (Requires you to configure WebLogic Tuxedo Connector (WTC) for this server.)
a-DefaultTGIOPUser-help: The default user associated with the Tuxedo GIOP (TGIOP) protocol. (Requires you to configure WebLogic Tuxedo Connector (WTC) for this server.) Deprecated in 12.2.1.3.
a-DefaultTargetingEnabled-help: Specifies whether this JMS resource defaults to the parent module's targeting or uses the subdeployment targeting mechanism. When set to true, this resource implicitly inherits the targeting of its parent module. When set to false, this resource gets targeted based its subdeployment's targets, if one is specified.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Connecti: The delay time, in milliseconds, between when a message is produced and when it is made visible on its destination. All messages produced by a producer created with this factory that have a DefaultTimeToDeliver of -1 will use this value.
f-WSReliableDeliveryPolicy-a-DefaultTime: The default number of seconds that the receiver of the reliable message should persist the history of the reliable message in its store. The default minimum number of seconds that the receiver of the reliably sent message should persist the message in its storage. If the DefaultTimeToLive number of message have passed since the message was first sent, the sender should not resent a message with the same message id. If a sender cannot send a message successfully before the DefaultTimeToLive has passed, the sender should report a delivery failure. The receiver, after recovering from a crash, will not dispatch saved messages that have expired.
f-SAFAgent-a-DefaultTimeToLive-help: The default amount of time, in milliseconds, that the agent guarantees to reliably send messages. A value of 0 means the agent guarantees to reliably send messages for the duration of the conversation.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Connecti: The maximum length of time, in milliseconds, that a message exists. This value is used for messages when both the time-to-live is not explicitly set by the sender application that is using this connection factory and the time-to-live is not explicitly overridden by the destination's TimeToLiveOverride attribute . A value of 0 indicates that the message has an infinite amount time to live.
f-any_SAML2CredentialMapper-a-DefaultTim: Specifies the time in seconds that, by default, an assertion should remain valid. Default value is 120 seconds (2 minutes). If the value is zero, then assertions have an infinite lifetime. Using assertions with an infinite lifetime is not recommended, however.
f-any_SAMLCredentialMapperV2-a-DefaultTi: Specifies the time in seconds that, by default, an assertion should remain valid. Default value is 120 seconds (2 minutes). If the value is zero, then assertions have an infinite lifetime. Using assertions with an infinite lifetime is not recommended, however.
a-DefaultTimeToLiveDelta-help: Specifies a time factor you can use to allow the Credential Mapper to compensate for clock differences between the source and destination sites. The value is a positive or negative integer representing seconds. Normally, an assertion is valid from the NotBefore time, which defaults to (roughly) the time the assertion was generated, until the NotOnOrAfter time, which is calculated as (NotBefore + TimeToLive). This value is a positive or negative integer indicating how many seconds before or after "now" the assertions NotBefore should be set to. If you set a value for DefaultTimeToLiveDelta, then the assertion lifetime is still calculated as (NotBefore + TimeToLive), but the NotBefore value is set to (now + TimeToLiveDelta). So, an assertion might have a two minute (120 second) lifetime that starts thirty seconds ago, or starts one minute from now. This allows the Credential Mapper to compensate for clock differences between the source and destination sites. The default can be overridden for specific assertions.
a-DefaultTimeToLiveOffset-help: Specifies the time factor you can use to allow the Credential Mapper to compensate for clock differences between the Identity Provider and Service Provider sites. The value is a positive or negative integer representing seconds. Default value is -5. Normally, an assertion is valid from the NotBefore time, which defaults to (roughly) the time the assertion was generated, until the NotOnOrAfter time, which is calculated as (NotBefore + TimeToLive). This value is a positive or negative integer indicating how many seconds before or after "now" the assertions NotBefore should be set to. If you set a value for DefaultTimeToLiveOffset, then the assertion lifetime is still calculated as (NotBefore + TimeToLive), but the NotBefore value is set to (now + TimeToLiveOffset). So, an assertion might have a two minute (120 second) lifetime that starts thirty seconds ago, or starts one minute from now.
a-DefaultUnitOfOrder-help: Specifies whether WebLogic Server creates a system-generated unit-of-order name based on the domain, JMS server, and destination name. Any message arriving at this destination that does not already belong to a unit-of-order is assigned this default name.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Connecti: The default Unit-of-Order name for producers that connect using this connection factory. A Unit-of-Order allows for messages to be processed in a certain order, even among multiple recipients. System-generated indicates that WebLogic Server will automatically generate a Unit-of-Order name. User-Generated indicates that the Unit-of-Order name will come from the name specified name in the Unit-of-Order Name field. If None is selected, no message ordering is enforced.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Template: Specifies whether WebLogic Server creates a system-generated unit-of-order name based on the domain, JMS server, and destination name. Any message arriving at a destination using this template that does not already belong to a unit-of-order is assigned this default name.
f-any_SingleSignOnServices-a-DefaultUrl-: The Service Provider's default URL. When an unsolicited SSO response arrives at the Service Provider without an accompanying target URL, the user (if authenticated) is redirected to this default URL.
a-DefaultUserNameMapperAttributeDelimite: Default User Name Mapper Attribute Delimiter
f-any_DefaultIdentityAsserter-a-DefaultU: Specifies the delimiter that ends the attribute value when mapping from the X.509 certificate or X.500 name token to the WebLogic user name. The default value is "@".
a-DefaultUserNameMapperAttributeType-lab: Default User Name Mapper Attribute Type
f-any_DefaultIdentityAsserter-a-DefaultU: Specifies the name of the attribute from the subject DN to use when mapping from the X.509 certificate or X.500 name token to the WebLogic user name. The default value is "E".
a-DefaultWebAppContextRoot-help: Sets the context-root for the default Web application for this Web server. Alternatively, you can use the context-root attributes in application.xml or weblogic.xml to set a default Web application.
a-DefaultWideCharCodeset-help: The wide character code set that this server will publish as its native code set. Older ORBs may have trouble interoperating with anything other than the default, which is UCS-2.
f-any_Realm-a-DelegateMBeanAuthorization: Configures the WebLogic Server MBean servers to use the security realm's Authorization providers to determine whether a JMX client has permission to access an MBean attribute or invoke an MBean operation. You can continue to use WebLogic Server's default security settings or modify the defaults to suit your needs. If you do not delegate authorization to the realm's Authorization providers, the WebLogic MBean servers allow access only to the four default security roles (Admin, Deployer, Operator, and Monitor) and only as specified by WebLogic Server's default security settings.
a-DelegatedRequestConnectTimeoutMillis-h: Determines the connection timeout, in milliseconds, when the Management Services Web application propagates an idempotent REST request from the admin server to a managed server. If DelegatedRequestConnectTimeoutMillis is zero, then the default underlying JAX-RS client API connection timeout will be used.
a-DelegatedRequestMaxWaitMillis-help: Determines how long the Management Services Web application will wait, in milliseconds, when it propagates an idempotent REST request from the admin server to a managed server. If zero, then it will try to propagate the request once. If greater than zero, then it will retry the request until it finishes or until it detects that the time limit has been exceeded. A request can override this value by specifying the requestMaxWaitMillis query parameter.
a-DelegatedRequestMinThreads-help: Specifies the minimum number of threads that should be dedicated to the Management Services Web application when interacting with managed servers in parallel for improved responsiveness in large domains.
a-DelegatedRequestReadTimeoutMillis-help: Determines the read timeout, in milliseconds, when the Management Services Web application propagates an idempotent REST request from the admin server to a managed server. If DelegatedRequestReadTimeoutMillis is zero, then the default underlying JAX-RS client API read timeout will be used.
a-DeletesPerBatchMaximum-help: The maximum number of table rows that are deleted per database call. The default value is 20.
a-DeletesPerStatementMaximum-help: The maximum number of table rows that are deleted per database call. The default value is 20.
a-DeliveryMode-help: The delivery mode assigned to all messages that arrive at the destination regardless of the DeliveryMode specified by the message producer. A value of No-Delivery specifies that the DeliveryMode will not be overridden.
f-WTCServer_WTCtBridgeGlobal-a-DeliveryM: The delivery mode to use when placing messages onto the target location. If this value is not specified, the message is placed on the target location with the same delivery mode specified from the source location. Note that this value overrides any delivery mode associated with a message.
a-DeployBasePredicatesEnabled-help: Specifies whether to use the original predicates Grp, Usr to construct the role expressions during the application deployments.
f-any_Realm-a-DeployableProviderSynchron: Specifies whether synchronization for deployable Authorization and Role Mapping providers is enabled. The Authorization and Role Mapping providers may or may not support parallel security policy and role modification, respectively, in the security provider database. If the security providers do not support parallel modification, the WebLogic Security Framework enforces a synchronization mechanism that results in each application and module being placed in a queue and deployed sequentially.
The timeout value, in milliseconds, for the deployable security provider synchronization operation. This value is only used if DeployableProviderSynchronizationEnabled is set to true
f-any_CertificateIssuerPlugin-a-Deployme: The plugin deployment for this plugin configuration.
a-DeploymentOrder-help: A priority that the server uses to determine when it deploys an item. The priority is relative to other deployable items of the same type. Items with the lowest Deployment Order value are deployed first.
f-Application-a-DeploymentPrincipalName-: A string value that indicates the principal that should be used when deploying the file or archive during startup and shutdown. This principal will be used to set the current subject when calling out into application code for interfaces such as ApplicationLifecycleListener. If no principal name is specified, then the anonymous principal will be used.
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource-a-Deplo: A string value that indicates the principal that should be used when deploying the file or archive during startup and shutdown. This principal will be used to set the current subject when calling out into application code for interfaces such as ApplicationLifecycleListener. If no principal name is specified, then the anonymous principal will be used.
f-JDBCSystemResource-a-DeploymentPrincip: A string value that indicates the principal that should be used when deploying the file or archive during startup and shutdown. This principal will be used to set the current subject when calling out into application code for interfaces such as ApplicationLifecycleListener. If no principal name is specified, then the anonymous principal will be used.
f-JMSSystemResource-a-DeploymentPrincipa: A string value that indicates the principal that should be used when deploying the file or archive during startup and shutdown. This principal will be used to set the current subject when calling out into application code for interfaces such as ApplicationLifecycleListener. If no principal name is specified, then the anonymous principal will be used.
f-WLDFSystemResource-a-DeploymentPrincip: A string value that indicates the principal that should be used when deploying the file or archive during startup and shutdown. This principal will be used to set the current subject when calling out into application code for interfaces such as ApplicationLifecycleListener. If no principal name is specified, then the anonymous principal will be used.
f-WLDFSystemResource-a-Description-help: Optional short description of this WLDFSystemResource. If provided, the WebLogic Server Administration Console will display the resource description.
f-any_DefaultAuditor-a-Description-help: A short description of the WebLogic Auditing provider.
a-DescriptionsSupported-help: Specifies whether user and group descriptions are supported by the database used by the authentication provider.
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource-a-Descr: The name of the file that contains the module configuration. By default the file resides in the DOMAIN_DIR/config/coherence/bean_name directory. The module file derives its name from the bean name using the following pattern: <beanName>.xml. Note that this is a read-only property that can only be set when the bean is created.
f-JDBCSystemResource-a-DescriptorFileNam: The name of the file containing this configuration. This is a relative name rooted at DOMAIN_DIR/config. By default the file resides in the jdbc subdirectory and derives its name from the bean name using the following pattern: <beanName>.xml. Note that this is a read-only property that can only be set when the bean is created.
f-JMSSystemResource-a-DescriptorFileName: The name of the file that contains the module configuration. By default the file resides in the DOMAIN_DIR/config/jms directory. The module file derives its name from the bean name using the following pattern: <beanName>.xml. Note that this is a read-only property that can only be set when the bean is created.
f-WLDFSystemResource-a-DescriptorFileNam: The name of the descriptor file that contains the XML configuration information for this system-level resource. The location of this file is a relative path rooted at DOMAIN_DIR/config. By default the file resides in the DOMAIN_DIR/config/diagnostics directory, and derives its name from the bean name using the following pattern: <beanName>.xml. Note that the filename is a read-only property, which is set when the WLDF resource is created.
f-JMSBridgeDestination-a-DestinationJNDI: The destination JNDI name for this JMS bridge destination.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_WatchN: The JNDI name of the JMS destination.
a-DestinationKey-help: The list of potential destination keys for sorting the messages that arrive on a JMS destination. The keys are ordered from most significant to least significant. If more than one key is specified, a key based on the JMSMessageID can only be the last key in the list. Note: If JMSMessageID is not defined in the key, it is implicitly assumed to be the last key and is set as "Ascending" (FIFO) for the sort order.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Template: The list of potential destination keys for sorting messages that arrive on destinations that use this JMS template. The keys are ordered from most significant to least significant. If more than one key is specified, a key based on the JMSMessageID can only be the last key in the list. Note: If JMSMessageID is not defined in the key, it is implicitly assumed to be the last key and is set as "Ascending" (FIFO) for the sort order.
f-JMSBridgeDestination-a-DestinationType: The destination type (queue or topic) for this JMS bridge destination. The default value is Queue
a-Determiner-itemHelp: Select a transaction resource (determiner) to add to the list.
a-Determiner-help: Select a transaction resource (determiner) from the list of resources. For JMS, select WebLogic JMS as the determiner. When a determiner is configured, the determiner's in-doubt transaction records are used during transaction recovery.
a-DiagnosticContextCompatibilityModeEnab: Specifies whether WLDF sends a pre-12.2.1-style diagnostic context along with the current-style diagnostic context. If outbound communication to pre-12.2.1 servers is possible, this setting should always be enabled to ensure that those servers receive a diagnostic context that they can process. Disabling this setting in those scenarios can result in correlation information being lost across tiers, and in information reported by WLDF and DMS to become of sync in some situations. If there is no outbound communication to pre-12.2.1 servers possible, it is suggested to disable this mode as only the current-style diagnostic context is needed to be propagated outbound (propagating the old style will not cause a failure, but is unnecessary overhead in that situation). This setting affects outbound only, inbound pre-12.2.1 style diagnostic contexts are always understood and handled.
a-DiagnosticContextDebugMode-help: Specifies how context based debugging is enabled for the Server. The default behavior in the Off mode is that debug output is emitted for all requests. The DiagnosticContextDebugMode works in conjunction with the DebugMaskCriteria specified in the And or Or modes. For context based debugging the WLDF Instrumentation needs to be enabled and DyeInjection monitor needs to be configured for the Server. When the context debug mode is set to And mode, debug is emitted only for the requests that have all the bits in the WLDF dye vector set for the flags specified in the DebugMaskCriteria attribute. When the context debug mode is set to Or mode, debug is emitted only for the requests that have any one of the bits in the WLDF dye vector set for the flags specified in the DebugMaskCriteria attribute. The default value is off.
f-any_ServerDiagnosticConfig-a-Diagnosti: Determines whether the current server persists its harvested metrics and event data in a diagnostic store (file-based store) or a JDBC based archive. The default store is file-based.
Directory where heap and thread dumps will be generated by actions. This directory is a relative path with respect to the server directory. The default value is logs/diagnostic_dumps.
The JDBC data source that the server uses to archive its harvested metrics and event data.

The schema name to use for accessing JDBC-based archive tables. If multiple WLDF JDBC archive schemas exist in the same database, this value specifies the correct schema to use for accessing JDBC-based archive tables in that database. There is no default value. If a schema name is not specified, no schema name is applied when WLDF validates the run-time table or is used for the SQL statements.

The smallest addressable block, in bytes, of a file. When a native wlfileio driver is available and the block size has not been configured by the user, the store selects the minimum OS-specific value for unbuffered (direct) I/O, if it is within the range [512, 8192]. A file store's block size does not change once the file store creates its files. Changes to block size only take effect for new file stores or after the current files have been deleted. The default value is -1.
The directory in which the current server maintains its diagnostic store. The default value is data/store/diagnostics.

Determines whether OS file locking is used. When file locking protection is enabled, a store boot fails if another store instance already has opened the store files. Do not disable this setting unless you have procedures in place to prevent multiple store instances from opening the same file. File locking is not required but helps prevent corruption in the event that two same-named file store instances attempt to operate in the same directories. This setting applies to both primary and cache files. The default value is false.
The I/O buffer size, in bytes, automatically rounded down to the nearest power of 2, controls the largest write size.
The maximum file size, in bytes. Oracle recommends not setting the Diagnostic Store Max File Size above the default value of 1,342,177,280.
a-DiagnosticStoreMaxWindowBufferSize-lab: Diagnostic Store Max Window Buffer Size
f-any_ServerDiagnosticConfig-a-Diagnosti: The maximum amount of data, in bytes and rounded down to the nearest power of 2, mapped into the JVM's address space per diagnostic store file. Applies only when a native wlfileio library is loaded. The default value is 4194304.
a-DiagnosticStoreMinWindowBufferSize-lab: Diagnostic Store Min Window Buffer Size
f-any_ServerDiagnosticConfig-a-Diagnosti: The minimum amount of data, in bytes and rounded down to the nearest power of 2, mapped into the JVM's address space per diagnostic store file. Applies only when a native wlfileio library is loaded. The default value is -1.
f-any_DefaultIdentityAsserter-a-DigestDa: Specifies the name of the data source to use for storing digest values. These digest values are used to detect replay attacks.
f-any_DefaultIdentityAsserter-a-DigestEx: Specifies how long digests are valid. A digest that was created before the specified time will not be valid. This setting impacts how long previous digest values must be stored in the database for use in detecting replay attacks.
f-any_DefaultIdentityAsserter-a-DigestRe: Enables the storage of the digest nonce values used to detect replay attacks. If this setting is enabled, you must configure a data source to store the nonces for the specified expiration period. WebLogic Server then stores all the nonces from digest authentication attempts for all the machines in the domain. On each digest authentication attempt, the nonce is validated against the stored nonces. If the nonce is present, a replay attack has occurred and the digest authentication attempt fails.
f-WTCServer_WTCtBridgeRedirect-a-Directi: The direction of data flow. At least one redirection must be specified or the Tuxedo queuing bridge will fail to start and an error will be logged. Each defined direction is handled by starting a new thread.
f-FileStore-a-Directory-help: The path name to the file system directory where the file store maintains its data files.
f-any_DefaultFileStore-a-Directory-help: The path name to the file system directory where the file store maintains its data files.
a-DiscoveryAddress-help: Controls whether the discovery address is set. If this property is set, then Coherence will configure the discovery address to the unicast listen address if there is one.
f-ManagedExecutorServiceTemplate-a-Dispa: The name of the Work Manager to use for this Concurrent Managed Object (CMO). If a Work Manager is not specified, the default one is used.
f-ManagedScheduledExecutorServiceTemplat: The name of the Work Manager to use for this Concurrent Managed Object (CMO). If a Work Manager is not specified, the default one is used.
f-any_CertRevocCa-a-DistinguishedName-he: Determines the identity of this per-CA configuration using the distinguished name (defined in RFC 2253), which is used in certificates issued by the represented certificate authority. For example:"CN=CertGenCAB, OU=FOR TESTING ONLY, O=MyOrganization, L=MyTown, ST=MyState, C=US". This will be used to match this configuration to issued certificates requiring revocation checking.
a-DistributionPolicy-help: Specifies how the instances of a configured JMS artifact are named and distributed when cluster-targeted. A JMS artifact is cluster-targeted when its target is directly set to a cluster, or when it is scoped to a resource group and the resource group is in turn targeted to a cluster. When this setting is configured on a store, it applies to all JMS artifacts that reference the store. The default value is "Distributed".
f-XMLRegistry-a-DocumentBuilderFactory-h: The fully qualified name of the class that implements the DocumentBuilderFactory interface. The javax.xml.parsers.DocumentBuilderFactory factory API enables applications deployed to WebLogic Server to obtain an XML parser that produces DOM object trees from XML documents.
f-any_XMLParserSelectRegistryEntry-a-Doc: Specifies the fully qualified name of the class that implements the DocumentBuilderFactory API. When WebLogic Server begins to parse an XML document identified by either the public ID, system ID, or root element specified in this entry, and the applications specifies it wants a DOM parser, then WebLogic Server uses this implementation class when using the javax.xml.parsers.DocumentBuilderFactory to obtain the DOM parser.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-DomainKeystor: Specifies the alias of the client certificate for this NetworkAccessPoint when SSLMBean.KeyStores effective value is set to "DomainKeystores".
f-any_SSL-a-DomainKeystoresClientCertAli: Specifies the alias of the client certificate for this server when SSLMBean.KeyStores effective value is set to "DomainKeystores".
f-NMProperties-a-DomainKeystoresDomain-h: Specifies the domain name of the domain that hosts the machine keystores for this Node Manager instance. The domain name must match one of the domains in the nodemanager.domains file. Only set this property if KeyStores is set to DomainKeystores and this is a per-host (not per-domain) configuration.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-DomainKeystor: Specifies the alias of the server certificate for this NetworkAccessPoint when SSLMBean.KeyStores effective value is set to "DomainKeystores".
f-any_SSL-a-DomainKeystoresServerCertAli: Specifies the alias of the server certificate for this server when SSLMBean.KeyStores effective value is set to "DomainKeystores".
f-any_Log-a-DomainLogBroadcastFilter-hel: The filter configuration for log events being sent to the domain log.
f-any_Log-a-DomainLogBroadcastSeverity-h: The minimum severity of log messages going to the domain log from this server's log broadcaster. Messages with a lower severity than the specified value will not be published to the domain log.
f-any_Log-a-DomainLogBroadcasterBufferSi: Broadcasts log messages to the domain log in batch mode. The size of the buffer for log messages that are sent to the domain log. The buffer is maintained on the Managed Server and is broadcasted to the domain log when it is full. If you notice performance issues due to a high rate of log messages being generated, set this value higher. This will cause the buffer to be broadcasted less frequently from the Managed Server to the domain log. In production environments, it is not recommended to set the buffer size lower than the production default of 10.
f-JMX-a-DomainMBeanServerEnabled-help: Specifies whether the Administration Server initializes the Domain MBean Server, which provides federated access to all run-time MBeans and read-only configuration MBeans in the domain. Through it, JMX clients can access all MBeans in a domain through a single connection. The Administration Console and the WebLogic Scripting Tool use this MBean server for many (but not all) of their read operations. This MBean server exists only on the Administration Server. The Administration Server initializes it the first time a JMX client requests a connection to it. If you set this attribute to false, the Administration Server will not start this MBean server and JMX clients cannot connect to it.
f-NMProperties-a-DomainsDirRemoteSharing: Specifies whether Node Manager is monitoring a shared domain directory. As such, more than one Node Manager may be monitoring the shared directory from different machines. Set to true to indicate that you have a shared domain directory (mounted directory or Windows NFS) that multiple nodes will be sharing. Enabling this property allows multiple Node Managers to share the domain without affecting each other.
f-NMProperties-a-DomainsFile-help: The path to the node manager's nodemanager.domains file. This property is only relevant for a per-host node manager configuration.
f-NMProperties-a-DomainsFileEnabled-help: If set to true, use the file specified in DomainsFile. If false, assumes the domain of the current directory or of WL_HOME. This property is only relevant for a per-host node manager configuration.
f-SecurityConfiguration-a-DowngradeUntru: Whether or not to downgrade to anonymous principals that cannot be verified. This is useful for server-server communication between untrusted domains.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: Specifies the absolute name of the application class used to intercept method calls to the JDBC driver. The application specified must implement the weblogic.jdbc.extensions.DriverInterceptor interface.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCDr: The full package name of JDBC driver class used to create the physical database connections in the connection pool in the data source.
f-MessagingBridge-a-DurabilityEnabled-he: Specifies whether or not the messaging bridge allows durable messages. When enabled and the source destination is a JMS topic, a messaging bridge instance uses a durable subscription to ensure that no messages are lost in the event of a failure. DurabilityEnabled ignored if the source destination is a JMS queue.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_Instru: Specifies whether dye filtering is enabled for the diagnostic actions associated with this monitor.
The dye mask for all diagnostic actions associated with this monitor.
f-Cluster_DynamicServers-a-DynamicCluste: Specifies the cool-off period (in seconds) used by the Elasticity Framework while performing scale up or scale down operations. If a scale up or scale down operation was performed, subsequent requests for scale up or down operations will be ignored by the Elasticity Framework during this period.
a-DynamicClusterServerGroupTargetingLimi: Dynamic Cluster Server Group Targeting Limit
The name of the server group
Dynamic Cluster Server Group Targeting Limits
The targets for the server group
A map of template-defined dynamic server groups to targets used to target FMW Infrastructure resources to dynamic clusters.
f-Cluster_DynamicServers-a-DynamicCluste: Specifies the timeout period (in seconds) used by the Elasticity Framework while gracefully shutting down a server. If the server does not shut down before the specified timeout period, the server will be forcibly shut down. With a negative time value, no timeout will be applied.

Specifies the current size of the dynamic cluster (the number of dynamic server instances allowed to be created). The specified number of server instances are dynamically created as ServerMBeans at runtime and associated ServerLifeCycleRuntimeMBeans are created.
a-DynamicGroupNameAttribute-help: Specifies the attribute of a dynamic LDAP group object that specifies the name of the group.
a-DynamicGroupObjectClass-help: Specifies the LDAP object class that stores dynamic groups.
a-DynamicMemberUrlAttribute-help: Specifies the attribute of the dynamic LDAP group object that specifies the URLs of the members of the dynamic group.
f-WTCServer_WTCExport-a-EJBName-help: The complete name of the EJB home interface to use when invoking a service. If not specified, the default interface used is tuxedo.services.servicenameHome. For example: If the service being invoked is TOUPPER and EJBName attribute is not specified, the home interface looked up in JNDI would be tuxedo.services.TOUPPERHome.
a-ELFFields-help: Specifies the list of fields specified for the extended logging format for access.log. The default value is "date time cs-method cs-uri sc-status".
a-EagerThreadLocalCleanup-help: Specifies whether to clean up all ThreadLocals storage from self-tuning thread pool threads after they have finished processing each work request. By default, the self-tuning thread pool only cleans up ThreadLocal storage in its threads after an application is undeployed to avoid ClassLoader memory leak. The default value is false.
a-EagerTrackingOfResourceMetricsEnabled-: Eager Tracking Of Resource Metrics Enabled
f-JMX-a-EditMBeanServerEnabled-help: Specifies whether the Administration Server initializes the Edit MBean Server, which contains the hierarchy of MBeans used to make modifications to the domain's configuration. All JMX clients, including utilities such as the Administration Console and the WebLogic Scripting Tool, use the Edit MBean Server to modify a domain's configuration. This MBean server exists only on the Administration Server. By default, when the Administration Server starts, it starts the Edit MBean Server. If you set the EditMBeanServerEnabled attribute to false, the Administration Server will not start this MBean server. If you disable this MBean server, JMX clients cannot modify the domain's configuration. You can, however, modify the domain configuration through the offline editing feature of WebLogic Scripting Tool.
