f-any_ActiveDirectoryAuthenticator-a-Ena: Specifies whether to enable cache statistics if LDAP Server Cache and Group Membership Lookup Hierarchy Cache are enabled. If true, the number of the cache entries, queries and hits will be recorded.
f-any_IPlanetAuthenticator-a-EnableCache: Specifies whether to enable cache statistics if LDAP Server Cache and Group Membership Lookup Hierarchy Cache are enabled. If true, the number of the cache entries, queries and hits will be recorded.
f-any_LDAPAuthenticator-a-EnableCacheSta: Specifies whether to enable cache statistics if LDAP Server Cache and Group Membership Lookup Hierarchy Cache are enabled. If true, the number of the cache entries, queries and hits will be recorded.
f-any_NovellAuthenticator-a-EnableCacheS: Specifies whether to enable cache statistics if LDAP Server Cache and Group Membership Lookup Hierarchy Cache are enabled. If true, the number of the cache entries, queries and hits will be recorded.
f-any_OpenLDAPAuthenticator-a-EnableCach: Specifies whether to enable cache statistics if LDAP Server Cache and Group Membership Lookup Hierarchy Cache are enabled. If true, the number of the cache entries, queries and hits will be recorded.
f-any_OracleInternetDirectoryAuthenticat: Specifies whether to enable cache statistics if LDAP Server Cache and Group Membership Lookup Hierarchy Cache are enabled. If true, the number of the cache entries, queries and hits will be recorded.
f-any_OracleUnifiedDirectoryAuthenticato: Specifies whether to enable cache statistics if LDAP Server Cache and Group Membership Lookup Hierarchy Cache are enabled. If true, the number of the cache entries, queries and hits will be recorded.
f-any_OracleVirtualDirectoryAuthenticato: Specifies whether to enable cache statistics if LDAP Server Cache and Group Membership Lookup Hierarchy Cache are enabled. If true, the number of the cache entries, queries and hits will be recorded.
a-EnableEeCompliantClassloadingForEmbedd: Enable EE-Compliant Classloading For Embedded Adapters

Specifies the class loading behavior for embedded adapters. If you enable this option, embedded adapters in the domain will use Jakarta EE compliant class loading. The embedded adapter's classes will be accessible from other modules in the same application.
a-EnableGroupMembershipLookupHierarchyCa: Enable Group Membership Lookup Hierarchy Caching

Specifies whether to cache group membership hierarchies found during recursive membership lookup. If true, each subtree found will be cached. This overwrites the default value defined in GroupMembershipHierarchyCacheMBean.
a-EnableIORServlet-help: Enables the getior servlet used to publish COS Naming Service IORs. The default value is false.
a-EnableJMSStoreDBPersistence-help: Whether to enable JMS JDBC stores when creating a new FMW Infrastructure domain.
a-EnableJTATLogDBPersistence-help: Whether to enable JTA JDBC stores when creating a new FMW Infrastructure domain.
f-any_ActiveDirectoryAuthenticator-a-Ena: Specifies whether SID to group name lookup results are cached or not. This is only used if the token group membership lookup algorithm is enabled.
f-any_Realm-a-EnableWebLogicPrincipalVal: Specifies whether the WebLogic Principal Validator caching is enabled. The Principal Validator is used by Oracle supplied authentication providers and may be used by custom authentication providers. If enabled, the default principal validator will cache WebLogic Principal signatures.
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource_Coheren: Specifies whether custom Coherence logging is enabled.
f-SNMPAgent-a-Enabled-help: Specifies whether this SNMP agent is enabled.
f-SnmpAgentDeployment-a-Enabled-help: Specifies whether this SNMP agent is enabled.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_Harves: Specifies whether this type is enabled. Note that enabling a type will have no effect unless the Harvester component is also enabled. A true value means that this type is harvested. A false value indicates that that this type is not harvested.
Specifies whether the Harvester component is enabled. If true, all types that are both configured and enabled are harvested. If false, nothing is harvested.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_Instru: Specifies whether the monitor and its associated diagnostics actions are enabled.

The state of the instrumentation behavior for the server or application. If false, there will no weaving (inserting of diagnostic code) in the application or server code during class loading. In addition, if woven classes are already loaded, disabling instrumentation will disable all the monitors in this scope.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_WatchN: Specifies whether this action is enabled.
Specifies whether this action is enabled.
Specifies whether this action is enabled.
Specifies whether this action is enabled.
Specifies whether this action is enabled.
Specifies whether this action is enabled.
Specifies whether this action is enabled.
Specifies whether this action is enabled.
Specifies whether this action is enabled.
Specifies whether this action is enabled.
Specifies whether this action is enabled.
Specifies whether this action is enabled.
Specifies whether this action is enabled.

Specifies whether the policy and action component is enabled. If true (the default), all configured policies are activated, incoming data or events are evaluated against the policies, and actions are generated when policy conditions are met. If false, all policies are rendered inactive.
f-any_CertificateIssuerPlugin-a-Enabled-: Whether this plugin configuration is enabled or not.
f-any_CertificateManagement-a-Enabled-he: Specified whether the Certificate Management Service is enabled or not.
f-any_HealthScore-a-Enabled-help: Specifies whether the health score service is enabled.
f-RestfulManagementServices-a-Enabled-he: Enables the monitoring of this WebLogic Server domain through the Restful Management Services Web application.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-Enabled-help: Specifies whether this channel should be started.
f-any_SSL-a-Enabled-help: Indicates whether the server can be reached through the default SSL listen port.
f-any_TransactionLogJDBCStore-a-Enabled-: When true, TLOGs are logged to a TLOG JDBC Store; otherwise, TLOGs are logged to the server's default store. The default value is false.
f-any_WebServiceRequestBufferingQueue-a-: A boolean flag indicating whether request buffering is enabled. Defaults to false.
f-any_WebServiceResponseBufferingQueue-a: A boolean flag indicating whether response buffering is enabled. Defaults to false.
a-EnabledServer-itemHelp: Add a server to the list.
a-EnabledServer-help: This attribute is applicable only when the SNMP Agent is running on the Admin Server of a WebLogic Domain. The EnabledServers attribute allows the users to limit the scope of the monitored data sources to the specific named Servers. The EnabledServers list is ignored when the SNMAgentDeploymentMBean is targeted to a Managed Server. In the case of a Managed Server the SNMP Agent only looks at the data available in the WebLogic Server where the SNMP Agent is deployed. For traps based on MBean attributes the SNMP Agent refers to the Domain Runtime MBean Server when it is running on the Admin Server and the Runtime MBean Server when it is deployed to a Managed Server.
f-any_ConfigurationProperty-a-EncryptVal: Specifies whether the property should be encrypted. By default, the value of a property is not encrypted and anyone using the Administration Console can view the value of the property. If this attribute is set to true, then the value of the property on the Administration Console will be set to all asterisks.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCDr: The value of the encrypted property value.
f-any_DefaultAuditor-a-EndMarker-help: The marker that indicates the end of the audit record.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_WatchN: The REST endpoint URL which will be invoked with the action payload.
f-SecurityConfiguration-a-EnforceStrictU: Whether or not the system should enforce strict URL pattern.
f-SecurityConfiguration-a-EnforceValidBa: Whether or not the system should allow requests with invalid Basic Authentication credentials to access unsecure resources.
f-any_SingleSignOnServices-a-EntityId-he: The string that uniquely identifies the local site.
a-EntityURI-help: The location of the external entity, either a pathname or URI. The location of the external entity can be either a pathname relative to the XML Registry directories, reachable by the Administration Server, or a URI of the entity location in some local repository.
a-Environment-keyHelp: Specify the name of the environment variable to add.
a-Environment-valueHelp: Specify the environment variable's value to add.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_WatchN: A map of environment variables to set for the child process.
f-any_DefaultAuditor-a-ErrorAuditSeverit: If the Severity value is set to Custom, causes the Auditing provider to generate audit records for events with a severity level of ERROR.
a-ErrorDestination-help: The name of the target error destination for messages that have expired or reached their redelivery limit. If no error destination is configured, then such messages are simply dropped. If a message has expired or reached its redelivery limit, and the Expiration Policy is set to Redirect, then the message is moved to the specified Error Destination. For standalone destinations, an error destination must be another standalone destination that is targeted to the same JMS server as the destinations for which the error destination is defined. For uniform distributed destinations (UDDs), the error destination must be another UDD that shares the same subdeployment (i.e., targets) as the current UDD.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Template: The name of the error destination that should be used for members who have the same SubDeploymentName. If this value is not set then the value from the templates DeliveryFailureParamsBean will be used if it is set.
f-any_ServerDiagnosticConfig-a-EventPers: The interval, in milliseconds, at which queued up instrumentation events will be periodically dispatched to the archive. The default value is 5000.
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource_Coheren: The events directory for the default persistence environment used to store durable events. If no value is specified, the directory which will be used is the coherence/events sub-directory under Domain Home directory.
f-any_ServerDiagnosticConfig-a-EventsIma: The time span, in milliseconds, for which recently archived events will be captured in the diagnostic image. All events archived on or after (System.currentTimeMillis() - interval) will be captured. The default value is 60000.
a-ExactlyOnceLoadBalancingPolicy-help: Controls the load balancing behavior when the SAF service forwards messages to a distributed destination with the Exactly-Once quality of service (QOS).
a-ExalogicOptimizationsEnabled-help: Specifies whether optimizations for Oracle Exalogic should be enabled. Optimizations include improved thread management and request processing, and reduced lock contention. This attribute should be enabled only when configuring a WebLogic domain for Oracle Exalogic.
a-Exclude-itemHelp: Specify a pattern expression for classes to exclude.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_Instru: Pattern expressions for classes that will be excluded for this instrumentation monitor. If specified, classes matching given patterns will not be instrumented with this monitor.
Pattern expressions for classes that will be excluded from this instrumentation scope. If specified, classes matching given patterns will not be instrumented.
a-ExcludedCiphersuite-itemHelp: Specifies an excluded cipher suite to add to the list.
a-ExcludedCiphersuite-help: Specifies the list of cipher suites not to be used by WebLogic Server.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-ExcludedCiphe: Specifies the list of cipher suites not to be used with this channel.
f-any_SSL-a-ExcludedCiphersuite-help: Specifies the list of cipher suites not to be used with this server.
a-ExcludedDomainName-itemHelp: Specify a remote domain to exclude from cross-domain checks.
f-SecurityConfiguration-a-ExcludedDomain: Specifies a list of remote domains for which cross-domain check should not be applied.
a-ExpirationLoggingPolicy-help: The policy that defines what information about the message is logged when the Expiration Policy is set to Log. When specifying multiple values, enter them as a comma-separated list. The %header% and %properties% values are not case sensitive. For example, you could use "%header%,%properties%" for all the JMS header fields and user properties. However, the enumeration of individual JMS header fields and user-defined properties are case sensitive. To enumerate only individual JMS header fields you could use "%header, name, address, city, state, zip". Note: The JMSMessageID field is always logged and cannot be turned off. Therefore, if the Expiration Logging Policy is not defined (i.e., null) or is defined as an empty string, then the output to the log file contains only the JMSMessageID of the message.
a-ExpirationPolicy-help: The message Expiration Policy to use when an expired message is encountered on a destination. It is illegal to use the Redirect policy when there is no valid error destination defined for the destination. Similarly, it is illegal to remove the error destination for a destination that is using the Redirect policy. Note: The Maximum Message quota is only enforced for sending new messages. It is ignored when moving messages because of the Redirect policy.
f-JMSServer-a-ExpirationScanInterval-hel: The number of seconds between this JMS server's cycles of scanning local destinations for expired messages. A value of 0 disables active scanning. A very large scan interval effectively disables active scanning. With scanning disabled, users still do not receive expired messages and any expired messages that are discovered by other system activities are removed. However, expired messages sitting in idle destinations (such as an inactive queue or disconnected durable subscriber) are not removed and continue to consume system resources.
f-any_SSL-a-ExportKeyLifespan-help: Indicates the number of times WebLogic Server can use an exportable key between a domestic server and an exportable client before generating a new key. The more secure you want WebLogic Server to be, the fewer times the key should be used before generating a new key. The default value is 500.
a-Expression-help: The EntitleNet expression of the role. For example, "?weblogic.entitlement.rules.AdministrativeGroup(AppMonitors)" identifies the "AppMonitors" group.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_WatchN: Returns the expression language type used by the policy, either "EL" or "WLDF" (deprecated).
a-ExternalDNSName-help: Specifies the external IP address or DNS name for this server. This address will be sent with HTTP session cookies and with dynamic server lists to HTTP proxies. It will also be used by external application clients to enable the propagation of RMI traffic through network address translating (NAT) firewalls. You must specify an external DNS name for configurations in which a firewall is performing network address translation, unless clients are accessing WebLogic Server using t3 and the default channel. For example, define the external DNS name for configurations in which a firewall is performing network address translation, and clients are accessing WebLogic Server using HTTP via a proxy plug-in.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-ExternalDNSNa: Specifies the external DNS name for the current channel, which will be sent with the session cookies and also with the dynamic server lists to the proxies. This will be required for the configurations in which you have firewall doing network address translations. A value of null indicates that this value is inherited from the server.
a-ExtraEjbcOptions-help: The extra options passed to ejbc during the dynamic ejbc of a jar file. For example: -J-mx128m By default this value is null. If no ExtraEJBCOptions are specified on the EJBComponent, the default will be pulled from the Server.ExtraEJBCOptions.
a-ExtraRmicOptions-help: The extra options passed to rmic during server-side generation are noted here. The default for this attribute must be null. If no ExtraRmicOptions are specified on the EJBComponent, the default will be pulled from Server.ExtraRmicOptions.
f-any_CertRevoc-a-FailOnUnknownRevocStat: Determines whether certificate path checking should fail, if revocation status could not be determined.
f-any_CertRevocCa-a-FailOnUnknownRevocSt: For this CA, determines whether certificate path checking should fail, if revocation status could not be determined.
a-FailOverLimit-help: Specify a limit for the number of cluster-targeted JMS artifact instances that can fail over to a particular JVM. This can be used to prevent too many instances from starting on a server, avoiding a system failure when starting too few servers of a formerly large cluster. A typical limit value should allow all instances to run in the smallest desired cluster size, which means (smallest-cluster-size * (limit + 1)) should equal or exceed the total number of instances. A value of -1 means there is no fail over limit (unlimited). A value of 0 prevents any fail overs of cluster-targeted JMS artifact instances, so no more than 1 instance will run per server (this is an instance that has not failed over). A value of 1 allows one fail-over instance on each server, so no more than two instances will run per server (one failed over instance plus an instance that has not failed over). The default value is -1.
a-FailbackDelaySeconds-help: Specifies the amount of time, in seconds, to delay before failing a cluster-targeted JMS artifact instance back to its preferred server after the preferred server failed and was restarted. This delay allows time for the system to stabilize and dependent services to be restarted, preventing a system failure during a reboot. A value > 0 specifies the time, in seconds, to delay before failing a JMS artifact back to its user preferred server. A value of 0 indicates that the instance would never failback. A value of -1 indicates that there is no delay and the instance would failback immediately.
a-FailoverAddress-itemHelp: Specify an address for a failover Jolt Server Listener (JSL).
f-JoltConnectionPool-a-FailoverAddress-h: The list of Jolt Server Listeners (JSLs) addresses that is used if the connection pool cannot establish connections to the Primary Addresses, or if the primary connections fail. The format of each address is: //hostname:port. Multiple addresses should be separated by commas. These JSLs need not reside on the same host as the primary JSLs.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCDa: For multi data sources with the failover algorithm, enables the multi data source to failover connection requests to the next data source if all connections in the current data source are in use.
a-FailureAction-help: Enable automatic force shutdown of the server on failed state. The server self-health monitoring detects fatal failures and mark the server as failed. The server can be restarted using NodeManager or a HA agent.
f-any_DefaultAuditor-a-FailureAuditSever: If the Severity value is set to Custom, causes the Auditing provider to generate audit records for events with a severity level of FAILURE.
f-StartupClass-a-FailureIsFatal-help: Specifies whether a failure in this startup class prevents the targeted server(s) from starting. If you specify that failure is not fatal, if the startup class fails, the server continues its startup process.
f-SelfTuning_FairShareRequestClass-a-Fai: Fair share value between 1 and 1000. The default value is 50.
f-SelfTuning_WorkManager-a-FairShareRequ: The name of the FairShareRequestClass that defines the fair share value to use for this request class. One of the components of work managers is a request class that indicates the proportional of the total server thread use time this request class gets. The default fair share value is 50.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCOr: Enables the data source to subscribe to and process Oracle FAN (Fast Application Notification) events. This attribute is only applicable for RAC configurations that publish FAN notification events using the ONS protocol.
a-FannedOutRequestMaxWaitMillis-label: Fanned Out Request Max Wait Millis
a-FannedOutRequestMaxWaitMillis-help: Determines how long the Management Services Web application will wait, in milliseconds, when it fans out an idempotent REST request from the admin server to all the managed servers. If zero, then it will choose an appropriate timeout. A request can override this value by specifying the requestMaxWaitMillis query parameter.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: Specifies a comma-separated list of error codes that are treated as fatal errors. These errors include deployment errors that cause a server to fail to boot and connection errors that prevent a connection from being put back in the connection pool. This optional attribute is used to define fatal error codes, that when specified as the exception code within a SQLException (retrieved by sqlException.getErrorCode()), indicate that a fatal error has occurred and the connection is no longer usable
f-WTCServer_WTCRemoteTuxDom-a-Federation: The context at which this remote Tuxedo access point federates to a foreign name service. If omitted, the default federation point is tuxedo.domains.
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource_Coheren: The federation topology to use.
f-WTCServer_WTCRemoteTuxDom-a-Federation: The URL for a foreign name service that is federated into JNDI. Note that the WebLogic Tuxedo Connector can federate to non-CORBA service providers. If this value is not specified, the WebLogic Tuxedo Connector assumes there is a CosNaming server in the foreign domain and federates to the CosNaming server using TGIOP.
f-Cluster_DatabaseLessLeasingBasis-a-Fen: The timeout, in seconds, to wait and retry getting the server state when the NodeManager is unreachable. We try once more after waiting for the fence timeout period to make sure that the machine is really unavailable as opposed to heavy disk swapping. The default value is 5.
f-Cluster-a-FencingGracePeriodMillis-hel: During automatic migration, if the Cluster Master determines a server to be dead, it waits for this period of time (in milliseconds) before the Cluster Master migrates the service to another server in the cluster.
f-any_DefaultAuditor-a-FieldPrefix-help: The prefix character that indicates the beginning of a field in the audit record.
f-any_DefaultAuditor-a-FieldSuffix-help: The suffix character that indicates the end of a field in the audit record.
a-FileCount-help: The maximum number of log files that the server creates when it rotates the log. This number does not include the file that the server uses to store current messages. The default value is 7.
f-FileStore-a-FileLockingEnabled-help: Determines whether OS file locking is used. When file locking protection is enabled, a store boot fails if another store instance already has opened the store files. Do not disable this setting unless you have procedures in place to prevent multiple store instances from opening the same file. File locking is not required but helps prevent corruption in the event that two same-named file store instances attempt to operate in the same directories. This setting applies to both primary and cache files.
f-any_DefaultFileStore-a-FileLockingEnab: Determines whether OS file locking is used. When file locking protection is enabled, a store boot fails if another store instance already has opened the store files. Do not disable this setting unless you have procedures in place to prevent multiple store instances from opening the same file. File locking is not required but helps prevent corruption in the event that two same-named file store instances attempt to operate in the same directories. This setting applies to both primary and cache files.
a-FileMinSize-help: The size (1 - 2097150 kilobytes) that triggers the server to move log messages to a separate file. The default is 500 kilobytes. After the log file reaches the specified minimum size, the next time the server checks the file size, it will rename the current log file as SERVER_NAME.lognnnnn and create a new one to store subsequent messages. The default value is 500.
f-JMSServer_JmsMessageLogFile-a-FileName: The name of the file that stores current JMS server log messages. Usually it is a computed value based on the name of the parent of this MBean. For example, for a JMS server log, it is jmsserverName.log. However, if the name of the parent cannot be obtained, the file name is weblogic.log. If you specify a relative pathname, it is interpreted as relative to the server's root directory.
f-SAFAgent_JmssafMessageLogFile-a-FileNa: The name of the file that stores current SAF agent log messages.
f-any_Log-a-FileName-help: The name of the file that stores domain log messages. Usually it is a computed value based on the name of the parent of this MBean. For example, for a domain log, it is DOMAIN_NAME.log. However, if the name of the parent cannot be obtained, the file name is weblogic.log. If you specify a relative pathname, it is interpreted as relative to the server's root directory. To include a time and date stamp in the file name when the log file is rotated, add java.text.SimpleDateFormat variables to the file name. Surround each variable with percentage (%) characters. For example, if the file name is defined to be mydomain_%yyyy%_%MM%_%dd%_%hh%_%mm%.log, the log file will be named mydomain_yyyy_mm_dd_hh_mm.log. When the log file is rotated, the rotated file name contains the date stamp. For example, if the log file is rotated for the first time on 2 April, 2003 at 10:05 AM, the log file that contains the old messages will be named mydomain_2003_04_02_10_05.log00001. If you do not include a time and date stamp, the rotated log files are numbered in order of creation. For example, mydomain.log00007.
f-any_DataSourceLogFile-a-FileName-help: The name of the file that stores datasource profile records. Usually it is a computed value based on the name of the parent of this MBean. For example, for a datasource profile log, it is serverName.log.
f-any_WebServerLog-a-FileName-help: The name of the log file that stores HTTP log entries.
a-FileTimeSpan-help: The interval (in hours) at which the server saves old log messages to another file. The default value is 24.
a-FileTimeSpanFactor-help: This factor is defined so that log rotation can be tested at a different frequency. The default value is 3600000.
f-WebAppContainer-a-FilterDispatchedRequ: Indicates whether or not to apply filters to dispatched requests. This is a backward compatibility flag. Until version 8.1, WebLogic Server applied ServletFilters (if configured for the web application) on request dispatches (and includes/forwards). Servlet 2.4 has introduced the "Dispatcher" element to make this behavior explicit. The default value is Dispatcher=REQUEST. In order to be compliant with the Java EE specification, the default value for FilterDispatchedRequestsEnabled is false beginning with WebLogic Server 9.0. Note that if you are using old descriptors (meaning web.xml does not have version=2.4), then WebLogic Server automatically uses FilterDispatchedRequestsEnabled = true for the web applications, unless filter-dispatched-requests-enabled is explicitly set to false in weblogic.xml. This means that old applications will work fine without any modification. Additionally, during migration of old domains to the 9.0 domain, the migration plug-in automatically sets this flag to true.
f-LogFilter-a-FilterExpression-help: The filter expression to be evaluated for qualifying log messages. The filter expression is specified as a string in the query language. The query language supports Boolean operators: AND, OR, and NOT, and relational operators. You can use the following column names (message attributes) in a query to filter data going to a log destination: RECORDID, DATE, SEVERITY, SUBSYSTEM, MACHINE, SERVER, THREAD, USERID, TXID, CONTEXTID, TIMESTAMP, MSGID, and MESSAGE.
a-FldTbl16Class-itemHelp: Specifies the name of a FldTbl16Class to add to the FldTbl array.
a-FldTbl16Class-help: The names of FldTbl16Classes that are loaded via a class loader and added to a FldTbl array. Use the fully-qualified class names.  Use a comma to separate multiple entries.
a-FldTbl32Class-itemHelp: Specifies the name of a FldTbl32Class to add to the FldTbl array.
a-FldTbl32Class-help: The names of FldTbl32Classes that are loaded via a class loader and added to a FldTbl array. Use the fully-qualified class names.  Use a comma to separate multiple entries.
a-FlowControlEnabled-help: Specifies whether a producer created using a connection factory allows flow control. If true, the associated message producers will be slowed down if a JMS server or a destination reaches its specified upper byte or message threshold.
a-FlowInterval-help: The adjustment period of time, in seconds, when a producer adjusts its flow from the FlowMaximum number of messages to the FlowMinimum amount, or vice versa. When a producer is flow controlled, it is slowed down from its FlowMaximum to its FlowMinimum over the specified FlowInterval amount of seconds.
a-FlowMaximum-help: The maximum number of messages-per-second allowed for a producer that is experiencing a threshold condition. When a producer is flow controlled it will never be allowed to go faster than the FlowMaximum messages per second. If a producer is not currently limiting its flow when a threshold condition is reached, the initial flow limit for that producer is set to FlowMaximum. If a producer is already limiting its flow when a threshold condition is reached (the flow limit is less than FlowMaximum), then the producer will continue at its current flow limit until the next time the flow is evaluated.
a-FlowMinimum-help: The minimum number of messages-per-second allowed for a producer that is experiencing a threshold condition. This is the lower boundary of a producer's flow limit. That is, WebLogic JMS will not further slow down a producer whose message flow limit is at its FlowMinimum. When a producer is flow controlled it will never be required to go slower than FlowMinimum messages per second.
a-FlowSteps-help: The number of steps used when a producer is adjusting its flow from the Flow Maximum amount of messages to the Flow Minimum amount, or vice versa. Specifically, the Flow Interval adjustment period is divided into the number of Flow Steps (for example, 60 seconds divided by 6 steps is 10 seconds per step).
a-FollowReferrals-help: Specifies whether referrals will automatically be followed within the LDAP Directory. If set to false, then a Referral exception will be thrown when referrals are encountered during LDAP requests.
f-any_SingleSignOnServices-a-ForceAuthn-: Specifies whether the Identity Provider must authenticate users directly and not use a previous security context. The default is false.
a-ForceGCEachDGCPeriod-label: Force GC Each Distributed GC Period
a-ForceShutdownTimeoutNumOfThreadDump-la: Force Shutdown Timeout Number of Thread Dumps
a-ForceShutdownTimeoutNumOfThreadDump-he: Sets total number of obtained thread dump when ServerLifeCycleTimeoutVal is reached. The default value is 0.
a-ForceShutdownTimeoutThreadDumpInterval: Force Shutdown Timeout Thread Dump Interval
Sets interval time, in milliseconds, of thread dump capturing when ServerLifeCycleTimeoutVal is reached. The default value is 60000.
a-ForgetHeuristics-help: Specifies whether the transaction manager automatically performs an XA Resource forget operation for heuristic transaction completions. When enabled, the transaction manager automatically performs an XA Resource forget() operation for all resources as soon as the transaction learns of a heuristic outcome. Disable this feature only if you know what to do with the resource when it reports a heuristic decision.
f-WebAppContainer-a-FormAuthXFrameOption: Returns the X-Frame-Options header value (DENY, SAMEORIGIN, or ALLOW-FROM uri) that will be set in the responses for all requests to the "j_security_check" endpoint when using FORM authentication.
a-ForwardDelay-help: The number of seconds after which a uniform distributed queue member with no consumers will wait before forwarding its messages to other uniform distributed queue members that do have consumers. The default value of -1 disables this feature so that no messages are forwarded to other uniform distributed queue members. Note: This attribute is ignored by standalone/singleton Queues, it only applies to distributed queues.
f-SAFAgent-a-ForwardingPausedAtStartup-h: Specifies whether the agent is paused for forwarding messages at the startup time. When enabled, the sending agent forwards messages. Otherwise, the sending agent does not forward any messages. If the value is changed and activated, you need to restart any servers to which the MBean is targeted before the value will take effect.
a-ForwardingPolicy-help: The uniform distributed topic message Forwarding Policy specifies whether a sent message is forwarded to all members. Note: This attribute is ignored by standalone/singleton Topics, it only applies to distributed topics.
f-WebAppContainer_Http2Config-a-FrameCou: The frame count limit reset interval.
a-FreeMemoryPercentHighThreshold-help: Percentage free memory after which the server overload condition is cleared. WorkManagers stop performing overloadActions and start regular execution once the overload condition is cleared.
a-FreeMemoryPercentLowThreshold-help: Percentage free memory below which the server is considered overloaded. WorkManagers perform overloadAction once the server is marked as overloaded.
a-FrontendHTTPPort-help: Specifies the name of the HTTP port to which all redirected URLs will be sent. Ensures that the webapp will always have the correct PORT information, even when the request is coming through a firewall or a proxy. If this parameter is configured, the HOST header will be ignored and the information in this parameter will be used in its place.
a-FrontendHTTPSPort-help: Specifies the name of the secure HTTP port to which all redirected URLs will be sent. Ensures that the webapp will always have the correct PORT information, even when the request is coming through a firewall or a proxy. If this parameter is configured, the HOST header will be ignored and the information in this parameter will be used in its place.
a-FrontendHost-help: The name of the host to which all redirected URLs will be sent. Ensures that the webapp will always have the correct HOST information, even when the request is coming through a firewall or a proxy. If this parameter is configured, the HOST header will be ignored and the information in this parameter will be used in its place, when constructing the absolute urls for redirects.
a-GatheredWritesEnabled-help: Enables gathered writes over NIO socket channels. Enabling this attribute increases efficiency during I/O in environments with high network throughput and should be used only when configuring a WebLogic domain for Oracle Exalogic. The default value is false.
a-GenerateAttributes-help: Specifies whether to generate <AttributeStatement> in the assertion for this partner. If true, the default implementation will generate group information as an <AttributeStatement> in the assertion if there is any.
a-GlobalSocketProvider-help: Specify the Global Socket Provider name. If not specified and secured production mode is enabled, Coherence uses WebLogic SSL configuration as Global Socket Provider. Otherwise, use the specified Global Socket Provider. Prior to 14.1.2, this parameter is expected to be a boolean instead of a string so make sure to enter "true" or "false" for the value.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCDa: Determines the transaction protocol (global transaction processing behavior) for the data source.
f-SelfTuning_ResponseTimeRequestClass-a-: A response time goal in milliseconds. You can either define a response time goal or keep the -1 default value, which acts as a placeholder for the response time goal. By doing so, you have not defined the response time goal at run time but can define one later.
a-GracefulShutdownTimeout-help: Number of seconds a graceful shutdown operation waits before forcing a shut down. A graceful shutdown gives WebLogic Server subsystems time to complete certain application processing currently in progress. If subsystems are unable to complete processing within the number of seconds that you specify here, then the server will force shutdown automatically. A value of 0 means that the server will wait indefinitely for graceful shutdown to complete. The graceful shutdown timeout applies only to graceful shutdown operations. The default value is 0.
a-GracefulShutdownTimeoutNumOfThreadDump: Graceful Shutdown Timeout Number Of Thread Dumps
Sets total number of obtained thread dump when GracefulShutdownTimeout is reached. The default value is 0.
a-GracefulShutdownTimeoutThreadDumpInter: Graceful Shutdown Timeout Thread Dump Interval
Sets interval time, in milliseconds, of thread dump capturing when GracefulShutdownTimeout is reached. The default value is 60000.
f-Cluster-a-GreedySessionFlushInterval-h: Specifies the interval in seconds until HTTP Sessions are periodically flushed to secondary server.
a-GroupBaseDN-help: Specifies the attribute of an LDAP user object that specifies the Distinguished Names (DNs) of dynamic groups to which the user belongs.
a-GroupFromNameFilter-help: Specifies the LDAP search filter for finding a group given the name of the group. If the attribute is not specified (that is, if the attribute is null or empty), a default search filter is created based on the group schema.
a-GroupFromUserFilterForMemberuid-label: Group From User Filter For Member UID
a-GroupFromUserFilterForMemberuid-help: This field is used when the UseMemberuidForGroupSearch field is checked. This LDAP search filter describes how to search groups for a user given the username.
a-GroupHierarchyCacheTTL-help: Specifies the maximum number of seconds a group membership hierarchy entry is valid in the LRU cache. The default value is 60.
a-GroupMembershipSearching-help: Specifies whether group searches into nested groups are unlimited, limited or off. For configurations that use only the first level of nested group hierarchy, this attribute allows improved performance during user searches by turning off the group search or limiting the group search level. If a limited search is specified, the Max Group Membership Search Level attribute must be specified. If an unlimited search is specified, the Max Group Membership Search Level attribute is ignored. If an off is specified, the Max Group Membership Search Level attribute is ignored. Note that when Use Token Groups For Group Membership Lookup is used during authentication, all the groups are returned in a single call, and the recursion limits and depth limits do not apply. They will apply in management operations.
f-any_CustomDBMSAuthenticator-a-GroupMem: Specifies whether recursive group membership searching is unlimited or limited.
f-any_ReadOnlySQLAuthenticator-a-GroupMe: Specifies whether recursive group membership searching is unlimited or limited.
f-any_SQLAuthenticator-a-GroupMembership: Specifies whether recursive group membership searching is unlimited or limited.
f-SelfTuning_ContextRequestClass_Context: The name of the user group whose requests are to be processed by the request class with the name specified in RequestClassName.
a-GroupSearchScope-help: Specifies how deep in the LDAP directory tree to search for groups. The default value is subtree.
a-GroupsTokenClaim-help: Specifies the token attribute used to get groups from the token. The default value is "groups".
a-GuidAttribute-help: Specifies the name of the GUID attribute defined in the Active Directory LDAP server. The default value is objectguid.
a-GzipCompressionContentType-itemHelp: Specifies a MIME type to include in compression.
f-WebAppContainer_GzipCompression-a-Gzip: The list of content MIME types to be included in compression.
This global property determines whether or not the container should provide GZIP compression.
The minimum content length to trigger GZIP compression. This allows you to bypass small-sized resources where compression does not yield a great return and uses unnecessary CPU.
f-XMLRegistry-a-HandleEntityInvalidation: Whether cached DTD/schema is invalidated when parsing error is encountered. The default value is false.
f-any_XMLEntitySpecRegistryEntry-a-Handl: Whether cached DTD/schema is invalidated when parsing error is encountered. The default value is defer to registry setting.
a-Handlers-itemHelp: Add a handler to the list.
a-Handlers-help: Specifies the list of handlers associated with the logger.
a-HandlingOrder-help: Specifies the order in which the token handlers execute on a given token. If you do not specify an order, it is determined by the order in which you added the token handlers.
a-HangDetectionMaxTestWaitSeconds-label: Hang Detection Max Test Wait Seconds
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: The amount of time to wait for connection tests to complete before the connection pool determines that a connection test is hung. Setting the value to 0 disables the hang detection feature.
a-HarvestedAttribute-itemHelp: Specify an attribute to add to the harvested attributes list.
a-HarvestedAttribute-help: The harvested attributes for this type. If a list of attributes is provided, only those attributes are harvested; otherwise all harvestable attributes are harvested.
a-HarvestedInstance-itemHelp: Specify a harvested instance name. The name must be a valid JMX ObjectName or an ObjectName pattern.
a-HarvestedInstance-help: The harvested instances of this type. The configuration of a type can optionally provide a set of identifiers for specific instances. If this list is provided, only the provided instances are harvested; otherwise all instances of the type are harvested. The identifier for an instance must be a valid JMX ObjectName or an ObjectName pattern.
f-WebAppContainer_Http2Config-a-HeaderTa: The server's maximum size of the header compression table used to decode header blocks, in octets.
f-Cluster-a-HealthCheckIntervalMillis-he: Specifies the interval in milliseconds at which Migratable Servers and Cluster Masters prove their liveness via the database.
a-HealthCheckIntervalSeconds-help: The number of seconds that defines the frequency of this server's self-health monitoring. The server monitors the health of it's subsystems every HealthCheckIntervalSeconds and changes the Server's overall state if required. The default value is 180.
f-Cluster-a-HealthCheckPeriodsUntilFenci: Specifies the maximum number of periods that a cluster member will wait before timing out a Cluster Master and also the maximum number of periods the Cluster Master will wait before timing out a Migratable Server.
a-HealthCheckStartDelaySeconds-help: The number of seconds the Node Manager should wait before starting to monitor the server.
a-HeapDumpingOnDeadlock-help: Specifies whether to perform a heap dump when a thread deadlock is detected. The default value is false.
a-HeapDumpingOnMaxStuckThread-label: Heap Dump On Max Stuck Threads
a-HeapDumpingOnMaxStuckThread-help: Specifies whether to perform a heap dump when the server detects that the number of stuck threads reaches StructThreadCount. The default value is false.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: The maximum number of connection requests that can concurrently block threads while waiting to reserve a connection from the data source's connection pool.
f-Callout-a-HookPoint-help: Specifies the hookpoint to which the callout is bound.
f-any_SNMPTrapDestination-a-Host-help: The DNS name or IP address of the computer on which the SNMP manager is running. The WebLogic SNMP agent sends trap notifications to the host and port that you specify.
f-any_ActiveDirectoryAuthenticator-a-Hos: Specifies the host name or IP address of the LDAP server.
f-any_IPlanetAuthenticator-a-Host-help: Specifies the host name or IP address of the LDAP server.
f-any_LDAPAuthenticator-a-Host-help: Specifies the host name or IP address of the LDAP server.
f-any_LDAPX509IdentityAsserter-a-Host-he: Specifies the host name or IP address of the LDAP server.
f-any_NovellAuthenticator-a-Host-help: Specifies the host name or IP address of the LDAP server.
f-any_OpenLDAPAuthenticator-a-Host-help: Specifies the host name or IP address of the LDAP server.
f-any_OracleInternetDirectoryAuthenticat: Specifies the host name or IP address of the LDAP server.
f-any_OracleUnifiedDirectoryAuthenticato: Specifies the host name or IP address of the LDAP server.
f-any_OracleVirtualDirectoryAuthenticato: Specifies the host name or IP address of the LDAP server.
f-any_weblogic.security.providers.authen: Specifies the host name used to connect to the Oracle Identity Cloud Service. The default value is localhost.
f-JMSServer-a-HostingTemporaryDestinatio: Specifies whether this JMS server can be used to host temporary destinations.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-HostnameVerif: Specifies whether to ignore the installed implementation of the weblogic.security.SSL.HostnameVerifier interface when this server is acting as a client to another application server.
f-any_SSL-a-HostnameVerificationIgnored-: Specifies whether to ignore the installed implementation of the weblogic.security.SSL.HostnameVerifier interface (when this server is acting as a client to another application server). The default value is false.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-HostnameVerif: The name of the class that implements the weblogic.security.SSL.HostnameVerifier interface. This class verifies whether the connection to the host with the hostname from URL should be allowed. The class is used to prevent man-in-the-middle attacks. The weblogic.security.SSL.HostnameVerifier has a verify() method that WebLogic Server calls on the client during the SSL handshake.
f-any_SSL-a-HostnameVerifier-help: The name of the class that implements the weblogic.security.SSL.HostnameVerifier interface. This class verifies whether the connection to the host with the hostname from URL should be allowed. The class is used to prevent man-in-the-middle attacks. The weblogic.security.SSL.HostnameVerifier has a verify() method that WebLogic Server calls on the client during the SSL handshake.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_WatchN: Indicates the hour(s) of the day for the schedule. Defaults to "*" (every hour).
The HTTP authentication mode when invoking the REST endpoint URL.
The HTTP authentication password when the REST endpoint is secured.
The HTTP authentication user name when the REST endpoint is secured.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-HttpEnabledFo: Specifies whether HTTP traffic should be allowed over this network channel. HTTP is generally required by binary protocols for downloading stubs and other resources. The default value is true.
f-Cluster-a-HttpPingRetryCount-help: Set the number of HTTP pings to execute before declaring a server unreachable. This comes into effect only when MaxServerCountForHTTPPing is greater than zero.
a-HttpTraceSupportEnabled-help: Attackers may abuse HTTP TRACE functionality to gain access to information in HTTP headers such as cookies and authentication data. In the presence of other cross-domain vulnerabilities in web browsers, sensitive header information could be read from any domains that support the HTTP TRACE method. This attribute is for disabling HTTP TRACE support. The default value is false.
a-HttpdEnabled-help: Whether HTTP support is enabled on the regular port or SSL port. The default value is true.
a-HttpsKeepAliveSecs-help: The amount of time, in seconds, this server waits before closing an inactive HTTPS connection.
a-IIOPEnabled-help: Specifies whether this server has IIOP support enabled for both the regular (non-SSL) and SSL ports. The default value is true.
f-any_SSL-a-IdentityAndTrustLocations-he: Indicates where SSL should find the server's identity (certificate and private key) as well as the server's trust (trusted CAs). The default value is "KeyStores".
f-any_Realm-a-IdentityAssertionCacheEnab: Specifies whether the Identity Assertion cache is enabled.
f-any_Realm-a-IdentityAssertionCacheTtl-: The time-to-live (TTL), in seconds, of the Identity Assertion cache. This value is used only if IdentityAssertionCacheEnabled is set to true.
a-IdentityAssertionDoNotCacheContextElem: Identity Assertion Do Not Cache Context Elements
Identity Assertion Do Not Cache Context Element
Specifies the ContextElement name to not store in the Identity Assertion cache.
f-any_Realm-a-IdentityAssertionDoNotCach: Specifies the names of the ContextElements that are not stored in the Identity Assertion cache because these elements are present in the ContextHandler of the requests. This value is used only if IdentityAssertionCacheEnabled is set to true.
a-IdentityAssertionHeaderNamePrecedence-: Specifies a token type name  used for Identity Assertion with HTTP request headers.
f-any_Realm-a-IdentityAssertionHeaderNam: Specifies an ordered list of token type names used for Identity Assertion with HTTP request headers. The list determines the precedence order when multiple HTTP headers are present in an HTTP request based on the list of active token types maintained on the configured Authentication providers.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: Enables identity-based-connection-pooling for the data source. When an application requests a database connection, WebLogic Server picks or creates a physical connection with requested DBMS identity based on a map of WebLogic user IDs and database IDs. You must also specify the map of WebLogic Server user IDs to database user IDs (credential mapping).
a-IdentityDomain-help: Specifies the name of the identity domain.
f-SecurityConfiguration-a-IdentityDomain: Specifies whether the identity domain values should be defaulted for the Administrative Identity Domain, Partition Primary Identity Domain, and Default Authenticator Identity Domain attributes.

Specifies whether all role mapping, authorization, credential mapping, and audit providers configured in the domain must support the IdentityDomainAwareProviderMBean interface's administrative identity domain.
a-IdentityDomains-itemHelp: Specifies an identity domain to add to the provider list.
a-IdentityDomains-help: Sets the identity domains that the provider supports. This overwrites the default value defined in MultiIdentityDomainAuthenticatorMBean.
f-WTCServer_WTCLocalTuxDom-a-IdentityKey: The path and file name of the identity keystore. The path name must either be absolute or relative to where the server was booted. The identity keystore file name is only used if KeystoreLocation is "Custom Stores".
The custom identity keystore passphrase. If empty or null, then the keystore will be opened without a passphrase. This attribute is only used if KeyStores is "Custom Stores".
f-any_SingleSignOnServices-a-IdentityPro: Specifies whether the Artifact binding is enabled for the Identity Provider. The default value is true.
Specifies whether the local site is enabled for the Identity Provider role. The default value is false.
Specifies whether the POST binding is enabled for the Identity Provider. The default value is true.
Specifies the preferred binding type for endpoints of the Identity Provider services. The default value is "None".
Specifies whether the Redirect binding is enabled for the Identity Provider. The default value is true.
a-IdleConnectionTimeout-help: The maximum number of seconds that a connection is allowed to be idle before it is closed by the server. The T3 and T3S protocols ignore this attribute. If you configure network channels for this server, each channel can override this idle connection message timeout. This timeout helps guard against server deadlock through too many open connections. The default value is 65.
f-Cluster-a-IdlePeriodsUntilTimeout-help: Specifies the maximum number of periods that a cluster member will wait before timing out a member of a cluster. The default value is 3.
f-Server-a-IdlePeriodsUntilTimeout-help: The number of idle periods until a peer is considered unreachable. The default value is 4.
f-ServerTemplate-a-IdlePeriodsUntilTimeo: The number of idle periods until a peer is considered unreachable. The default value is 4.
f-MessagingBridge-a-IdleTimeMaximum-help: The maximum amount of time, in seconds, that a messaging bridge instance remains idle. In asynchronous mode, this is the longest amount of time a messaging bridge instance stays idle before it checks the sanity of its connection to the source. In synchronous mode, this is the amount of time the messaging bridge can block on a receive call if no transaction is involved.
a-IgnoreDuplicateMembership-help: Specifies whether duplicate members are ignored when adding groups. The attribute cycles in the Group membership.
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource_Coheren: Check if ignore hostname verification is set. In Secured Production Mode, Coherence hostname verification is enabled by default. If WebLogic isHostnameVerificationIgnored is set, then Coherence will inherit it through this property. The default value is false.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: Enables the data source to be shutdown even if connections obtained from the pool are still in use.
a-IgnoreSessionsDuringShutdown-help: Indicates whether a graceful shutdown operation drops all HTTP sessions immediately. If this is set to false, a graceful shutdown operation waits for HTTP sessions to complete or timeout. The default value is false.
f-Cluster_DynamicServers-a-IgnoreSession: Indicates if the Elasticity Framework should ignore inflight HTTP sessions while shutting down servers.
f-SelfTuning_WorkManager-a-IgnoreStuckTh: Specifies whether this Work Manager ignores "stuck" threads. Typically, stuck threads will cause the associated Work Manager to take some action: either switching the application to Admin mode, shutting down the server, or shutting down the Work Manager. If this flag is set, then no thread in this Work Manager is ever considered stuck.
f-any_ServerDiagnosticConfig-a-ImageDir-: The default directory where the server stores captured diagnostic images. If you specify a relative pathname, the root of that path is the server's root directory. If the directory does not exist, it will be created when the WebLogic Diagnostic Framework is initialized on the server. Note that each image capture request can override this default directory location.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_WatchN: The directory where diagnostic images are stored. The default directory, relative to a server's root directory, is ./logs/diagnostic_images.
The length of time, in minutes, during which no diagnostic images requests will be accepted; that is, the minimum amount of time between image capture requests.
f-any_ServerDiagnosticConfig-a-ImageTime: The default timeout period, in minutes, that the server uses to delay future diagnostic image-capture requests. The default value is 1.
f-CdiContainer-a-ImplicitBeanDiscoveryEn: Specifies whether to limit implicit bean discovery.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: The number of inactive seconds on a reserved connection before WebLogic Server reclaims the connection and releases it back into the connection pool. You can use the Inactive Connection Timeout feature to reclaim leaked connections - connections that were not explicitly closed by the application. Note that this feature is not intended to be used in place of properly closing connections. When set to 0, the feature is disabled.
a-InactivityTimeout-help: If during this duration, an endpoint (RM source or RM destination) has received no application or control messages, the endpoint MAY consider the RM Sequence to have been terminated due to inactivity. String value in "Duration" format. Defaults to "P0DT600S" (600 seconds). Implementations of RM source and RM destination are free to manage resources associated with the sequence as they please, but in general, there are no guarantees that the sequence will be usable by either party after the inactivity timeout expires. Set at sequence creation time, and cannot be reset.
a-InboundCertificateValidation-help: Indicates the client certificate validation rules for inbound SSL. This attribute only applies to ports and network channels using 2-way SSL.
a-Include-itemHelp: Specify a pattern expression for classes to include.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_Instru: Pattern expressions for classes that are included for this instrumentation monitor. If specified, only included classes will be instrumented with this monitor. If not specified, all classes loaded within the application and which are not explicitly excluded are eligible for instrumentation with this monitor. A pattern can end with an asterisk (*), in which case it will match with all classes whose fully qualified classname starts with the prefix of the pattern. For example, weblogic.rmi.* will match with all classes in weblogic.rmi and its subpackages.

Pattern expressions for classes that are included in this instrumentation scope. If specified, only included classes will be instrumented. If not specified, all classes loaded within the application and which are not explicitly excluded are eligible for instrumentation. A pattern can end with an asterisk (*), in which case it will match with all classes whose fully qualified classname starts with the prefix of the pattern. For example, weblogic.rmi.* will match with all classes in weblogic.rmi and its subpackages.
f-any_CertificateManagement-a-IncludeRoo: Whether the Domain Certificates Issuer should include the self-signed root CA in the certificate chain for a generated certificate.
f-SAFAgent-a-IncomingPausedAtStartup-hel: Specifies whether the agent is paused for incoming messages at startup time. When enabled, the sending agent accepts new messages. Otherwise, the sending agent does not accept any new messages. If the value is changed and activated, you need to restart any servers to which the MBean is targeted before the value will take effect.
a-IncompleteWorkExpirationTime-help: Specifies the maximum length of time, in milliseconds, before undelivered messages in an incomplete UOW are expired. Such messages will then follow the expiration policy defined for undeliverable messages. Note: An error destination for UOW messages cannot be configured with a Unit-of-Work Handling Policy of Single Message Delivery value. This attribute is effective only if the Unit-of-Work Handling Policy is set to Single Message Delivery value. A value of -1 means that UOW messages will never expire.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Template: Specifies the maximum amount of time, in milliseconds, before undelivered messages in an incomplete UOW are expired. Such messages will then follow the template's expiration policy defined for undeliverable messages. Note: A template's error destination for UOW messages cannot be configured to use the Single Message Delivery value.
a-InformEnabled-help: Configures this SNMP agent to send notifications as an INFORM instead of a TRAP. Requires you to specify the agent's SNMPTrapVersion as SNMPv2 or SNMPv3. When an agent sends an INFORM notification, it waits for a confirmation response from the SNMP manager. If it does not receive a response, it resends the INFORM notification.
a-InformRetryInterval-help: The number of milliseconds that this SNMP agent will wait for a response to an INFORM notification. If the agent does not receive a response within the specified interval, it will resend the notification.
f-any_DefaultAuditor-a-InformationAuditS: If the Severity value is set to Custom, causes the Auditing provider to generate audit records for events with a severity level of INFORMATION.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: SQL statement to execute that will initialize newly created physical database connections. Start the statement with SQL followed by a space. If the Init SQL value begins with "SQL ", then the rest of the string following that leading token will be taken as a literal SQL statement that will be used to initialize database connections. If the Init SQL value does not begin with "SQL ", the value will be treated as the name of a table and the following SQL statement will be used to initialize connections: "select count(*) from InitSQL"
a-InitialBootDelaySeconds-help: Specifies the amount of time, in seconds, to delay before starting a cluster-targeted JMS instance on a newly booted WebLogic Server instance. When this setting is configured on a store, it applies to all JMS artifacts that reference the store. This allows time for the system to stabilize and dependent services to be restarted, preventing a system failure during a reboot. A value > 0 is the time, in seconds, to delay before before loading resources after a failure and restart. A value of 0 specifies no delay. The default value is 60.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: The number of physical connections to create when creating the connection pool in the data source. If unable to create this number of connections, creation of the data source will fail.
f-JMSBridgeDestination-a-InitialContextF: The initial context factory class name for this JMS bridge destination. The default value is weblogic.jndi.WLInitialContextFactory.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_ForeignS: The name of the class that must be instantiated to access the JNDI provider. This class name depends on the JNDI provider and the vendor that are being used. This value corresponds to the standard JNDI property, java.naming.factory.initial. Note: This value defaults to weblogic.jndi.WLInitialContextFactory, which is the correct value for WebLogic Server.
f-ForeignJNDIProvider-a-InitialContextFa: The initial context factory to use to connect. This class name depends on the JNDI provider and the vendor you are using. The value corresponds to the standard JNDI property, java.naming.factory.initial.
f-FileStore-a-InitialSize-help: The initial file size, in bytes.
f-any_DefaultFileStore-a-InitialSize-hel: The initial file size, in bytes.
f-WebAppContainer_Http2Config-a-InitialW: The server's initial window size (in octets) for stream-level flow control. This setting affects the window size of all streams.
a-InsertionPausedAtStartup-help: Specifies whether new message insertion is paused on a destination at startup.
f-JMSServer-a-InsertionPausedAtStartup-h: Indicates whether insertion is paused at startup on destinations targeted to this JMS server. A destination cannot receive any new messages while it is paused. When the value is set to true, then immediately after the host server instance is booted, then this JMS server and its targeted destinations are modified such that they are in a "insertion paused" state, which results preventing messages that are result of the "in-flight" work completion to arrive on those destinations.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Template: Specifies whether new message insertion is paused on destinations that use this template at server startup.
a-InsertsPerBatchMaximum-help: The maximum number of table rows that are inserted per database call. The default value is 20.
f-Application-a-InstallDir-help: The path to the application's install-root directory, relative to the domain/config/deployments directory. When the installation directory is specified, SourcePath, PlanDir, and PlanPath are derived from this path and need not be specified. The default value for this is the name of the deployment.
a-InstalledSoftwareVersion-help: Installed software version that can be used for rolling updates of config changes.
a-InstrumentStackTraceEnabled-help: Specifies whether the server returns stack traces for RMI calls that generate exceptions. With RMI stack tracking enabled, if a client issues an RMI call to a server subsystem or to a module running within the server, and if the subsystem or module generates an exception that includes a stack trace, the server will return the exception as well as the stack trace. With it disabled, the server will return the exception without the stack trace details. The default value  is true.
a-InterClusterCommLinkHealthCheckInterva: Inter-Cluster Communication Link Health Check Interval
f-Cluster-a-InterClusterCommLinkHealthCh: If the cluster link between two clusters goes down, a trigger will run periodically to see if the link is restored. The duration is specified in milliseconds and the default value is 30000.
f-NMProperties-a-Interface-help: The primary interface names used by migratable servers. For server migration, the primary interface names used by migratable servers must be the same. See the <InterfaceName> property for more flexibility specifying multiple interfaces and a corresponding range of IP addresses that should be bound to a specific interface.
a-InterfaceAddress-help: The IP address of the NIC that this server should use for multicast traffic.
f-NMProperties-a-InterfaceName-help: An interface name along with a corresponding range of IP addresses and optional netmask value that should be bound to this specific network interface when migratable servers are started. Syntax: <InterfaceName>=<IP_RANGE_MIN>-<IP_RANGE_MAX>,(optional) NetMask=<NETMASK_ADDRESS>
a-InternalAppsDeployOnDemandEnabled-labe: Internal Apps Deploy On Demand Enabled
a-InternalAppsDeployOnDemandEnabled-help: Specifies whether internal applications such as the console, uddi, wlstestclient, and uddiexplorer are deployed on demand (first access) instead of during server startup. The default value is true.
a-Interoperate-help: Specifies whether this local Tuxedo access point interoperates with remote Tuxedo access points that are based upon Tuxedo release 6.5. If this value is set to Yes, the local Tuxedo access point interoperates with a Tuxedo 6.5 domain.
f-JMX-a-InvocationTimeoutSeconds-help: The number of seconds that internal WebLogic Server processes wait to connect to an MBean server, invoke an MBean server method, and return the results of the invocation. If the MBean server method does not complete (return) within the timeout period, WebLogic Server abandons its invocation attempt. Some internal management processes within WebLogic Server require a server instance to connect to MBean servers in other WebLogic Server instances and invoke an MBean server method. The timeout period prevents the internal process from locking up if an MBean server cannot successfully return a method invocation. A value of 0 (zero) prevents the method invocation from timing out. With such a value, the internal process will wait indefinitely until the MBean server's method returns.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: When true, and when a JDBC 4.3 compatible driver is used, the connection pool will invoke Connection.beginRequest() prior to returning the connection to the application, and will invoke Connection.endRequest() before the connection is released to the pool.
f-FileStore-a-IoBufferSize-help: The I/O buffer size, in bytes, automatically rounded down to the nearest power of 2.
f-any_DefaultFileStore-a-IoBufferSize-he: The I/O buffer size, in bytes, automatically rounded down to the nearest power of 2.
a-Issuer-help: Specifies an override for the token issuer value used during validation. The issuer is normally obtained from the Oracle Identity Cloud Service Discovery Metadata. When configured, the issuer value is used for all tenants.
a-IssuerUri-help: Specifies the Issuer URI (name) of this SAML2 Identity Provider.
a-JDBCLLRTableName-label: JDBC Last Logging Resource (LLR) Table Name
a-JDBCLLRTableName-help: The table name for this server's Logging Last Resource (LLR) database table(s). WebLogic Server creates the table(s) and then uses them during transaction processing for the LLR transaction optimization. This setting must be unique for each server. The default table name is WL_LLR_SERVERNAME.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: Specifies level of JDBC debugging for XA drivers, where larger values in the range provide more debugging information.
a-JMSDefaultConnectionFactoriesEnabled-h: Specifies whether this server uses JMS default connection factories. The default value is true.
f-WSReliableDeliveryPolicy-a-JMSServer-h: The JMS server used by WebLogic Server, in its role as a sender, to persist the reliable messages that it sends, or the JMS server used by the receiver WebLogic Server to persist the history of a reliable message sent by a sender.
f-any_CoherenceCacheConfig-a-JNDIName-he: The JNDI Name for this CoherenceCacheConfigMBean.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCDa: Add a JNDI name to the data source.
The JNDI names for this data source. By default, the JNDI name is the name of the data source.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Connecti: The JNDI Name for this JMS connection factory. The global JNDI name used to look up a connection factory within a clustered JNDI namespace. In a clustered environment, this name is propagated to the entire cluster. If you want the JNDI name to be bound only on the local server, and not propagated to the rest of the cluster, then use the Local JNDI Name setting. If not specified, then the connection factory is not bound into a clustered JNDI namespace.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Queue-a-: The JNDI Name for this JMS queue. The global JNDI name used to look up a connection factory within a clustered JNDI namespace. In a clustered environment, this name is propagated to the entire cluster. If you want the JNDI name to be bound only on the local server, and not propagated to the rest of the cluster, then use the Local JNDI Name setting. If not specified, then the connection factory is not bound into a clustered JNDI namespace.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Topic-a-: The JNDI Name for this JMS topic. The global JNDI name used to look up a connection factory within a clustered JNDI namespace. In a clustered environment, this name is propagated to the entire cluster. If you want the JNDI name to be bound only on the local server, and not propagated to the rest of the cluster, then use the Local JNDI Name setting. If not specified, then the connection factory is not bound into a clustered JNDI namespace.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_UniformD: The JNDI Name for this JMS uniform distributed queue. The global JNDI name used to look up a connection factory within a clustered JNDI namespace. In a clustered environment, this name is propagated to the entire cluster. If you want the JNDI name to be bound only on the local server, and not propagated to the rest of the cluster, then use the Local JNDI Name setting. If not specified, then the connection factory is not bound into a clustered JNDI namespace.

The JNDI Name for this JMS uniform distributed topic. The global JNDI name used to look up a connection factory within a clustered JNDI namespace. In a clustered environment, this name is propagated to the entire cluster. If you want the JNDI name to be bound only on the local server, and not propagated to the rest of the cluster, then use the Local JNDI Name setting. If not specified, then the connection factory is not bound into a clustered JNDI namespace.
f-MailSession-a-JNDIName-help: The JNDI Name for this JavaMail session.
a-JNDIPrefix-help: Specifies the string that will prefix the local JNDI name of a remote destination.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_ForeignS: Any Credentials that must be set for the JNDI provider. These Credentials will be part of the properties will be passed directly to the constructor for the JNDI provider's InitialContext class. Some foreign providers require other properties to be set while obtaining an initial naming context. These properties can be set with a JNDIProperty bean.
a-JNDITransportableObjectFactoryList-ite: Specifies an object factory that creates transportable objects.
a-JNDITransportableObjectFactoryList-hel: Specifies the list of factories that create transportable objects.
f-WebAppContainer-a-JSPCompilerBackwards: Global property to determine the behavior of the JSP compiler. When this property set to "true", the JSP compiler throws a translation error for JSPs that do not conform to the JSP2.0 specification. This property exists for backward compatibility.
a-JSSEEnabled-help: Determines whether the SSL implementation in Weblogic Server is based on JSSE. The default value is true.
a-JavaCompiler-help: The Java compiler to use for all applications hosted on this server that need to compile Java code.
f-EJBContainer-a-JavaCompiler-help: The path to the Java compiler to use to compile EJBs (e.g. "sj" or "javac"). Note: the default must be null. If no JavaCompiler is specified on this specific EJBComponent, the default will be pulled in the following order from - EJBContainerMBean - Server.JavaCompiler.
a-JavaCompilerPostClassPath-help: Provides a list of the options to append to the Java compiler classpath when you compile Java code.
a-JavaCompilerPreClassPath-help: Provides a list of the options to prepend to the Java compiler classpath when you compile Java code.
f-SystemComponent_SystemComponentStart-a: The Java home directory (path on the machine running Node Manager) to use when starting this server.
f-any_ServerStart-a-JavaHome-help: The Java home directory (on the machine running Node Manager) to use when starting this server.
a-JavaServiceConsoleEnabled-help: Specifies whether the Administration Server automatically deploys the Java Service Administration Console in the current domain. The default value is derived from the JavaServiceEnabled attribute value.
a-JavaServiceEnabled-help: Specifies whether features to support the use of this WebLogic Server as a Java Service in a cloud environment should be enabled. The default value is false.
f-RestfulManagementServices-a-JavaServic: Specifies whether the REST resource features for administering WebLogic Server as a Java Service within a cloud environment should be enabled in this domain.
f-any_CertificateManagement-a-JavaStanda: Whether or not the domain should trust the Java Standard Trust certificates, in addition to the Domain Certificate Authority certificate(s) and any Provisioned Trust certificates. Java Standard Trust is a collection of well-known, trusted root certificate authorities distributed (and updated) as part of the JDK.
f-NMProperties-a-JavaStandardTrustKeySto: Specifies the password defined when creating the Trust keystore. This field is optional or required depending on the type of keystore. All keystores require the passphrase in order to write to the keystore. However, some keystores do not require the passphrase to read from the keystore. Oracle WebLogic Server reads only from the keystore, so whether or not you define this property depends on the requirements of the keystore. This property is required when the Keystores property is set as CustomIdentityAndJavaStandardTrust or DemoIdentityAndDemoTrust.
a-JavaStandardTrustKeyStorePassPhraseEnc: The password for the Java Standard Trust keystore. This password is defined when the keystore is created. If empty or null, then the keystore will be opened without a passphrase.
f-SystemComponent_SystemComponentStart-a: The Java Vendor value to use when starting this server. If the server is part of a cluster and configured for automatic migration across possibly different platforms with different vendors providing the JDKs, then, both JavaVendor and JavaHome should be set in the generated configuration file instead.
f-any_ServerStart-a-JavaVendor-help: The Java Vendor value to use when starting this server.
f-WebAppContainer-a-JaxRsMonitoringDefau: Global property to determine the behavior of monitoring in JAX-RS applications. When the property is set to true (or not set) the monitoring is turned on (if not overridden by properties set directly in application). If the property is set to false the monitoring for all JAX-RS applications is disabled.
a-JmsConnectionFactory-help: For use only with the JAX-RPC stack. For JAX-WS, use WebServiceBufferingMBean instead. The default value is "weblogic.jms.XAConnectionFactory".
a-JmsConnectionFactoryUnmappedResRefMode: JMS Connection Factory Unmapped Resource Reference Mode

Use this unmapped resource reference mode to specify the behavior of any resource reference to a Connection Factory when the resource reference does not directly specify a JNDI name by a lookup attribute, or by a mappedName attribute, or by a jndi-name in a descriptor file. If a JNDI name is specified, the resource reference either resolves to the specified object in the JNDI tree or generates a javax.naming.NameNotFoundException. The default value is "ReturnDefault".
a-JmsCreateDestinationIdentifier-help: A reference name for a destination or a member of a distributed destination that provides a way to lookup that destination without JNDI using jakarta.jms.Session createQueue or createTopic. See "How to Lookup a Destination" in Programming JMS for more information on how to use this attribute. This name must be unique within the scope of the JMS server to which this destination is targeted. However, it does not need to be unique within the scope of an entire JMS module or WebLogic Cluster. For example, two queues can have the same destination name as long as those queues are targeted to different JMS servers. Note: Since this name must be unique within the scope of a JMS server, verify whether other JMS modules may contain destination names that conflict with this name. It is the responsibility of the deployer to resolve the destination names targeted to JMS servers.
f-WTCServer_WTCtBridgeGlobal-a-JmsFactor: The name of the JMS connection factory; for example, weblogic.jndi.ConnectionFactory.  The default value is weblogic.jms.XAConnectionFactory.
a-JmsToTuxPriorityMap-help: The mapping of priorities from JMS to Tuxedo. The default JMS To Tux Priority Map is: 0:1 | 1:12 | 2:23 | 3:34 | 4:45 |5:56 | 6:67 | 7:78 | 8:89 | 9:100.
a-JndiFactory-label: JNDI Initial Context Factory Class Name
f-WTCServer_WTCtBridgeGlobal-a-JndiFacto: The name of the JNDI lookup factory. The default value is weblogic.jndi.WLInitialContextFactory.
f-Cluster-a-JobSchedulerTableName-help: Specifies the table name to use for storing timers active with the job scheduler.
a-JsonWebKeySetUri-help: Specifies an override for the JSON Web Key Set location (jwks_uri) used during validation of tokens. A file location can be specified to load keys from the local environment. The location of the keys is normally obtained from the Oracle Identity Cloud Service Discovery Metadata. When configured, the URI is used for all tenants.
a-JwtTokenExpiration-help: Specifies the time of the JWT token being valid after issuing, in minutes. The default value is 3.
f-WTCServer_WTCLocalTuxDom-a-KeepAlive-h: Return value tells whether this local Tuxedo access point is configured with Application Level Keep Alive, and it maximum idle time value before wait timer start ticking.
f-WTCServer_WTCRemoteTuxDom-a-KeepAlive-: Indicates whether this remote Tuxedo access point is configured with Application Level Keep Alive. Greater than 0 means that the application-level Keep Alive is enabled and the value indicates the amount of idle time, in milliseconds rounded to the nearest second, allowed before starting the wait timer.
a-KeepAliveEnabled-help: Specifies whether to use keep alive to prevent LDAP connections from timing out.
