f-EmbeddedLDAP-a-KeepAliveEnabled-help: Whether keep alive is enabled on the socket connection.
f-any_WebServer-a-KeepAliveEnabled-help: Indicates whether there should be a persistent connection to this server.
a-KeepAliveSecs-help: The amount of time, in seconds, this server waits before closing an inactive HTTP connection.
f-WTCServer_WTCLocalTuxDom-a-KeepAliveWa: Return value that tells whether this local Tuxedo access point requires the acknowledgement of Application Level Keep Alive, and how long it will wait without receiving acknowledgement before declare the connection is inaccessible.
f-WTCServer_WTCRemoteTuxDom-a-KeepAliveW: Indicates whether this remote Tuxedo access point requires the acknowledgement of Application Level Keep Alive. A value of 0 indicates that application-level Keep Alive is not enabled for the access point but the access point acknowledges if a heartbeat is received. A value greater than 0 indicates that application-level Keep Alive is enabled and the value indicates the amount of idle time, in milliseconds rounded to the nearest second, allowed before WebLogic Tuxedo Connector marks the connection as failed if the heartbeat is not acknowledged.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCDa: Enables WebLogic Server to keep the physical database connection associated with the logical connection when committing a global transaction instead releasing it and getting another physical connection when needed. Setting this option to true may require additional connections to be configured on the database. Use this setting to work around specific problems with JDBC XA drivers.
f-EJBContainer-a-KeepGenerated-help: Specifies whether KeepGenerated is enabled and the EJB compiler source files will be kept.
a-KeepLogicalConnOpenOnRelease-label: Keep Logical Connection Open On Release
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCXA: Enables WebLogic Server to keep the logical JDBC connection open for a global transaction when the physical XA connection is returned to the connection pool. Select this option if the XA driver used to create database connections or the DBMS requires that a logical JDBC connection be kept open while transaction processing continues (although the physical XA connection can be returned to the connection pool). Only applies to data sources that use an XA driver. Use this setting to work around specific problems with JDBC XA drivers.
a-KeepXaConnTillTxComplete-label: Keep XA Connection Until Transaction Completes
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCXA: Enables WebLogic Server to associate the same XA database connection from the connection pool with a global transaction until the transaction completes. Only applies to connection pools that use an XA driver. Use this setting to work around specific problems with JDBC XA drivers.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_ForeignS: The name of the JNDI property.
f-any_SingleSignOnServices-a-KeyEncrypti: Get the preferred key encryption algorithm for SAML assertion encryption. This algorithm is used if it is found in the Service Provider's metadata or if the Service Partner's metadata does not include any key encryption algorithm.
f-JoltConnectionPool-a-KeyPassPhraseEncr: The identity certificate private key's passphrase.
a-KeyStoreFileName-help: Specifies the location of the keystore relative to the directory where the server was started.
f-JoltConnectionPool-a-KeyStoreName-help: The path and file name of the identity keystore containing the private key used in SSL mutual authentication.
f-JoltConnectionPool-a-KeyStorePassPhras: The identity keystore passphrase. If empty or null, then the keystore will be opened without a passphrase.
a-KeyStoreProvider-help: Specifies the provider for the Java Security API that should be used.
a-KeyStoreType-help: Specifies the provider will generate a keystore object of this type. The default value is JKS.
a-KeyStores-help: Specifies the set of Identity and Trust keystores the server will use.
f-NMProperties-a-KeyStores-help: Specifies the configuration that Node Manager uses to find its identity (private key and digital certificate) and trust (trusted CA certificates) keystores.
f-WTCServer_WTCLocalTuxDom-a-KeyStoresLo: Provides the configuration rule to be used for finding Local Access Point's identity keystore and trust keystore. In plain text, it contains information on where the identity keystore and trust keystore are configured. When KeyStoreLocation is configured with WLS Store, WTC uses configuration information from the WLS keystores configuration. Otherwise, it uses the keystores information configured in the Local Access Point.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Destinat: The expected property type for this destination key.
a-KnownTenantEmptyMetadataTtl-help: Specifies the time-to-live (TTL) of the empty metadata for known Oracle Identity Cloud Service tenants in Oracle Identity Cloud Service metadata cache, in seconds. The default value 300.
a-KnownTenantPrefix-itemHelp: Specifies a tenant prefix to add to the list.
a-KnownTenantPrefix-help: Specifies the list of tenant prefixes that would identify known or valid Oracle Identity Cloud Service tenant names. Used in combination with KnownTenantEmptyMetadataTTL to decide the TTL of cached empty metadata for Oracle Identity Cloud Service tenants. When no perfixes are configured, all tenants are considered as Oracle Identity Cloud Service tenants. The default value includes "idcs-".
a-KnownType-help: Specifies whether this type is known at startup. Normally, if a type is not available, the Harvester will keep looking for it. If a type is designated as "known", the Harvester issues a validation fault if the type cannot be immediately resolved. A true value means that this type is known. A false value indicates that this type may not be known. This flag is useful for WebLogic Server types, where the type information is always available. In this case, setting the flag to true results in earlier detection and reporting of problems. This flag is optional, but is recommended for WebLogic Server types.
f-Cluster_DatabaseLessLeasingBasis-a-Lea: Sets the LeaderHeartbeatPeriod value, in seconds. The cluster leader heartbeats a special leader heartbeat every period seconds to publish group view version and other cluster information. Members look at this heartbeat and perform any sync up operations if required. The default value is 10.
a-ListenAddress-help: The DNS name or IP address.
f-any_SNMPProxy-a-ListenAddress-help: The address on which the external SNMP agent for which the WebLogic SNMP Agent is acting as a proxy is listening for incoming requests from SNMP managers that use the UDP protocol. If not specified the Server's ListenAddress is used as the ListenAddress of the external SNMPAgent.
f-SNMPAgent-a-ListenAddress-help: The listen address on which you want this SNMP agent to listen for incoming requests from SNMP managers that use the UDP protocol. If not specified the Server's ListenAddress is used as the ListenAddress for the SNMPAgent.
f-SnmpAgentDeployment-a-ListenAddress-he: The listen address on which you want this SNMP agent to listen for incoming requests from SNMP managers that use the UDP protocol. If not specified the Server's ListenAddress is used as the ListenAddress for the SNMPAgent.
f-NMProperties-a-ListenAddress-help: Any address upon which the machine running Node Manager can listen for connection requests.
f-any_NodeManager-a-ListenAddress-help: Specifies the host name or IP address of the NodeManager for the server or clients on the server to use when connecting to the NodeManager instance.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-ListenAddress: The IP address or DNS name this network channel uses to listen for incoming connections. A value of null indicates that the network channel should obtain this value from the server's configuration.
f-NMProperties-a-ListenBacklog-help: Maximum number of Node Manager backlog requests that the listener will accept; the default value is 50. Additional incoming requests will be dropped until the backlogged requests are handled. Typically, you need not adjust this property.
a-ListenPort-help: The default TCP port that this server uses to listen for regular (non-SSL) incoming connections.
f-any_SSL-a-ListenPort-help: The TCP/IP port at which this server listens for SSL connection requests.
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource_Coheren: The listen port. Deprecated in 12.2.1 since the well-known address no longer needs a port to bne specified.
f-NMProperties-a-ListenPort-help: Specifies the TCP port number on which Node Manager listens for connection requests.
f-any_NodeManager-a-ListenPort-help: Specifies the port number of the NodeManager for the server or clients on the server to use when connecting to the NodeManager instance.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-ListenPort-he: The default TCP port this network channel uses to listen for regular (non-SSL) incoming connections. A value of -1 indicates that the network channel should obtain this value from the server's configuration.
a-ListenPortEnabled-help: Specifies whether this server can be reached through the default plain-text (non-SSL) listen port.
f-Topology-a-ListenPortEnabled-help: Specifies the domain-wide setting for whether the server ListenPorts are enabled. Can be overridden at the server level. The default value is true except in secure production mode.
a-ListenThreadStartDelaySecs-help: Specifies the maximum time that the server will wait for server sockets to bind before starting a listen thread. The default value is 60.
a-ListenersBindEarly-help: Determines whether the server should bind server sockets early. Early binding detects port conflicts quickly and also gives user feedback on the default listen port as to the server state.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_WatchN: Indicates whether or not to include the set of live objects in the heap dump capture.
f-StartupClass-a-LoadAfterAppsRunning-he: Specifies whether the targeted servers load and run this startup class after applications and EJBs are running. If you enable this feature for a startup class, a server loads and runs the startup class after the activate phase. At this point, JMS and JDBC services are available. (Deployment for applications and EJBs consists of three phases: prepare, admin and activate.)
a-LoadBalancingEnabled-help: Specifies whether non-anonymous producers created through a connection factory are load balanced within a distributed destination on a per-call basis.
a-LoadBalancingPolicy-help: Determines how messages are distributed to the members of this destination. Note: This attribute is ignored by standalone/singleton queues and topics, it only applies to distributed destinations.
f-StartupClass-a-LoadBeforeAppActivation: Specifies whether the targeted servers load and run this startup class after activating JMS and JDBC services and before activating applications and EJBs. If you enable this feature for a startup class, a server loads and runs the startup class before the activate phase. At this point, JMS and JDBC services are available. (Deployment for applications and EJBs consists of three phases: prepare, admin and activate.)
f-StartupClass-a-LoadBeforeAppDeployment: Specifies whether the targeted servers load and run this startup class before activating JMS and JDBC services and before starting deployment for applications and EJBs. If you enable this feature for a startup class, a server loads and runs the startup class before the deployment prepare phase. At this point, JMS and JDBC services are not yet available. (Deployment for applications and EJBs consists of three phases: prepare, admin and activate.)
a-LoadStubUsingContextClassLoader-label: Load Stub Using Context Class Loader
f-WTCServer_WTCRemoteTuxDom-a-LocalAcces: The local domain name from which this remote Tuxedo domain is reached.
f-WTCServer_WTCExport-a-LocalAccessPoint: The name of the local access point that exports this service.
f-WTCServer_WTCImport-a-LocalAccessPoint: The name of the local access point that offers this service.
f-WTCServer_WTCPassword-a-LocalAccessPoi: The name of the local access point to which this password applies.
a-LocalDomainSecurityCacheEnabled-help: Specifies whether the Local Domain Security subject cache is enabled.
a-LocalDomainSecurityCacheTtl-help: Specifies the time-to-live (TTL), in seconds, of the Local Domain Security subject cache. This value is used only if LocalDomainSecurityCacheEnabled is set to true.
a-LocalDomainSecurityEnabled-help: Specifies whether Local Domain Security is enabled. When enabled, the transaction coordinator makes intra-domain calls using an identity from the credential mapper where remoteHost equals the local domain name and protocol is cross-domain-protocol. When disabled, the subject used for intra-domain communication is determined by the Security Interop Mode setting.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Connecti: The local JNDI name used to look up the connection factory within the JNDI namespace of the server where the connection factory is targeted. In a clustered environment, this name is bound only on the local server instance and is not propagated to the rest of the cluster. If not specified, then the connection factory is not bound into the local JNDI namespace.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_ForeignS: The name that the remote object will be bound to in the local server's JNDI tree. This is the name that should be used to look up the object on the local server.
The name that the remote object will be bound to in the local server's JNDI tree. This is the name that should be used to look up the object on the local server.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Queue-a-: The local JNDI name used to look up the destination within the JNDI namespace of the server where the destination resource is targeted. In a clustered environment, this name is bound only on the local server instance and is not propagated to the rest of the cluster. A destination can have both a local JNDI name and a (global) JNDI name.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_SAFImpor: The local JNDI name of the remote destination.
The local JNDI name of the remote destination.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Topic-a-: The local JNDI name used to look up the destination within the JNDI namespace of the server where the destination resource is targeted. In a clustered environment, this name is bound only on the local server instance and is not propagated to the rest of the cluster. A destination can have both a local JNDI name and a (global) JNDI name.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_UniformD: The local JNDI name used to look up the destination within the JNDI namespace of the server where the destination resource is targeted. In a clustered environment, this name is bound only on the local server instance and is not propagated to the rest of the cluster. A destination can have both a local JNDI name and a (global) JNDI name.

The local JNDI name used to look up the destination within the JNDI namespace of the server where the destination resource is targeted. In a clustered environment, this name is bound only on the local server instance and is not propagated to the rest of the cluster. A destination can have both a local JNDI name and a (global) JNDI name.
f-ForeignJNDIProvider_ForeignJNDILink-a-: The JNDI name that the foreign JNDI object will be bound to in the local JNDI namespace.
f-WTCServer_WTCPassword-a-LocalPassword-: The local password used to authenticate connections between the local access point and the remote access point. Note that this password is used to authenticate connections between the local Tuxedo access point identified by LocalAccessPoint and the remote Tuxedo access point identified by RemoteAccessPoint.
f-WTCServer_WTCPassword-a-LocalPasswordI: The initialization vector used to encrypt the local password.
a-LocalStorageEnabled-help: Specifies whether Local Storage is enabled.
f-any_CoherenceMemberConfig-a-LocalStora: Specifies whether or not this member will contribute storage to the Coherence cluster. This attribute is used only when the WebLogic Server is not part of a WLS Cluster.
f-SNMPAgent-a-LocalizedKeyCacheInvalidat: The number of milliseconds after which WebLogic Server invalidates its cache of SNMP security keys. Setting a high value creates a risk that users whose credentials have been removed can still access SNMP data. An SNMP security key is an encrypted version of an SNMP agent's engine ID and an authentication password or privacy password. WebLogic Server generates one security key for each entry that you create in the SNMP credential map. When a WebLogic Server SNMP agent receives an SNMPv3 request, it compares the key that is in the request with its WebLogic Server keys. If it finds a match, it processes the request. The SNMP agent also encodes these keys in its responses and notifications. (You configure which keys are encoded when you create a trap destination.) Instead of regenerating the keys for each SNMPv3 communication, WebLogic Server caches the keys. To make sure that the cache contains the latest set of SNMP credentials, WebLogic Server periodically invalidates the cache. After the cache is invalidated, the next time an SNMP agent requests credentials, WebLogic Server regenerates the cache. Note that making a change to the credential map does not automatically update the cache. Instead, the cache is updated only after it has been invalidated.
f-SnmpAgentDeployment-a-LocalizedKeyCach: The number of milliseconds after which WebLogic Server invalidates its cache of SNMP security keys. Setting a high value creates a risk that users whose credentials have been removed can still access SNMP data. An SNMP security key is an encrypted version of an SNMP agent's engine ID and an authentication password or privacy password. WebLogic Server generates one security key for each entry that you create in the SNMP credential map. When a WebLogic Server SNMP agent receives an SNMPv3 request, it compares the key that is in the request with its WebLogic Server keys. If it finds a match, it processes the request. The SNMP agent also encodes these keys in its responses and notifications. (You configure which keys are encoded when you create a trap destination.) Instead of regenerating the keys for each SNMPv3 communication, WebLogic Server caches the keys. To make sure that the cache contains the latest set of SNMP credentials, WebLogic Server periodically invalidates the cache. After the cache is invalidated, the next time an SNMP agent requests credentials, WebLogic Server regenerates the cache. Note that making a change to the credential map does not automatically update the cache. Instead, the cache is updated only after it has been invalidated.
a-Location-help: For file stores, specifies the directory that will hold all files related to the store. The actual file names are controlled internally by the file store implementation. For other types of stores, this location may be a URL or URI, or other description string.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_Instru: Attached actions are applied at selected locations: before, after, or around pointcuts. This is relevant only for custom monitors. (A location where diagnostic code is added is called a diagnostic joinpoint. A set of joinpoints, identified by an expression, is called a pointcut.)
a-LockoutCacheSize-help: Specifies the number of invalid login records that the server places in a cache. The server creates one record for each invalid login. The default value is 5.
a-LockoutDuration-help: Specifies the number of minutes that a user account is locked out. The default value is 30.
a-LockoutEnabled-help: Specifies whether the server locks out users when there are invalid login attempts. A true value for this attribute causes the server to consider the other attributes of this MBean. A false value causes the server to ignore the other attributes of this MBean. The default value is true.
a-LockoutGcThreshold-help: Specifies the maximum number of invalid login records that the server keeps in memory. If the number of invalid login records is equal to or greater than this value, the server's garbage collection purges the records that have expired. A record expires when the user associated with the record has been locked out. The lower the threshold, the more often the server uses its resources to collect garbage. The default value is 400.
a-LockoutResetDuration-help: Specifies the number of minutes within which consecutive invalid login attempts cause the user account to be locked out. The default value is 5.
a-LockoutThreshold-help: Specifies the maximum number of consecutive invalid login attempts before account is locked out. When the number of invalid logins within a specified period of time is greater than LockoutThreshold value, the user is locked out. For example, with a setting of 1, the user is locked out on the second consecutive invalid login. With a setting of 2, the user is locked out on the third consecutive invalid login. The default value is 5.
f-NMProperties-a-LogAppend-help: If set to true, then a new log file is not created when Node Manager restarts; the existing log is appended instead.
f-NMProperties-a-LogCount-help: Maximum number of log files to create when LogLimit exceeds.
a-LogCriticalRemoteExceptionsEnabled-hel: Specifies whether the server message log includes only critical exceptions that are raised in remote systems. Non-critical exceptions, such as javax.management.InstanceNotFoundException and javax.management.AttributeNotFoundException, will not be included in the message log. The default value is false in development mode and true in production mode.
f-NMProperties-a-LogFile-help: Location of the Node Manager log file.
f-any_Log-a-LogFileFilter-help: The filter configuration for the domain log file. A filter configuration defines simple filtering rules to limit the volume of log messages written to the log file.
a-LogFileFormat-help: The format of the HTTP log file. Both formats are defined by the W3C. With the extended log format, you use server directives in the log file to customize the information that the server records. The default value is common.
a-LogFileRotationDir-help: The directory where the rotated log files will be stored. By default the rotated files are stored in the same directory where the log file is stored.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_SAFError: Specifies how information is logged when Message Handling Policy is set to Log. When specifying multiple values, enter them as a comma-separated list. The %header% and %properties% values are not case sensitive. For example, you could use "%header%,%properties%" for all the JMS header fields and user properties. However, the enumeration of individual JMS header fields and user-defined properties are case sensitive. To enumerate only individual JMS header fields you could use "%header, name, address, city, state, zip". Note: The JMSMessageID field is always logged and cannot be turned off. Therefore, if the Log Format is not defined (i.e., null) or is defined as an empty string, then the output to the log file contains only the JMSMessageID of the message.
f-any_Log-a-LogFileSeverity-help: The minimum severity of log messages going to the domain log file.
a-LogFormatCompatibilityEnabled-help: Specifies whether log messages will be logged in legacy format without supplemental attributes. The default value is false.
f-NMProperties-a-LogFormatter-help: Specifies the formatter classname to use for Node Manager log messages.
f-NMProperties-LogLevel-help: Severity level of logging used for the Node Manager log. Node Manager uses the standard logging levels from the java.util.logging.level package.
f-NMProperties-a-LogLimit-help: Specifies the maximum size of the Node Manager log specified as an integer in bytes. When this limit is reached, a new log file is started.
f-any_Log-a-LogMonitoringEnabled-help: Specifies whether log monitoring is enabled.
f-any_Log-a-LogMonitoringIntervalSecs-he: Timer interval in seconds to check the counts of messages logged during the interval.
a-LogMonitoringMaxThrottleMessageSignatu: Log Monitoring Max Throttle Message Signature Count
f-any_Log-a-LogMonitoringMaxThrottleMess: Maximum number of unique message signatures that will be monitored during the throttle interval.
f-any_Log-a-LogMonitoringThrottleMessage: Cut-off length of the log message for evaluation during throttle period. The log message length is truncated to this length for evaluation of repeated logging events.
f-any_Log-a-LogMonitoringThrottleThresho: The threshold number of messages logged during the evaluation period which enables or disables the throttling. Once throttling is enabled messages with the same repeating message signatures are throttled. Every nth repeated message specified by this attribute is logged in a monitoring cycle.
a-LogRemoteExceptionsEnabled-help: Specifies whether the server message log includes exceptions that are raised in remote systems. The default value is false.
a-LogTimeInGMT-help: Specifies whether the time stamps for HTTP log messages are in Greenwich Mean Time (GMT) regardless of the local time zone that the host computer specifies. Use this method to comply with the W3C specification for Extended Format log files. The specification states that all time stamps for Extended Format log entries be in GMT. This method applies only if you have specified the extended message format. The default value is false.
f-NMProperties-a-LogToStderr-help: If set to true, the log output is also sent to the standard error output.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_WatchN: The threshold severity level of log messages evaluated by log policies. Messages with a lower severity than this value will be ignored and not evaluated against the policies. Do not confuse LogWatchSeverity with Severity. LogWatchSeverity filters which log messages will be evaluated; Severity sets the default severity level for an action.
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource_Coheren: The logger name for Coherence logs.
f-any_Log-a-LoggerSeverity-help: The minimum severity of log messages going to all log destinations.
a-LoggerSeverityProperties-keyHelp: Specifies the name of the logger to which the severity level should be set.
a-LoggerSeverityProperties-valueHelp: Specifies the logger's severity level. Legal values are "Emergency", "Alert", "Critical", "Error", "Warning", "Notice", "Info", "Debug", or "Trace".
f-any_Log-a-LoggerSeverityProperties-hel: The configuration of the different logger severities keyed by name. The values are one of the predefined Severity strings namely Emergency, Alert, Critical, Error, Warning, Notice, Info, Debug, Trace.
f-SAFAgent-a-LoggingEnabled-help: Specifies whether a message is logged in the server log file when a message fails to be forwarded. If selected, this applies to messages that fail to be forwarded and delivered to the final destination when there is no error handling in a SAF application or the application's error handling fails.
f-any_WebServerLog-a-LoggingEnabled-help: Indicates whether this server logs HTTP requests. Note that the remaining fields are only relevant if this option is enabled. The default value is true.
a-LogicalName-help: The name used by subsystems to refer to different stores on different servers using the same name. For example, an EJB that uses the timer service may refer to its store using the logical name, and this name may be valid on multiple servers in the same cluster, even if each server has a store with a different physical name. Multiple stores in the same domain or the same cluster may share the same logical name. However, a given logical name may not be assigned to more than one store on the same server.
a-LoginAttemptsWhileLockedTotalCount-lab: Login Attempts While Locked Total Count
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: The number of seconds to delay before creating each physical database connection. This delay supports database servers that cannot handle multiple connection requests in rapid succession. The delay takes place both during initial data source creation and during the lifetime of the data source whenever a physical database connection is created.
f-any_SingleSignOnServices-a-LoginReturn: The name of the query parameter to be used for conveying the login-return URL to the login form web application.
a-LoginTimeoutMillis-help: Specifies the login timeout in milliseconds for this server's default regular (non-SSL) listen port. A value of 0 indicates there is no maximum. The default value is 5000.
f-any_SSL-a-LoginTimeoutMillis-help: Specifies the number of milliseconds that WebLogic Server waits for an SSL connection before timing out. SSL connections take longer to negotiate than regular connections. If clients are connecting over the Internet, raise the default number to accommodate additional network latency. The default value is 25000.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-LoginTimeoutM: The amount of time that this network channel should wait for a connection before timing out. A value of 0 disables network channel login timeout. A value of -1 indicates that the network channel obtains this timeout value from the server's configuration.

Sets the duration allowed for an SSL login sequence. If the duration is exceeded, the login is timed out. A value of 0 disables the channel login timeout. Setting this to -1 implies that this value is inherited from the SSLMBean.
a-LoginTokenAssociatonEnabled-help: Specifies whether the SAML2 Assertion token is associated with the Session at the time of login.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_SAFRemot: Specifies the URL to connect to when using this SAF Login Context. SAFImportedDestinations are associated with a SAFRemoteContext that has a SAFLoginContext. This SAFLoginContext defines the URL to use to connect.
f-any_SingleSignOnServices-a-LoginUrl-he: The URL of the login form web application to which unauthenticated requests are directed. By default, the login URL is /saml2/idp/login using Basic authentication. Typically you specify this URL if you are using a custom login web application.
f-ManagedExecutorServiceTemplate-a-LongR: An integer that specifies the long-running daemon thread's priority. If a value is specified, all long-running threads are affected.
f-ManagedScheduledExecutorServiceTemplat: An integer that specifies the long-running daemon thread's priority. If a value is specified, all long-running threads are affected.
a-MBEncodingMapFile-help: The encoding name map file between Java and Tuxedo MBSTRING.
a-MTUSize-help: Specifies the MTU size to use with the NIC. The default value is 1500.
a-Machine-help: The WebLogic Server host computer (machine) on which this server is meant to run. If you want to use a Node Manager to start this server, you must assign the server to a machine and you must configure the machine for the Node Manager.
f-Cluster_DynamicServers-a-MachineMatchE: Specifies the machine tag expression to use when selecting machine names. If the MachineMatchType is "name", each value will either match a machine name exactly or, if specified with a trailing '*' suffix, will match multiple machine names. If the MachineMatchType is "tag", the values will match all of the machines that have all of the tag values.
f-Cluster_DynamicServers-a-MachineMatchT: Specifies the machine tag expression to use when selecting machine names. If the MachineMatchType is "name", each value will either match a machine name exactly or, if specified with a trailing '*' suffix, will match multiple machine names. If the MachineMatchType is "tag", the values will match all of the machines that have all of the tag values.
f-Cluster_DynamicServers-a-MachineNameMa: The expression is used when determining machines to use for server assignments. If null, then all machines in the domain are used. If a expression is provided, then only the machines in the domain that match the expression will be used when assigning machine names to dynamic servers. The expression is a comma separated set of values that specify the machines to match. Each value will either match a machine name exactly or if specified with a trailing '*' suffix, the value will match multiple machine names.
a-MagicThreadDumpBackToSocket-label: Magic Thread Dump Back To Socket
a-MagicThreadDumpFile-help: Specifies the magic thread dump file name. The default value is "debugMagicThreadDumpFile".
a-MagicThreadDumpHost-help: Specifies the magic thread dump hostname. The default value is 127.0.0.1.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_WatchN: The JNDI name of the mail session. This name must match the attribute in the corresponding MailSessionMBean.
a-ManagedServerIndependenceEnabled-help: Specifies whether this Managed Server can be started when the Administration Server is unavailable. The default value is true.
f-JMX-a-ManagedServerNotificationsEnable: Specifies whether the WebLogic Server Domain Runtime MBean Server will support notifications from the federated Runtime MBean Servers on the managed and administration servers. Supporting notifications requires a significant amount of memory resources. A list of ObjectNames is maintained for each MBean from the Runtime MBean Servers. If notifications are not required for this domain, then disabling them will save on CPU and memory resources. This is particularly critical if there are large numbers of runtime MBeans and/or large numbers of servers.
f-JMX-a-ManagementAppletCreateEnabled-he: Specifies whether the WebLogic Server MBean Servers will support creation of management applet (MLet) MBeans. MLet MBeans allow a user to upload the MBean implementation from a remote server and should only be enabled if the environment and security manager restrict access to trusted JMX clients.
f-JMX-a-ManagementEJBEnabled-help: Enables access to the Management EJB (MEJB), which is part of the Java EE Management APIs (JSR-77). The Management API specification provides a standardized management data model for common resources on Java EE Web application servers. The MEJB provides access to Java EE Managed Objects (JMOs), which describe the common Java EE resources. If you set this attribute to false, WebLogic Server does not register the MEJB in the JNDI tree, and effectively disables the Java EE Management APIs for the domain.
f-any_Realm-a-ManagementIdentityDomain-h: Sets the Management Identity Domain value for the realm.
a-ManagementTokenMaxTimeout-help: Specifies the maximum time, specified in minutes, that a management token issued for a user can be valid. The default value is 480.
a-MasterAgentXPort-help: The port that this SNMP agent uses to communicate with its subagents. The agent uses subagents to provide access to custom MBeans (MBeans that you create and register) and to other software components. WebLogic Server SNMP agents do not enable users to register their own subagents.
f-EmbeddedLDAP-a-MasterFirst-help: Specifies whether a Managed Server should always connect to the master LDAP server (contained in the Administration Server), instead of connecting to the local replicated LDAP server (contained in the Managed Server).
a-MatchGroupBaseDn-help: Specifies whether or not the group membership search result should match the GroupBaseDN value.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-MaxBackoffBet: The maximum back off time between failures while accepting client connections. -1 implies that this value is inherited from the server.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: The maximum number of physical connections that this connection pool can contain.
a-MaxConcurrentLongRunningRequests-help: The maximum number of running long-running requests that can be submitted to all the Managed Executor Services or Managed Scheduled Executor Services in the server. The default value is 100.
f-ManagedExecutorServiceTemplate-a-MaxCo: The maximum number of running long-running tasks submitted to this Concurrent Managed Object (CMO).
f-ManagedScheduledExecutorServiceTemplat: The maximum number of running long-running tasks submitted to this Concurrent Managed Object (CMO).
f-Topology-a-MaxConcurrentLongRunningReq: The domain-wide default for the maximum number of running long-running requests that can be submitted to all the Managed Executor Services or Managed Scheduled Executor Services on a server. The default value is 50.
a-MaxConcurrentNewThreads-help: The maximum number of running threads that can be created by all the Managed Thread Factories in the server.
f-ManagedThreadFactoryTemplate-a-MaxConc: The maximum number of concurrent new threads that can be created by this Managed Thread Factory (MTF). The default value is 100.
f-Topology-a-MaxConcurrentNewThreads-hel: The domain-wide default for the maximum number of running threads that can be created by all the Managed Thread Factories on a server. The default value is 50.
f-WebAppContainer_Http2Config-a-MaxConcu: The maximum number of concurrent streams that the server will allow. This limit is directional: it applies to the number of streams that the server permits the receiver to create.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-MaxConnectedC: The maximum number of clients that can be connected on this network channel.
a-MaxConsecutiveCharacters-help: Specifies the maximum number of repeating consecutive characters that is allowed in the password. A value of 0 means no restriction. For example, with a value of 2, user can not create a password such as "baaag". Valid value for this attribute must be greater than or equal to 0.
f-CXluster_DynamicServers-a-MaxDynamicCl: Specifies the upper bound on the DynamicClusterSize that the Elasticity Framework is allowed to assign to DynamicClusterSize.
f-WTCServer_WTCLocalTuxDom-a-MaxEncryptB: The maximum encryption key length (in bits) this local Tuxedo access point uses when establishing a session connection. A value of 0 indicates no encryption is used.
f-WTCServer_WTCRemoteTuxDom-a-MaxEncrypt: The maximum encryption key length (in bits) this remote Tuxedo access point uses when establishing a session connection. A value of 0 indicates no encryption is used.
f-FileStore-a-MaxFileSize-help: The maximum file size, in bytes, of an individual data file. A small number of larger files is normally preferred over a large number of smaller files as each file allocates Window Buffer and file handles. If MaxFileSize is larger than 2^24 * BlockSize, then MaxFileSize is ignored, and the value becomes 2^24 * BlockSize. The default BlockSize is 512, and 2^24 * 512 is 8 GB.
f-any_DefaultFileStore-a-MaxFileSize-hel: The maximum file size, in bytes, of an individual data file. A small number of larger files is normally preferred over a large number of smaller files as each file allocates Window Buffer and file handles. If MaxFileSize is larger than 2^24 * BlockSize, then MaxFileSize is ignored, and the value becomes 2^24 * BlockSize. The default BlockSize is 512, and 2^24 * 512 is 8 GB.
f-WebAppContainer_Http2Config-a-MaxFrame: The size of the largest frame payload that the server is willing to receive, in octets.
a-MaxGroupHierarchiesInCache-help: Specifies the maximum size of the LRU cache for holding group membership hierarchies if caching is enabled. The default value is 100.
a-MaxGroupMembershipSearchLevel-help: Specifies how many levels of group membership can be searched. This setting is valid only if GroupMembershipSearching is set to limited. Valid values are 0 and positive integers. For example, 0 indicates only direct group memberships will be found, and a positive number indicates the number of levels to search. Note that when Use Token Groups For Group Membership Lookup is used during authentication, all the groups are returned in a single call, and the recursion limits and depth limits do not apply. They will apply in management operations.
f-WebAppContainer_Http2Config-a-MaxHeade: The maximum size of header list that the server is prepared to accept, in octets. The value is based on the uncompressed size of header fields, including the length of the name and value in octets plus an overhead of 32 octets for each header field.
f-any_ServerDiagnosticConfig-a-MaxHeapDu: Sets the maximum number of heap dump files to be retained which are generated by heap dump actions. If this limit is reached, oldest heap dumps will be deleted while creating new heap dump so that this limit is not exceeded. The default value is 8.
a-MaxInformRetryCount-help: The maximum number of times that this SNMP agent will resend INFORM notifications for which it has not received a response.
a-MaxInstancesOfAnyCharacter-help: Specifies the maximum number of times the same character can appear in a password. "0" means no restriction. For example, with a value of 2, user can not create a password such as "abagia". Valid value for this attribute must be greater than or equal to 0.
a-MaxMessageSize-help: The maximum number of bytes allowed in messages that are received over all supported protocols, unless overridden by a protocol-specific setting or a custom channel setting. The order of precedence for setting message size maximums is as follows: 1.) A channel-wide maximum in a custom network channel, 2.) A protocol-specific setting in the default network channel, 3.) The message maximum in this attribute. This maximum message size helps guard against a denial of service attack in which a caller attempts to force the server to allocate more memory than is available thereby keeping the server from responding quickly to other requests. The default value is 10000000.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-MaxMessageSiz: The maximum message size allowable in a message header. This maximum attempts to prevent a denial of service attack whereby a caller attempts to force the server to allocate more memory than is available thereby keeping the server from responding quickly to other requests.
a-MaxOpenSockCount-help: The maximum number of open sockets allowed in server at a given point of time. When the maximum threshold is reached, the server stops accepting new requests until the number of sockets drops below the threshold. A value less than 0 indicates an unlimited size.
a-MaxPasswordLength-help: Specifies the maximum length of password, a password length must be greater than or equal to the value. "0" means no restriction. Valid value for this attribute must be greater than or equal to 0.
a-MaxPostSize-help: The maximum post size, in bytes, this server allows for reading HTTP POST data in a servlet request. A value less than 0 indicates an unlimited size. The default value is -1.
a-MaxPostTimeSecs-help: Maximum post time (in seconds) for reading HTTP POST data in a servlet request. MaxPostTime < 0 means unlimited. The default value is -1.
f-WebserviceSecurity_WebserviceTimestamp: Specifies the freshness policy for received messages: the Web Service observes the processing delay by subtracting the Created time in the Timestamp from the current time. If the observed processing delay is greater than maxProcessingDelay plus clockSkew, then the message is rejected as stale. This attribute is specified in milliseconds. Setting maxProcessingDelay to -1 (the default) disables to enforcement of the freshness policy.
a-MaxRequestParameterCount-help: The maximum request parameter count this server allows for reading maximum HTTP POST parameters count in a servlet request. Gets the maxRequestParameterCount attribute of the WebServerMBean object. The default value is 10000.
a-MaxResourceRequestsOnServer-help: Maximum number of concurrent requests to resources allowed for each server.
a-MaxResourceUnavailableMillis-help: Maximum duration time, in milliseconds, that a resource is declared dead. After the duration, the resource is declared available again, even if the resource provider does not explicitly re-register the resource.
f-WTCServer_WTCLocalTuxDom-a-MaxRetries-: The maximum number of times that this local Tuxedo access point tries to establish a session connection to remote Tuxedo access points. Use this value only when Connection Policy is set to ON_STARTUP. The default value is 9223372036854775807.
f-WTCServer_WTCRemoteTuxDom-a-MaxRetries: The maximum encryption key length (in bits) this remote Tuxedo access point uses when establishing a session connection. A value of 0 indicates no encryption is used. Note that when the ConnectionPolicy value is LOCAL, the MaxRetries value from the local Tuxedo access point is used. When the ConnectionPolicy value is ON_STARTUP, a value of -1 indicates 9223372036854775807.
a-MaxRetrySecondsBeforeDeterminerFail-la: Max Retry Seconds Before Determiner Fail
a-MaxRetrySecondsBeforeDeterminerFail-he: The maximum amount of time, in seconds, WebLogic Server waits for the determiner to recover from a failure. If the determiner does not recover after this period, WebLogic Server sets the TLog health state to HEALTH_FAILED.
a-MaxRetrySecondsBeforeTlogFail-label: Max Retry Seconds Before TLOG Fail
a-MaxRetrySecondsBeforeTlogFail-help: The maximum amount of time, in seconds, WebLogic Server tries to recover from a JDBC transaction log store failure. If store remains unusable after this period, WebLogic Server set the health state to HEALTH_FAILED. A value of 0 indicates WebLogic Server does not conduct a retry and and immediately sets the health state as HEALTH_FAILED.
a-MaxRetrySecondsBeforeTxException-label: Max Retry Seconds Before Transaction Exception
a-MaxRetrySecondsBeforeTXException-help: The maximum amount of time, in seconds, WebLogic Server waits before trying to recover from a JDBC transaction log store failure while processing a transaction. If store remains unusable after this amount of time, WebLogic Server throws an exception the affected transaction. A value of 0 indicates WebLogic Server does not conduct a retry and an exception will thrown immediately. The practical maximum value is a value less than the current value of MaxRetrySecondsBeforeTLogFail. The default value is 60.
a-MaxRetrySecondsBeforeTxRollback-label: Max Retry Seconds Before Tx Rollback
f-any_ActiveDirectoryAuthenticator-a-Max: The maximum size of the LRU cache for holding SID to group lookups if caching of SID to group name mappings is enabled and if the tokenGroups group membership lookup is enabled. The default value is 500.
f-Cluster-a-MaxSecondarySelectionAttempt: Specifies the max number of attempts at choosing a suitable secondary server for replication. If it is set to 0,secondary server selection for replication will be tried on all servers in the cluster.
a-MaxServerCountForHttpPing-label: Max Server Count For HTTP Ping
f-Cluster-a-MaxServerCountForHttpPing-he: Set the number of HTTP pings to execute before declaring a server unreachable. This comes into effect only when MaxServerCountForHTTPPing is > 0.
a-MaxSingleHeaderSize-help: The maximum size of a single header (name and value) this server allows in a servlet request. A value less than 0 indicates an unlimited size. The default value is -1.
a-MaxSize-help: Provides the maximum number of entries that can be stored in the cache at any given time.
f-WebAppContainer_Http2Config-a-MaxStrea: Gets the maximum number of stream resets(RST_STREAM frames) allowed per connection.
f-SelfTuning_WorkManager_WorkManagerShut: Time in seconds after which a executing thread is marked as stuck.
f-Cluster_OverloadProtection_ServerFailu: The number of seconds that a thread must be continually working on a single request before this server diagnoses the thread as being stuck.
f-any_ServerFailureTrigger-a-MaxStuckThr: The number of seconds that a thread must be continually working on a single request before this server diagnoses the thread as being stuck. The default value is 600.
f-any_ServerDiagnosticConfig-a-MaxThread: Sets the maximum number of thread dump files to be retained which are generated by thread dump actions. If this limit is reached, oldest thread dump files will be deleted while creating new thread dump file so that this limit is not exceeded. The default value is 100.
f-SelfTuning_WorkManager-a-MaxThreadsCon: The name of the MaxThreadsConstraint that defines the maximum number of concurrent threads that can be allocated to execute requests.
a-MaxTotalHeadersSize-help: The maximum total headers size this server allows for reading HTTP headers in a servlet request. A value less than 0 indicates an unlimited size. The default value is -1.
a-MaxTransactions-help: The maximum number of simultaneous in-progress transactions allowed on a server in this WebLogic Server domain.
a-MaxTransactionsHealthIntervalMillis-he: The time interval, in milliseconds, for which the transaction map must be full for the JTA subsystem to declare its health as CRITICAL.
a-MaxUniqueNameStatistics-help: The maximum number of unique transaction names for which statistics are maintained. The first 1001 unique transaction names are maintained as their own transaction name and stored in each statistic. After the 1001st transaction name is reached, the transaction name is stored as weblogic.transaction.statistics.namedOverflow, and the transaction statistic is also merged and maintained in weblogic.transaction.statistics.namedOverflow. A transaction name typically represents a category of business transactions, such as "funds-transfer."
f-any_Realm-a-MaxWebLogicPrincipalsInCac: The maximum size of the LRU cache for holding WebLogic Principal signatures. This value is only used if EnableWebLogicPrincipalValidatorCache is set to true
f-FileStore-a-MaxWindowBufferSize-help: The maximum amount of data, in bytes and rounded down to the nearest power of 2, mapped into the JVM's address space per primary store file. Applies to synchronous write policies Direct-Write-With-Cache and Disabled but only when the native wlfileio library is loaded. A window buffer does not consume Java heap memory, but does consume off-heap (native) memory. If the store is unable to allocate the requested buffer size, it allocates smaller and smaller buffers until it reaches MinWindowBufferSize, and then fails if cannot honor MinWindowBufferSize.
f-any_DefaultFileStore-a-MaxWindowBuffer: The maximum amount of data, in bytes and rounded down to the nearest power of 2, mapped into the JVM's address space per primary store file. Applies to synchronous write policies Direct-Write-With-Cache and Disabled but only when the native wlfileio library is loaded. A window buffer does not consume Java heap memory, but does consume off-heap (native) memory. If the store is unable to allocate the requested buffer size, it allocates smaller and smaller buffers until it reaches MinWindowBufferSize, and then fails if cannot honor MinWindowBufferSize.
a-MaxXACallMillis-help: Maximum allowed time duration, in milliseconds, for XA calls to resources. If a particular XA call to a resource exceeds the limit, the resource is declared unavailable.
f-JMSServer-a-MaximumMessageSize-help: The maximum number of bytes allowed in individual messages on this JMS server. The size of a message includes the message body, any user-defined properties, and the user-defined JMS header fields JMSCorrelationID and JMSType. The maximum message size is only enforced for the initial production of a message. Messages that are redirected to an error destination or forwarded to a member of a distributed destination are not checked for size.
f-SAFAgent-a-MaximumMessageSize-help: The maximum number of bytes allowed in individual messages on this SAF agent. The message size includes the message body, any user-defined properties, and the user-defined JMS header fields: JMSCorrelationID and JMSType. The maximum message size is only enforced for the initial production of a message. Messages that are redirected to an error destination or forwarded to a member of a distributed destination are not checked for size.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Queue-a-: The maximum size of a message that is accepted from producers on this destination. The message size includes the message body, any user-defined properties, and the user-defined JMS header fields: JMSCorrelationID and JMSType. Producers sending messages that exceed the configured maximum message size for the destination receive a ResourceAllocationException. The maximum message size is only enforced for the initial production of a message. Messages that are redirected to an error destination or forwarded to a member of a distributed destination are not checked for size. For instance, if a destination and its corresponding error destination are configured with a maximum message size of 128K bytes and 64K bytes, respectively, a message of 96K bytes could be redirected to the error destination (even though it exceeds the 64K byte maximum), but a producer could not directly send the 96K byte message to the error destination.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Template: The maximum size of a message that will be accepted from producers a destination using this template. The message size includes the message body, any user-defined properties, and the user-defined JMS header fields: JMSCorrelationID and JMSType. Producers sending messages that exceed the configured maximum message size for the destination receive a ResourceAllocationException . The maximum message size is only enforced for the initial production of a message. Messages that are redirected to an error destination or forwarded to a member of a distributed destination are not checked for size. For instance, if a destination and its corresponding error destination are configured with a maximum message size of 128K bytes and 64K bytes, respectively, a message of 96K bytes could be redirected to the error destination (even though it exceeds the 64K byte maximum), but a producer could not directly send the 96K byte message to the error destination.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Topic-a-: The maximum size of a message that is accepted from producers on this destination. The message size includes the message body, any user-defined properties, and the user-defined JMS header fields: JMSCorrelationID and JMSType. Producers sending messages that exceed the configured maximum message size for the destination receive a ResourceAllocationException. The maximum message size is only enforced for the initial production of a message. Messages that are redirected to an error destination or forwarded to a member of a distributed destination are not checked for size. For instance, if a destination and its corresponding error destination are configured with a maximum message size of 128K bytes and 64K bytes, respectively, a message of 96K bytes could be redirected to the error destination (even though it exceeds the 64K byte maximum), but a producer could not directly send the 96K byte message to the error destination.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_UniformD: The maximum size of a message that is accepted from producers on this destination. The message size includes the message body, any user-defined properties, and the user-defined JMS header fields: JMSCorrelationID and JMSType. Producers sending messages that exceed the configured maximum message size for the destination receive a ResourceAllocationException. The maximum message size is only enforced for the initial production of a message. Messages that are redirected to an error destination or forwarded to a member of a distributed destination are not checked for size. For instance, if a destination and its corresponding error destination are configured with a maximum message size of 128K bytes and 64K bytes, respectively, a message of 96K bytes could be redirected to the error destination (even though it exceeds the 64K byte maximum), but a producer could not directly send the 96K byte message to the error destination.

The maximum size of a message that is accepted from producers on this destination. The message size includes the message body, any user-defined properties, and the user-defined JMS header fields: JMSCorrelationID and JMSType. Producers sending messages that exceed the configured maximum message size for the destination receive a ResourceAllocationException. The maximum message size is only enforced for the initial production of a message. Messages that are redirected to an error destination or forwarded to a member of a distributed destination are not checked for size. For instance, if a destination and its corresponding error destination are configured with a maximum message size of 128K bytes and 64K bytes, respectively, a message of 96K bytes could be redirected to the error destination (even though it exceeds the 64K byte maximum), but a producer could not directly send the 96K byte message to the error destination.
f-JoltConnectionPool-a-MaximumPoolSize-h: The maximum number of connections that can be made from this Jolt connection pool.
f-Cluster-a-MemberDeathDetectorEnabled-h: Enables faster Automatic Service Migration times with Database Leasing Basis.
f-Cluster_DatabaseLessLeasingBasis-help: Specifies the amount of time, in seconds, a server waits during or after startup to discover members that belong to the same cluster. This information is used to join or form a new cluster. The default value is 30.
f-Cluster-a-MemberWarmupTimeoutSeconds-h: Maximum number of seconds that a cluster member will wait to discover and synchronize with other servers in the cluster. Normally, the member will be able to sync in 30 seconds. If the value of this attribute is higher, that does not necessarily mean that it will take longer for the member to warmup. Instead it defines an upper bound on the time that a server will wait to sync with the servers that it has discovered. If the value is set 0, servers will not attempt to discover other running server in the cluster during server initialization.
f-any_COM-a-MemoryLoggingEnabled-help: Specifies whether this server should log memory usage.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_WatchN: The customized log message for this action.
f-JMSServer-a-MessageBufferSize-help: The amount of memory (in bytes) that this JMS server can use to store message bodies before it writes them to disk. When the JMS server writes the message bodies to disk, it clears them from memory. A value of -1 (the default) specifies that the server will automatically determine a size based on the maximum heap size of the JVM. This default will be set to either one-third the maximum heap size, or 512 megabytes, whichever is smaller.
f-SAFAgent-a-MessageBufferSize-help: The amount of memory (in bytes) that this SAF agent can use to store message bodies in memory before they are paged out to disk. A value of -1 (the default) specifies that the server will automatically determine a size based on the maximum heap size of the JVM. This default will be set to either one-third the maximum heap size, or 512 megabytes, whichever is smaller.
f-JMSServer-a-MessageCompressionOptions-: Specifies the type of message compression used when JMS message body compression is enabled for Persistent Stores and JMS Paging Stores.
f-SAFAgent-a-MessageCompressionOptions-h: Specifies the type of message compression used when JMS message body compression is enabled for Persistent Stores and JMS Paging Stores.
f-Cluster_DatabaseLessLeasingBasis-a-Mes: Sets the message delivery timeout value in milliseconds that a server waits to get a response from the remote peer before taking recovery actions. The default value is 5000.
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource_Coheren: The Coherence logs message format.
a-MessageId-itemHelp: Specifies the message ID or range of message IDs to add. Examples: 20 or 50-100.
f-any_SNMPLogFilter-a-MessageId-help: A list of message IDs or ID ranges that cause a WebLogic Server SNMP agent to generate a notification. If no IDs are specified, this filter selects all message IDs.  Example list: 20,50-100,300.
a-MessageIdPrefixEnabled-help: Indicates whether message IDs in logged messages will include a prefix. Message ids are 6 digit numeric strings that can be optionally presented in a log entry with a prefix. The prefix used by server messages is "BEA-".
a-MessageLoggingEnabled-help: Specifies whether the module logs information about the message life cycle.
a-MessageLoggingFormat-help: Defines which information about the message is logged. When specifying multiple values, enter them as a comma-separated list. The %header% and %properies% values are not case sensitive. For example, you could use "%header%,%properties%" for all the JMS header fields and user properties. However, the enumeration of individual JMS header fields and user-defined properties are case sensitive. To enumerate only individual JMS header fields you could use "%header, name, address, city, state, zip". Note: The JMSMessageID field is always logged and cannot be turned off. Therefore, if the Message Logging Format is not defined (i.e., null) or is defined as an empty string, then the output to the log file contains only the JMSMessageID of the message. Gets the message-logging-format element.
f-Cluster-a-MessageOrderingEnabled-help: Forces unicast messages to be processed in order. There are scenarios where JMS may update JNDI very frequently. It will result in a lot of messages over unicast. Due to the close proximity of messages the probability of out of order handling of messages increases which would trigger frequent state dumps. Frequent JNDI tree refresh may result in NameNotFoundException. Use this property to prevent out of order handling of messages.
f-any_SNMPLogFilter-a-MessageSubstring-h: A string that is searched for in the message text. Only messages that contain the string are selected. If a string is not specified, all messages are selected.
a-MessagesHigh-help: The upper threshold (total number of messages in this destination) that triggers logging or flow control events. The value of java.lang.Long.MAX_VALUE disables logging and flow control events for the destination.
a-MessagesLimitOverride-help: The maximum number of messages that can be stored in a topic subscription. If a new message arrives on subscriptions that have reached the specified limit, then the first-most available messages on these subscriptions will be deleted to make room for the new message. Subscription messages are immune from this deletion if they're participating in a pending transaction, have already been passed to a consumer and are awaiting acknowledgement, or if they are part of a Unit-of-Work that is still waiting to accumulate all of its messages. Note that if all messages are immune from deletion, then a new message can cause a subscription size to exceed its limit. A value of -1 means no limit override.
a-MessagesLow-help: The lower threshold (total number of messages in this destination) that triggers logging or flow control events. The value of java.lang.Long.MAX_VALUE disables logging and flow control events for the destination.
f-JMSServer-a-MessagesMaximum-help: The maximum number of messages that can be stored in this JMS server. A value of -1 removes any WebLogic Server limits.
f-SAFAgent-a-MessagesMaximum-help: The maximum message quota (total amount of messages) that can be stored in this SAF agent. The default value of -1 specifies that the server instance has no limit on the number of messages that can be stored.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Connecti: The maximum number of messages that can exist for an asynchronous session and that have not yet been passed to the message listener. When the Synchronous Prefetch Mode is enabled, this value also affects synchronous sessions with a message consumer that will prefetch messages in one server access. A value of -1 indicates that there is no limit on the number of messages. In this case, however, the limit is set to the amount of remaining virtual memory.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Quota-a-: The total number of bytes that can be stored in a destination that uses this quota. A value of zero means that no messages can be placed on a destination without exceeding the quota. A value of -1 prevents WebLogic Server from imposing a limit.
f-JMSServer-a-MessagesThresholdHigh-help: The upper threshold (number of messages stored in this JMS server) that triggers flow control and logging events. A value of -1 disables the events for this JMS server.
f-SAFAgent-a-MessagesThresholdHigh-help: The upper threshold that triggers events based on the number of messages stored in the SAF agent. The default value of -1 disables the events for this SAF agent.
f-JMSServer-a-MessagesThresholdLow-help: The lower threshold (number of messages stored in this JMS server) that triggers flow control and logging events. A value of -1 disables the events for this JMS server.
f-SAFAgent-a-MessagesThresholdLow-help: The low threshold that triggers events based on the number of messages stored in the SAF agent. A value of -1 disables the events for this SAF agent.
a-MessagingPerformancePreference-help: Controls how long destinations are willing to wait to create full batches of available messages (if at all) for delivery to consumers. At the minimum value, batching is disabled; at the default value, less-than-full batches will not wait and are delivered immediately with currently available messages; tuning higher than the default value controls the maximum wait time for additional messages before less-than-full batches are delivered to consumers. The maximum message count of a full batch is controlled by the JMS connection factory's Messages Maximum setting.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Template: Controls how long destinations that use this template are willing to wait to create full batches of available messages (if at all) for delivery to consumers. At the minimum value, batching is disabled; at the default value, less-than-full batches will not wait and are delivered immediately with currently available messages; tuning higher than the default value controls the maximum wait time for additional messages before less-than-full batches are delivered to consumers. The maximum message count of a full batch is controlled by the JMS connection factory's MessagesMaximum setting.
a-MessagingQueue-help: or use only with the JAX-RPC stack. For JAX-WS, use WebServiceBufferingMBean instead. The default value is "weblogic.wsee.DefaultQueue".
a-MessagingQueueMdbRunAsPrincipalName-la: Messaging Queue MDB Run As Principal Name
a-MessagingQueueMdbRunAsPrincipalName-he: For use only with the JAX-RPC stack. For JAX-WS, use WebServiceBufferingMBean instead.
f-WTCServer_WTCtBridgeRedirect-a-MetaDat: The name of the metadata file URL used to pass the call to the XML-to-non-XML WebLogic XML Translator (WLXT).
a-MetadataEncryptionAlgorithm-itemHelp: Specify an encryption algorithm to add to the published list.
f-any_SingleSignOnServices-a-MetadataEnc: The default list of data, key encryption algorithms to be published in a WebLogic Service Partner's metadata.
f-any_RemoteResource-a-Method-help: The HTTP method used to access the credential mapping's remote resource.
f-any_CertRevoc-a-MethodOrder-help: Determines the certificate revocation checking method order.
f-any_CertRevocCa-a-MethodOrder-help: For this CA, determines the certificate revocation checking method order. NOTE THAT omission of a specific method disables that method.
f-Cluster-a-MigrationBasis-help: Controls the mechanism used for server and service migration.
a-MigrationCheckpointIntervalSeconds-hel: The time interval, in seconds, that the checkpoint is done for the migrated transaction logs (TLOGs).
f-FileStore-a-MigrationPolicy-help: Controls migration and restart behavior of cluster-targeted JMS service artifact instances. When this setting is configured on a cluster-targeted store, it applies to all JMS artifacts that reference the store. See the migratable target settings for enabling migration and restart on migratable-targeted JMS artifacts.
f-JDBCStore-a-MigrationPolicy-help: Controls migration and restart behavior of cluster-targeted JMS service artifact instances. When this setting is configured on a cluster-targeted store, it applies to all JMS artifacts that reference the store. See the migratable target settings for enabling migration and restart on migratable-targeted JMS artifacts.
f-MessagingBridge-a-MigrationPolicy-help: Controls migration and restart behavior of cluster-targeted JMS service artifact instances. When this setting is configured on a cluster-targeted store, it applies to all JMS artifacts that reference the store. See the migratable target settings for enabling migration and restart on migratable-targeted JMS artifacts.
f-MigratableTarget-a-MigrationPolicy-hel: Defines the type of migration policy to use for the services hosted by this migratable target.
f-any_JTAMigratableTarget-a-MigrationPol: Defines the type of migration policy to use for the JTA migratable target.
f-any_TransactionLogJDBCStore-a-Migratio: Defines the type of migration policy to use for the server's Transaction log JDBC store. The default value is "Off".
a-MillisToSleepBetweenAttempts-help: Controls how long of a pause there should be between the migration attempts described in getAdditionalMigrationAttempts(). Note that this delay only happens when the service has failed to come up on every server. It does not cause any sort of delay between attempts to migrate otherwise. The default value is 300000.
a-MillisToSleepBetweenAutoMigrationAttem: Milliseconds To Sleep Between Auto Migration Attempts
f-Cluster-a-MillisToSleepBetweenAutoMigr: Controls how long of a pause there should be between the migration attempts described in AdditionalAutoMigrationAttempts. Note that this delay only happens when the server has failed to come up on every machine.
f-WebAppContainer-a-MimeMappingFile-help: The name of the file containing mime-mappings for the domain. The format of the file should be: extension=mime-type.
a-MinAlphabeticCharacters-help: Specifies the minimum number of alphabetic characters that a password must contain. Valid value for this attribute must be greater than or equal to 0.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: The minimum number of physical connections that this connection pool can contain after it is initialized.
f-Cluster_DynamicServers-a-MinDynamicClu: Specifies the minimum number of running server instances that the Elasticity Framework will attempt to keep in the dynamic cluster.
f-WTCServer_WTCLocalTuxDom-a-MinEncryptB: The minimum encryption key length (in bits) this local Tuxedo access point uses when establishing a session connection. A value of 0 indicates no encryption is used.
f-WTCServer_WTCRemoteTuxDom-a-MinEncrypt: The minimum encryption key length (in bits) this remote Tuxedo access point uses when establishing a session connection. A value of 0 indicates no encryption is used.
a-MinLowercaseCharacters-help: Specifies the minimum number of lowercase characters that a password must contain. Valid value for this attribute must be greater than or equal to 0.
a-MinNonAlphanumericCharacters-help: Specifies the minimum number of non-alphanumeric characters that a password must contain. Valid value for this attribute must be greater than or equal to 0.
a-MinNumericCharacters-help: Specifies the minimum number of numeric characters that a password must contain. Valid value for this attribute must be greater than or equal to 0.
a-MinNumericOrSpecialCharacters-help: Specifies the minimum number of numeric or special characters that a password must contain. Valid value for this attribute must be greater than or equal to 0.
a-MinPasswordLength-help: Specifies the minimum length of password, a password length must be greater than or equal to the value. Valid value for this attribute must be greater than or equal to 0.
f-AdminConsole-a-MinThreads-help: Specifies the minimum number of threads that should be available to the Administration Console. These threads are used to interact with managed servers in parallel for improved responsiveness in large domains. 5 is the smallest accepted number.
f-SelfTuning_WorkManager-a-MinThreadsCon: The name of the MinThreadsConstraint that defines the minimum number of threads allocated to resolve deadlocks.
a-MinUppercaseCharacters-help: Specifies the minimum number of uppercase characters that a password must contain. Valid value for this attribute must be greater than or equal to 0.
f-FileStore-a-MinWindowBufferSize-help: The minimum amount of data, in bytes and rounded down to the nearest power of 2, mapped into the JVM's address space per primary store file. Applies to synchronous write policies Direct-Write-With-Cache and Disabled, but only when a native wlfileio library is loaded.
f-any_DefaultFileStore-a-MinWindowBuffer: The minimum amount of data, in bytes and rounded down to the nearest power of 2, mapped into the JVM's address space per primary store file. Applies to synchronous write policies Direct-Write-With-Cache and Disabled, but only when a native wlfileio library is loaded.
a-MinimumParserPoolSize-help: Specifies the minimum number of parsers to maintain in the parser pool. The default value is 5.
f-any_DefaultAuthenticator-a-MinimumPass: Specifies the minimum number of characters required in a password.
f-JoltConnectionPool-a-MinimumPoolSize-h: The minimum number of connections to be added to this Jolt connection pool when WebLogic Server starts.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-MinimumTlsPro: Sets the minimum SSL/TLS protocol version to be used in this network channel.
f-any_SSL-a-MinimumTlsProtocolVersion-he: Sets the minimum SSL/TLS protocol version to be used in this server.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_WatchN: Indicates the minutes of the hour for the schedule. Defaults to every five minutes of the hour (*/5).
a-ModuleType-help: The type of the module (ear, jar, war, or rar).
f-any_SNMPCounterMonitor-a-Modulus-help: A value to be subtracted from the threshold value when the threshold value is crossed. If Modulus is 0, a notification is generated each time the agent polls the monitored attribute and its value still exceeds or equals the threshold value. If Modulus is larger than 0, the value of the modulus is subtracted from the threshold each time the threshold is crossed.
a-MonitoredAttributeName-help: The name of an MBean attribute to monitor. This attribute must be in the WebLogic Server MIB.
a-MonitoredMBeanName-help: The name of the MBean instance that you want to monitor. If you leave the name undefined, WebLogic Server monitors all instances of the MBean type that you specify in Monitored MBean Type.
a-MonitoredMBeanType-help: The MBean type that defines the attribute you want to monitor. Do not include the MBean suffix. For example, ServerRuntime.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_WatchN: Indicates the month for the schedule. Defaults to "*" (every month).
f-Cluster-a-MulticastAddress-help: The multicast address used by cluster members to communicate with each other. The valid range is from from 224.0.0.0 to 239.255.255.255. The default value used by WebLogic Server is 239.192.0.0. You should avoid using multicast addresses in the range x.0.0.1. This address should be unique to this cluster and should not be shared by other applications.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Template: The IP address that a topic using this template uses to transmit messages to multicast consumers.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Topic_Mu: The IP address that this topic uses to transmit messages to multicast consumers.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_UniformD: The IP address that this topic uses to transmit messages to multicast consumers.
f-Cluster-a-MulticastBufferSize-help: Specifies the multicast socket send/receive buffer size in kilobytes. The minimum and default values are 64.
f-Cluster-a-MulticastDataEncryption-help: Enables multicast data to be encrypted. Only the multicast data is encrypted. Multicast header information is not encrypted.
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource_Coheren: The IP address for the cluster multicast listener.
The port for the cluster multicast listener. Deprecated in 12.2.1. Use ClusterListenPort instead.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Connecti: The policy to use when the number of outstanding multicast messages reaches the value specified in MessagesMaximum and some messages must be discarded.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Template: The IP port that this topic using this template uses to transmit messages to multicast consumers.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Topic_Mu: The IP port that this topic uses to transmit messages to multicast consumers.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_UniformD: The IP port that this topic uses to transmit messages to multicast consumers.
f-Cluster-a-MulticastPort-help: Specifies the multicast port (between 1 and 65535) used by cluster members to communicate with each other. The default value is 7001.
f-Cluster-a-MulticastSendDelay-help: Defines the amount of time in milliseconds to delay sending message fragments over multicast in order to avoid OS-level buffer overflow. The default value is 3.
f-Cluster-a-MulticastTTL-help: Defines the number of network hops that a cluster multicast message is allowed to travel. The default value is 1, which restricts the cluster to one subnet.
a-MulticastTimeToLive-help: The number of routers that a message traverses en route to a consumer. A value of 1 limits the message to one subnet (which prevents it from traversing any routers). This value is independent of the JMSExpirationTime value.
a-MuxerClass-help: Non-blocking IO is enabled by default on the server side so the default value is weblogic.socket.NIOSocketMuxer. The Certicom SSL implementation is not supported with NIOSocketMuxer. If you need to secure internet communication, Oracle recommends enabling JSSE (Java Secure Socket Extension).
f-SystemComponent_SystemComponentStart-a: The Middleware Home directory (path on the machine running Node Manager) to use when starting this server. Specify the directory on the Node Manager machine under which all of Oracle's MW products were installed. For example, c:\Oracle\Middleware\.
f-any_ServerStart-a-MwHome-help: The Middleware Home directory (on the machine running Node Manager) to use when starting this server.
a-NMSocketCreateTimeoutInMillis-label: Node Manager Socket Create Timeout In Milliseconds
a-NMSocketCreateTimeoutInMillis-help: Specifies he timeout value to be used by NodeManagerRuntime when creating a a socket connection to the agent. Default set high as SSH agent may require a high connection establishment time. The default value is 180000. Deprecated in 12.2.1.2.
f-any_NodeManager-a-NMSocketCreateTimeou: Specifies the timeout value to be used by NodeManagerRuntime when creating a a socket connection to the agent. Default set high as SSH agent may require a high connection establishment time. The default value is 15000.
a-NMType-help: Specifies the node manager type for the server or clients on the server to use when connecting to the NodeManager instance. The default value is SSL.
f-any_COM-a-NTAuthHost-help: The address of the primary domain controller this server uses for authenticating clients. If not specified, COM clients will not be authenticated.
f-WTCServer_WTCLocalTuxDom-a-NWAddr-help: The network address and port number of this local Tuxedo access point.  Specify the address in either TCP/IP or SDP format
f-WTCServer_WTCRemoteTuxDom-a-NWAddr-hel: The network address and port number of this remote Tuxedo access point.  Specify the address in either TCP/IP or SDP format
f-any_DefaultAuthenticator-a-NameCallbac: Specifies whether the provider is allowed to get the user name from a NameCallback versus getting the user name (and identity domain) from an IdentityDomainUserCallback when the provider is configured with an identity domain.
