The default value of true resets the delivery counts on messages when they are forwarded to another distributed queue member. Note: This attribute is ignored by standalone/singleton Queues, it only applies to distributed queues.
a-ResolveDNSName-help: Resolve the listen address to use for all T3 communication. The default value is false.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCXA: Enables JTA resource health monitoring for an XA data source. When enabled, if an XA resource fails to respond to an XA call within the period specified in MaxXACallMillis, WebLogic Server marks the data source as unhealthy and blocks any further calls to the resource. This property applies to XA data sources only, and is ignored for data sources that use a non-XA driver.
f-WLSPolicies-a-ResourceID-help: The resource ID for the object(s) and action(s) to which the policy should be applied. For example, "type=<jms>, application=MyJmsModule, destinationType=queue, resource=MyQueue, action=send" is identifying the "send" action on the JMS queue "MyQueue" defined in the JMS system resource "MyJmsModule".
f-WTCServer_WTCExport-a-ResourceName-hel: The name used to identify this exported service. The combination of ResourceName and LocalAccessPoint must be unique within defined Exports. This allows you to define unique configurations having the same ResourceName.
f-WTCServer_WTCImport-a-ResourceName-hel: The name used to identify this imported service. Note that this name must be unique within defined Imports. This allows you to define unique configurations having the same Remote Name.
a-ResourceTenantTokenClaim-help: Specifies the token attribute used to get the Identity Domain for the resource from the access token. The default value is "tenant".
a-ResponseBufferingQueueJndiName-help: Specifies the JNDI name of the response buffering queue that web services should use. If this is null, the request buffering queue is used.
a-ResponseReadTimeout-help: Specifies the maximum time to wait, in seconds, for a response from the Oracle Identity Cloud Service. The default value is 60.
f-SelfTuning_WorkManager-a-ResponseTimeR: The name of the ResponseTimeRequestClass that defines the response time goal for this request class. Response time goals can be used to differentiate request classes. We do not try to meet a response time goal for an individual request. Rather we compute a tolerable waiting time for a request class by subtracting the observed average thread use time.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_WatchN: The REST method for invoking the endpoint.
a-RestartDelaySeconds-help: The number of seconds the Node Manager should wait before restarting this server. After killing a server process, the system might need several seconds to release the TCP port(s) the server was using. If Node Manager attempts to restart the Managed Server while its ports are still active, the startup attempt fails. If AutoMigration is enabled and RestartDelaySeconds is 0, the RestartDelaySeconds is automatically set to the lease time. This prevents the server from failing to restart after migration when the previous lease is still valid.
a-RestartInPlace-help: Enables a periodic automatic in-place restart of failed cluster-targeted or standalone-server-targeted JMS artifact instance(s) running on healthy WebLogic Server instances. See the migratable target settings for in-place restarts of migratable-targeted JMS artifacts. When the Restart In Place setting is configured on a store, it applies to all JMS artifacts that reference the store.
a-RestartIntervalSeconds-help: The number of seconds during which this server can be restarted, up to the number of times specified in RestartMax. The default value is 3600.
a-RestartMax-help: The number of times that the Node Manager can restart this server within the interval specified in RestartIntervalSeconds. The default value is 2.
a-RestartOnFailure-help: Specifies whether a failed service will first be deactivated and reactivated in place, instead of being migrated. The number of restart attempts is controlled by NumberOfRestartAttempts . Once these restart attempts are exhausted, the service will migrate. A restarting migratable target will deactivate all services on it in order, then reactivate them all. The default value is false.
a-RestrictUserManagementAccessPattern-it: Specifies the user name pattern to add to the list.
f-WebAppContainer-a-RestrictUserManageme: The user name patterns for the WebLogic Restrict User Management Access Servlet Filter. Specify username patterns for the WebLogic Restrict User Management Access Servlet (RestrictUserManagementAccess) filter. Username patterns consist of a string array of regular expressions. When the RestrictUserManagementAccess filter matches any of the specified regular expressions with the principal name of the user in the security context for the HTTP request of a WebLogic management application (such as WebLogic Remote Console, REST APIs, and so on), the filter will block the user from accessing the application and terminate the user session. The messages about blocked requests will appear in the server log file. The regular expression must follow the Java Pattern syntax specification.
f-any_SecureMode-a-RestrictiveJmxPolicie: Specifies whether restrictive policies will be used for JMX authorization. If secure mode is enabled and restrictive policies are enabled, then the default policies for JMX only allow MBean access to the standard WLS roles (Admin, Deployer, Operator, or Monitor).
a-ResultsTimeLimit-help: Specifies the maximum number of milliseconds to wait for results before timing out. If set to 0, there is no maximum time limit.
f-SelfTuning_WorkManager_WorkManagerShut: Whether to resume the work manager once the stuck threads are cleared.
f-WebAppContainer-a-RetainOriginalURL-he: The retain-original-url property is used in FORM based authentication scenarios. When this property is set to true, after a successful authentication, WebLogic Server will redirect back to the web resource (page/servlet) retaining the protocol (http/https) used to access the protected resource in the original request. If set to false (which is the default value), WebLogic Server will redirect back to the protected resource using the current protocol. The retain-original-url value can also be specified at per web application level in weblogic.xml. The value in weblogic.xml, if specified, overrides the domain level value.
f-any_Realm-a-RetireTimeoutSeconds-help: Specifies the retire timeout for a realm that is restarted. The old realm will be shutdown after the specified timeout period has elapsed.
a-RetransmissionExponentialBackoff-help: A boolean flag indicating that the retransmission interval will be adjusted using the exponential backoff algorithm ([Tanenbaum]). Defaults to false. Set at sequence creation time, and cannot be reset.
f-WTCServer_WTCtBridgeGlobal-a-Retries-h: The number of attempts to redirect a message before this Tuxedo queuing bridge places the message in the specified error location and logs an error.  Must be between 0 and 2147483647.
a-RetrievePrincipalFromUserDn-help: Specifies whether to retrieve the user principal from the userDN or the username attribute.
f-any_ActiveDirectoryAuthenticator-a-Ret: Specifies whether to retrieve the userAccountControl attribute from Active Directory. The default value is true.
a-RetryCount-help: The number of times a buffered request or response can be retried before it is abandoned (and moved to any error queue defined for the buffer queue).
f-any_WebServiceResiliency-a-RetryCount-: The number of times a wsdl get request can be retried before it is abandoned. Default value is zero.
a-RetryDelay-help: The amount time between retries of a buffered request and response. Note, this value is only applicable when RetryCount > 0. String value in "Duration" format. Defaults to "P0DT30S" (30 seconds).
f-WTCServer_WTCtBridgeGlobal-a-RetryDela: The minimum number of milliseconds this Tuxedo queuing bridge waits before redirecting a message after a failure. Must be between 0 and 2147483647; the default value is 10.
f-any_WebServiceResiliency-a-RetryDelay-: The amount time in milliseconds between retries . Note, this value is only applicable when RetryCount > 0. Defaults to "5000".
f-WTCServer_WTCLocalTuxDom-a-RetryInterv: The number of seconds that this local Tuxedo access point waits between automatic connection attempts to remote Tuxedo access points. Use this only when the ConnectionPolicy value is set to ON_STARTUP  The default value is 60.
f-WTCServer_WTCRemoteTuxDom-a-RetryInter: The number of seconds that this remote Tuxedo access point waits between automatic connection attempts to local Tuxedo access points. Use this only when the ConnectionPolicy value is set to ON_STARTUP  Note that when the ConnectionPolicy value is LOCAL, the RetryInterval value from the local Tuxedo access point is used. When the ConnectionPolicy value is ON_STARTUP, a value of -1 indicates 60..
a-RetryIntervalBeforeMsiMode-label: Retry Interval Before Managed Server Independence Mode
a-RetryIntervalBeforeMsiMode-help: Specified the number of seconds between the retries to contact admin server, before starting in Managed Server Independence Mode.
a-RetryIntervalSeconds-help: The amount of time, in seconds, WebLogic Server waits before attempting to verify the health of the TLOG store after a store failure has occurred. The default value is 5.
a-ReverseDNSAllowed-help: Specifies whether the server is allowed to perform reverse DNS lookups. The default value is false.
a-RMIDeserializationMaxTimeLimit-help: Sets the maximum time limit, in milliseconds, before a deserialization process is terminated. This time limit helps guard against a denial of service attack. Enter a value of 100 or greater to enable. If set to 0, the RMIDeserializationMaxTimeLimit attribute is disabled and there is no maximum time limit. The default value is 0.
a-RmiJDBCSecurity-help: The security protocol used by an RMI client to access a data source. The default value is "Secure" for new domains.
a-RoleDeploymentEnabled-help: Specifies whether this Role Mapping provider stores roles that are created while deploying a Web application or EJB.
f-any_CoherenceMemberConfig-a-RoleName-h: Specifies a name used to logically group similar members.
a-RollbackLocalTxUponConnClose-label: Rollback Local Tx Upon Conn Close
f-SystemComponent_SystemComponentStart-a: The directory that this server uses as its root directory. This directory must be on the computer that hosts the Node Manager. If you do not specify a Root Directory value, the domain directory is used by default.
f-any_ServerStart-a-RootDirectory-help: The directory that this server uses as its root directory. This directory must be on the computer that hosts Node Manager. If you do not specify a Root Directory value, the domain directory is used by default.
a-RootElementTag-help: Specifies the root element of the XML document type for which this XML registry entry is being configured. When WebLogic Server starts to parse an XML document that is identified with this root element, it uses the SAX or DOM parser factory implementation class specified by this registry entry, rather than the built-in or default, when obtaining a SAX or DOM parser.
a-RotateLogOnStartup-help: Specifies whether a server rotates its log file during its startup cycle. The default value is true in development mode and false in production mode.
f-any_DefaultAuditor-a-RotationMinutes-h: Specifies how many minutes to wait before creating a new DefaultAuditRecorder.log file. At the specified time, the audit file is closed and a new one is created.  The default value is 1440 (one day)
f-any_DefaultAuditor-a-RotationSize-help: Specifies the size limit to reach before creating a new DefaultAuditRecorder.log file. After the size limit is reached, the audit file is closed and a new one is created.
a-RotationTime-help: Determines the start time (hour and minute) for a time-based rotation sequence. At the time that this value specifies, the server renames the current log file. Thereafter, the server renames the log file at an interval that you specify in File Time Span. Note that WebLogic Server sets a threshold size limit of 500 MB before it forces a hard rotation to prevent excessive log file growth.
a-RotationType-help: Specifies the criteria for moving old log records to a separate file. The default value is by size.
a-RtexprvalueJspParamName-label: Error on JSP Param Name with Request Time Value
f-WebAppContainer-a-RtexprvalueJspParamN: Global property which determines the behavior of the JSP compiler when a jsp:param attribute "name" has a request time value. Without this property set to "true", the JSP compiler throws an error for a JSP using a request time value for the "name" attribute as mandated by the JSP 2.0 specification. This property exists for backward compatibility.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_WatchN: The expression used to evaluate the policy.

The expression type for the policy: Harvester refers to harvested data, Log refers to server log entry data, DomainLog refers to domain log entry data, and EventData refers to instrumentation event data. The default type is Harvester.
a-RuntimeCacheConfigurationUri-help: The cache configuration file used at runtime.
f-JMX-a-RuntimeMBeanServerEnabled-help: Specifies whether each server instance in the domain initializes its Runtime MBean Server, which provides access to a server's run-time MBeans and read-only configuration MBeans. The Administration Console and the WebLogic Scripting Tool use this MBean server for some (but not all) of their read operations. If RuntimeMBeanServerEnabled is true, each server starts its Runtime MBean Server during the server's startup cycle. If this attribute is false, no server instance in the domain will start its Runtime MBean Server.
a-SAFErrorHandling-help: Specifies the error handling configuration used by this SAF destination.
a-SAFRemoteContext-help: Specifies the remote context used for the imported destinations.
f-XMLRegistry-a-SAXParserFactory-help: The fully qualified name of the class that implements the SAXParserFactory interface. The javax.xml.parsers.SAXParserFactory factory API enables applications deployed to WebLogic Server to configure and obtain a SAX-based XML parser to parse XML documents.
f-any_XMLParserSelectRegistryEntry-a-SAX: Specifies the fully qualified name of the class that implements the SAXParserFactory API. When WebLogic Server begins to parse an XML document identified by either the public ID, system ID, or root element specified in this entry, and the applications specifies it wants a SAX parser, then WebLogic Server uses this implementation class when using the javax.xml.parsers.SAXParserFactory to obtain the SAX parser.
a-SNMPPort-help: The port on which you want this SNMP agent to listen for incoming requests from SNMP managers that use the UDP protocol. SNMP managers can use this port to ping the SNMP agent and request the status of specific attributes. If you target this SNMP agent to multiple server instances, and if two or more servers are running on the same computer, WebLogic Server will automatically increment this UDP port value by 1 for each agent. WebLogic Server never assigns port 162 because it is the default port that an agent uses to send notifications. In addition, if any port is already in use, WebLogic Server skips the port and assigns the next available port.
a-SNMPTrapVersion-help: The SNMP notification version that this SNMP agent generates.
a-SQLAddMemberToGroup-help: Specifies the SQL statement used to add a specific member to a group. The SQL statement requires two parameters: the group name and the group member being added.
a-SQLCreateGroup-help: Specifies the SQL statement used to create a new group. The SQL statement requirements depend on the value of Descriptions Supported. There is a minimum of one parameter, the group name. If Descriptions Supported is true, the group's description is required. The default SQL is based on the default setting of Descriptions Supported. The setting of Create Group must be updated manually if the setting of Descriptions Supported changes.
a-SQLCreateUser-help: Specifies the SQL statement used to create a new user record. The SQL statement requirements depend on the value of Descriptions Supported. There is a minimum of two parameters: a username and its associated password. If Descriptions Supported is true, the user's description is required. The default SQL is based on the default setting of Descriptions Supported. The setting of Create User must be updated manually if the setting of Descriptions Supported changes.
a-SQLGetGroupDescription-help: Specifies the SQL statement used to retrieve the description of a group. Only valid if Descriptions Supported is enabled. The SQL statement requires a single parameter for the group name and must return a resultSet containing at most a single record containing the group description.
a-SQLGetUserDescription-help: Specifies the SQL statement used to retrieve the description of a specific user. Only valid if Descriptions Supported is enabled. The SQL statement requires a single parameter for the username and must return a resultSet containing at most a single record containing the user description.
a-SQLGetUsersPassword-help: Specifies the SQL statement used to look up a user's password. The SQL statement requires a single parameter for the username and must return a resultSet containing at most a single record containing the password.
a-SQLGroupExists-help: Specifies the SQL statement used to look up a group. The SQL statement requires a single parameter for the group name and must return a resultSet containing at most a single record containing the group.
a-SQLIsMember-help: Specifies the SQL statement used to look up members of a group. The SQL statement requires two parameters: a group name and a member or group name. It must return a resultSet containing the group names that matched.
a-SQLListGroupMembers-help: Specifies the SQL statement used to list groups that have a group name with a list of wildcarded member names. The SQL statement requires two parameters: the group name and the wildcarded member name.
a-SQLListGroups-help: Specifies the SQL statement used to retrieve group names that match a wildcard The SQL statement requires a single parameter for the wildcarded group name and return a resultSet containing matching group names.
a-SQLListMemberGroups-help: Specifies the SQL statement used to look up the groups a user or group is a member of. The SQL statement requires a single parameter for the username or group name and returns a resultSet containing the names of the groups that matched.
a-SQLListUsers-help: Specifies the SQL statement used to retrieve users that match a particular wildcard search The SQL statement requires a single parameter for the wildcarded usernames and returns a resultSet containing matching usernames.
a-SQLRemoveGroup-help: Specifies the SQL statement used to remove a member from a group. The SQL statement requires a single parameter: the group name being removed.
a-SQLRemoveGroupMember-help: Specifies the SQL statement used to remove a member from a group. The SQL statement requires a single parameter: the username or group name being removed.
a-SQLRemoveGroupMemberships-help: Specifies the SQL statement used to delete a group member (either a user or group) from all groups to which it belongs. The SQL statement requires 2 parameters. Both parameters refer to the specific username or group name being removed.
a-SQLRemoveMemberFromGroup-help: Specifies the SQL statement used to remove a member from a group. The SQL statement requires two parameters: the group name and the group member being deleted from the group.
a-SQLRemoveUser-help: Specifies the SQL statement used for deleting a user. The SQL statement requires a single parameter, the username.
a-SQLSetGroupDescription-help: Specifies the SQL statement used to specify a description for a group. Only valid if Descriptions Supported attribute is enabled. The SQL statement requires two parameters: the group description and the group name.
a-SQLSetUserDescription-help: Specifies the SQL statement used to specify description for a user. Only valid if Descriptions Supported is true. The SQL statement requires two parameters: the username description and the username.
a-SQLSetUserPassword-help: Specifies the SQL statement used to set the password for a user. The SQL statement requires two parameters: the password for the user and the username.
a-SQLUserExists-help: Specifies the SQL statement used to look up a user. The SQL statement requires a single parameter for the username and must return a resultSet containing at most a single record containing the user.
f-any_ActiveDirectoryAuthenticator-a-SSL: Specifies whether SSL will be used to connect to the LDAP server.
f-any_IPlanetAuthenticator-a-SSLEnabled-: Specifies whether SSL will be used to connect to the LDAP server.
f-any_LDAPAuthenticator-a-SSLEnabled-hel: Specifies whether SSL will be used to connect to the LDAP server.
f-any_LDAPX509IdentityAsserter-a-SSLEnab: Specifies whether SSL will be used to connect to the LDAP server.
f-any_NovellAuthenticator-a-SSLEnabled-h: Specifies whether SSL will be used to connect to the LDAP server.
f-any_OpenLDAPAuthenticator-a-SSLEnabled: Specifies whether SSL will be used to connect to the LDAP server.
f-any_OracleInternetDirectoryAuthenticat: Specifies whether SSL will be used to connect to the LDAP server.
f-any_OracleUnifiedDirectoryAuthenticato: Specifies whether SSL will be used to connect to the LDAP server.
f-any_OracleVirtualDirectoryAuthenticato: Specifies whether SSL will be used to connect to the LDAP server.
f-Topology-a-SSLEnabled-help: Specifies the domain-wide value for whether the servers' SSL ListenPorts are enabled. Can be overridden at the server level. The default value is false except in secure production mode.
f-any_SSL-a-SSLRejectionLoggingEnabled-h: Indicates whether warning messages are logged in the server log when SSL connections are rejected. The default value is true.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_SAFError: Specifies the error destination when the Policy attribute is set to Redirect.
a-SafExportPolicy-help: Specifies whether a user can send messages to a destination using Store-and-Forward.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Template: Specifies whether a user can send messages to destinations that use this template using Store-and-Forward.
a-SameSiteFilterCookieSetting-itemHelp: Specify a cookie setting to add to the list. The setting specifies a match for the Cookie name using a regular expression, a value for the SameSite attribute and optionally, a secure setting for the Cookie. The regular expression follows the Java Pattern syntax specification.
f-WebAppContainer-a-SameSiteFilterCookie: The HTTP Cookie configuration for the WebLogic HTTP SameSite Java EE Servlet Filter. The Cookie configuration specifies a String array of settings. Each setting specifies a match for the Cookie name using a regular expression, a value for the SameSite attribute and optionally, a secure setting for the Cookie. The regular expression follows the Java Pattern syntax specification.
f-WebAppContainer-a-SameSiteFilterSecure: The Secure Channel configuration specifies if a secure channel is required when setting the SameSite Cookie attribute where the Secure attribute is also set to true for the specific Cookie. By default, the Secure attribute setting will be applied for any channel as the user agent may reside in front of a proxy or load balancer when accessing resources.
a-SameSiteFilterUserAgentRegEx-label: SameSite Filter User Agent Regular Expressions
a-SameSiteFilterUserAgentRegEx-itemLabel: SameSite Filter User Agent Regular Expression
a-SameSiteFilterUserAgentRegEx-itemHelp: Specifies a user agent regular expression to add to the list.
f-WebAppContainer-a-SameSiteFilterUserAg: The User Agent configuration specifies a String array of regular expressions. When the WebLogic HTTP SameSite filter matches any of these expressions with the HTTP User-Agent header value, then the Cookie settings will be applied for the HTTP request. The regular expression follows the Java Pattern syntax specification. By default, there are no expressions, thus the SameSite Cookie settings are applied for all requests.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_Harves: The interval, in milliseconds, between samples.  The default value is 300000.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_WatchN: Indicates the number of instances to scale by when the action is invoked.
Indicates the number of instances to scale by when the action is invoked.
a-ScatteredReadsEnabled-help: Enables scattered reads over NIO socket channels. Enabling this attribute increases efficiency during I/O in environments with high network throughput and should be used only when configuring a WebLogic domain for Oracle Exalogic.
f-XMLRegistry-a-SchemaFactory-help: The fully qualified name of the class that implements the SchemaFactory interface. The javax.xml.validation.SchemaFactory factory API enables applications deployed to WebLogic Server to configure and obtain a Schema object used to validate XML document using schema.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-SDPEnabled-he: Enables Socket Direct Protocol (SDP) on this channel. Enable this attribute when configuring session replication enhancements for Managed Servers in a WebLogic cluster for Oracle Exalogic. SDP is removed from JDK11. Deprecated in 14.1.1.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_WatchN: Indicates the second(s) of the minute for the schedule. Defaults to "0" (at the "0" second of each minute).
a-SecondsBetweenRestarts-help: Specifies the amount of time, in seconds, to wait in between attempts to restart a failed service instance. The default value is 30.
f-MigratableTarget-a-SecondsBetweenResta: Specifies how many seconds to wait in between attempts to restart the failed migratable target. The default value is 30.
f-any_JTAMigratableTarget-a-SecondsBetwe: Specifies how many seconds to wait in between attempts to restart the failed migratable target. The default value is 30.
a-SecondsToTrustAnIdlePoolConnection-lab: Seconds To Trust An Idle Pool Connection
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: The number of seconds within a connection use that WebLogic Server trusts that the connection is still viable and will skip the connection test, either before delivering it to an application or during the periodic connection testing process. This option is an optimization that minimizes the performance impact of connection testing, especially during heavy traffic.
f-Cluster-a-SecureClusterBroadcastEnable: Servers in a cluster broadcast messages to each other using either unicast or multicast. If a broadcast channel is defined then cluster members broadcast messages using the named Network Access Point (NAP). If no broadcast channel is defined and secured cluster broadcast is enabled then messages will be sent over SSL using the default secured channel. However, this added security for broadcasting cluster messages comes with a significant cluster performance degradation. It should only be enabled if security is of greater concern than performance degradation. If secure cluster broadcast is not enabled then messages will be sent using the default channel. The default value for this attribute is true if all cluster members have SSL enabled, and either secure mode is enabled. Otherwise, the default is false.
f-NMProperties-a-SecureListener-help: If set to true, use the SSL listener, otherwise use the plain socket.
f-any_SecureMode-a-SecureModeEnabled-hel: Specifies whether the domain will run in secure mode. In secure mode, the configuration defaults are those recommended for securing a domain. The authorization policies for JNDI and MBean access are more restrictive in secure mode. In addition, WLS will validate the domain configuration and log warnings and errors for any insecure settings. Secure mode requires the domain to be in production mode.
f-Cluster-a-SecureReplicationEnabled-hel: Servers in a cluster replicate session data. If a replication channel is defined then the session data will be sent using the replication channel protocol and secured replication settings will be ignored. If no replication channel is defined and secured replication is enabled then session data for in-memory replication will be sent over SSL using the default secured channel. However, this added security for replication traffic comes with a significant cluster performance degradation. It should only be enabled if security is of greater concern than performance degradation. The default value for this attribute is true if all cluster members have SSL enabled, and either secure mode is enabled or no plaintext replication channel is available. Otherwise, the default is false.
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource_Coheren: Specify whether secured production mode is enabled. When it is not set, Coherence inherits the Secured Production Mode from WebLogic. Once Coherence Secured Production Mode is specified (Yes or No), then Coherence will no longer inherit the mode from WebLogic.
f-WTCServer_WTCLocalTuxDom-a-Security-he: The type of application security enforced. NONE means that no security is used. APP_PW means that password security is enforced when a connection is established from a remote domain; the application password is defined in the WTCResourcesMBean. DM_PW means that the domain password security is enforced when a connection is established from a remote domain; the domain password is defined in the WTCPasswordsMBean.
f-JoltConnectionPool-a-SecurityContextEn: Indicates whether this Jolt connection pool passes the connection pool's security context (user name, password and other information) from the WebLogic Server user to the Tuxedo domain. If you enable the connection pool to pass the security context, you must start the Jolt Service Handler (JSH) with the -a option. When the JSH gets a message with the caller's identity, it calls impersonate_user() to get the appkey for the user. JSH caches the appkey, so the next time the caller makes a request, the appkey is retrieved from the cache and the request is forwarded to the service. A cache is maintained by each JSH, which means that there will be a cache maintained for all the session pools connected to the same JSH. You must enable Security Context if Tuxedo requires secured connections.
f-Application-a-SecurityDDModel-help: The security model that is used to secure a deployed module. To set this value, you can use the weblogic.Deployer command-line tool, the Deployment Assistant in the Administration Console, the WebLogic Scripting Tool (WLST), or another JMX client. If you deploy a module using one of the previously mentioned tools and you do not specify a security model value, the module is secured with the security realm's default model. If you deploy a module by modifying the domain's config.xml file and restarting the server, and if you do not specify a security model value for the module in config.xml, the module is secured with the DDOnly model, which is the default value of this AppDeploymentMBean attribute.
f-any_Realm-a-SecurityDDModel-help: Specifies the default security model for Web applications or EJBs that are secured by this security realm. You can override this default during deployment.
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource_Coheren: Control the use of the Coherence security framework.
a-SecurityInteropMode-help: Specifies the security mode of the communication channel used for XA calls between servers that participate in a global transaction. All server instances in a domain must have the same security mode setting. In default mode, the transaction coordinator makes calls using the kernel identity over an admin channel if it is enabled, and anonymous otherwise. Man-in-the-middle attacks are possible if the admin channel is not enabled. In performance mode, the transaction coordinator makes calls using anonymous at all times. This implies a security risk since a malicious third party could then try to affect the outcome of transactions using a man-in-the-middle attack.
f-any_SNMPProxy-a-SecurityLevel-help: The security level that the proxied SNMP agent expects for the specified security name.
f-any_SNMPTrapDestination-a-SecurityLeve: Specifies the security protocols that the SNMP agent uses when sending SNMPv3 responses or notifications to the SNMP manager that this trap destination represents. Requires you to specify a security name for this trap destination.
f-any_SNMPProxy-a-SecurityName-help: The user name on whose behalf the WebLogic SNMP agent forwards v3 requests. If not specified, the request is forwarded as a v1 request. If you specify a security name, you must also specify a security level that is equal to or lower than the security level that is configured for communication between the WebLogic SNMP agent and SNMP managers. For example, if the WebLogic SNMP agent requires incoming SNMPv3 requests to use the authentication protocol but no privacy protocol, the security level for this proxy must be either Authentication Only or None. Note that if you want to use the authorization or privacy protocols, you must configure credential mapping in the WebLogic Server security realm. The WebLogic SNMP agent cannot forward or pass through the credentials that are contained in SNMPv3 requests from SNMP managers. Instead, the agent authenticates and performs other security operations on incoming requests, and then constructs a new request to forward to a proxied agent.
f-any_SNMPTrapDestination-a-SecurityName: Specifies the user name that the WebLogic Server SNMP agent encodes into SNMPv3 responses or notifications. Requires you to create a credential map for this user name in the WebLogic Server security realm. The credential map contains an authentication password and an optional privacy password for this user. The user name and passwords must match the credentials required by the SNMP manager that this trap destination represents.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Connecti: The security policy used for the connection factory. The default security policy is Thread-Based.
f-any_ServerStart-a-SecurityPolicyFile-h: The security policy file (directory and filename on the machine running Node Manager) to use when starting this server.
f-MessagingBridge-a-Selector-help: The filter for messages that are sent across the messaging bridge instance. Only messages that match the selection criteria are sent across the messaging bridge. For queues, messages that do not match the selection criteria are left behind and accumulate in the queue. For topics, messages that do not match the connection criteria are dropped.
a-SelfTuningThreadPoolSizeMax-label: Self Tuning Thread Pool Size Max
a-SelfTuningThreadPoolSizeMax-help: Sets the maximum thread pool size of the self-tuning thread pool. The self-tuning thread pool starts with the default size of 1. It grows and shrinks automatically as required. Setting this attribute changes the default maximum pool size. The active thread count will never increase beyond this value. This value defines the maximum number of threads permitted in the server. Note that the server will add threads only if it improves throughput. Measurements are taken every two seconds and the decision to increase or decrease the thread count is based on the current throughput measurement versus past values. This attribute is used only when setUse81StyleExecuteQueues is turned off which is the default. Thew default value is 400.
a-SelfTuningThreadPoolSizeMin-label: Self Tuning Thread Pool Size Min
a-SelfTuningThreadPoolSizeMin-help: Set the minimum thread pool size of the self-tuning thread pool. The self-tuning thread pool starts with the default size of 1. It grows and shrinks automatically as required. Setting this attribute changes the default minimum pool size. The thread count will never shrink below this value. It can add threads to improve throughput but will never decrease below the set minimum. This attribute is used only when setUse81StyleExecuteQueues is turned off which is the default.
a-SendAutomaticTrapsEnabled-help: Specifies whether this SNMP agent sends automatically generated notifications to SNMP managers.
a-SendServerHeaderEnabled-help: Indicates whether this server instance includes its name and WebLogic Server version number in HTTP response headers. The default value is false.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Connecti: The maximum length of time, in milliseconds, that a sender will wait when there isn't enough available space (no quota) on a destination to accommodate the message being sent. The default time is 10 milliseconds. A value of 0 indicates that the sender does not want to wait for space.
a-SequenceExpiration-help: This is the maximum lifetime of a sequence. If this limit is reached before the sequence naturally completes, it will be forcibly terminated. String value in "Duration" format. Defaults to "P1D" (1 day). Set at sequence creation time, and cannot be reset.
f-AllowList-a-SerialPropFilePollingInter: Specifies the polling interval, in seconds, for finding the serial properties file in the filesystem.
a-SerializeEnlistmentsGCIntervalMillis-h: The time interval, in milliseconds, at which internal objects used to serialize resource enlistment are cleaned up.
a-ServerAffinityEnabled-help: Specifies whether a server instance that is load balancing consumers or producers across multiple members destinations of a distributed destination, will first attempt to load balance across any other physical destinations that are also running on the same server instance.
a-ServerBackoffEnabled-help: Specifies whether to backoff and retry requests when Oracle Identity Cloud Service returns a response that too many requests are being processed in a specific time window. The default value is true.
a-ServerCipherSuitesOrderEnabled-help: Indicates whether to honor the server cipher suites preference. The default value is true.
a-ServerGroupTargetingLimits-keyHelp: The name of the server group
a-ServerGroupTargetingLimits-valueHelp: The dynamic cluster targets for the server group
a-ServerGroupTargetingLimits-help: A map of template-defined server groups to targets used to target FMW Infrastructure resources to servers or clusters.
a-ServerKeyStores-help: Specifies the domain-wide default value for the per-server KeyStores attribute. This value can be overridden at the server level. The server KeyStores attribute selects the set of Identity and Trust keystores the server will use. The default value is "DemoIdentityAndDemoTrust".
a-ServerLifeCycleTimeoutVal-help: Number of seconds a force shutdown operation waits before timing out and killing itself. If the operation does not complete within the configured timeout seconds, the server will shutdown automatically if the state of the server at that time was SHUTTING_DOWN. A value of 0 means that the server will wait indefinitely for life cycle operation to complete. The default value is 30 unless in secure production mode where it is 120.
a-ServerLoggingBridgeAtRootLoggerEnabled: Server Logging Bridge At Root Logger Enabled
a-ServerLoggingBridgeUseParentLoggersEna: Server Logging Bridge Use Parent Loggers Enabled
a-ServerMigrationHistorySize-help: Specifies the history size of server migrations. A value of -1 indicates that the history size is unlimited. The default value is 100.
f-Cluster_DynamicServers-a-ServerNamePre: The server name prefix is used to specify the naming convention when creating server names. When the server name prefix is defined, server names are calculated with the specified prefix followed by the index starting with the value specified by ServerNameStartingIndex.
f-Cluster_DynamicServers-a-ServerNameSta: Specifies the starting index to use in server names. Server names are calculated with the prefix specified in ServerNamePrefix followed by an index starting with the value specified in this attribute.
a-ServerNotAvailableCounterInterval-help: Specifies the interval, in seconds, that the count of authentication failures caused by the Oracle Identity Cloud Service not being available are logged to the server log. Setting to zero (0) or negative value turns off the logging of the count. The default value is 300.
f-any_SSL-a-ServerPrivateKeyAlias-help: Specifies the server's private key in the keystore. This private key is associated with the server's digital certificate.
f-any_SSL-a-ServerPrivateKeyPassPhraseEn: The passphrase used to retrieve the server's private key from the keystore. This passphrase is assigned to the private key when it is generated.
a-ServerStartMode-help: The mode to use when creating a new domain. The default value is development mode.
f-Server-a-ServerTemplate-help: The template used to configure this server.
f-Cluster_DynamicServers-a-ServerTemplat: The server template used to create dynamic servers.
a-Servers-itemHelp: Add a server to the list.
a-Servers-help: Specifies the list of servers to which the ODL logging.xml is written
f-Cluster-a-ServiceActivationRequestResp: Specifies the maximum time, in milliseconds seconds, for services to wait for response from cluster members.
f-Cluster-a-ServiceAgeThresholdSeconds-h: Defines the number of seconds by which the age of two conflicting services must differ before one is considered older than the other. The default value is 180.
a-ServiceMigrationHistorySize-help: Specifies the history size of service migrations. A value of -1 indicates that the history size is unlimited. The default value is 100.
f-any_SingleSignOnServices-a-ServiceProv: Specifies whether the Artifact binding is enabled for the Service Provider. The default value is true.
Specifies whether the local site is enabled for the Service Provider role. This attribute must be enabled in order to publish the metadata file. The default value is false.
Specifies whether the POST binding is enabled for the Service Provider. The default value is true.
Specifies the preferred binding type for endpoints of Service Provider services. The default value is "None".
The binding used by the Service Provider to send SAML Single Logout Requests. The default value is "HTTP/Redirect".
Specifies whether Single Logout is enabled for the Service Provider. The default value is true.
a-ServiceProviderSingleLogoutRedirectUri: Service Provider Single Logout Redirect URIs
Service Provider Single Logout Redirect URI
Specify an allowed redirect URI after logout.
f-any_SingleSignOnServices-a-ServiceProv: The list of allowed redirect URIs to be used by the initiating Service Provider for after Logout redirection.
f-SAFAgent-a-ServiceType-help: The type of service that this SAF agent provides. JMS requires only a Sending agent on the sending side for messages. Whereas, Web Services Reliable Messaging requires both a Sending and Receiving agent for messages.
f-WebAppContainer-a-ServletAuthenticatio: ServletAuthenticationFormURL is used for backward compatibility with previous releases of WebLogic Server. If ServletAuthenticationFormURL is set to true (default), then ServletAuthentication.getTargetURLForFormAuthentication() and HttpSession.getAttribute(AuthFilter.TARGET_URL) will return the URL of the protected target resource. If set to false, the above APIs will return the URI of the protected target resource. By default, the value is set to true.(new method added in 9.0.0.1).
f-WebAppContainer-a-ServletReloadCheckSe: Controls how often WebLogic Server checks for modifications to servlets and reloads them if changes are detected.
f-Cluster-a-SessionFlushInterval-help: Defines the interval in seconds until HTTP Sessions are periodically flushed to the backup cluster to dump session state on disk.
f-Cluster-a-SessionFlushThreshold-help: When number of sessions to be flushed reaches this threshold limit, sessions will be flushed to the backup cluster before the flush interval. This helps the server to flush sessions faster under load. The default value is 10000.
f-Cluster-a-SessionLazyDeserializationEn: Enables increased efficiency with session replication by not deserializing the secondary copy of the session until it is needed.
a-SessionReplicationOnShutdownEnabled-he: Indicates if session replication on server shutdown is enabled. During server shutdown, any active http and ejb stateful session states will be replicated to a secondary server (if available) in the cluster. The default value is false.
f-Cluster-a-SessionStateQueryProtocolEna: Indicates if session state query protocol is enabled. The Session State Query protocol will query the local cluster for the location of a session state instance if a request arrives at a server that is neither the primary or secondary server.
f-Cluster-a-SessionStateQueryRequestTime: Specifies the maximum time, in seconds, for session state query request to wait for response from cluster members.
f-AdminConsole-a-SessionTimeout-help: Specifies the Session Timeout value (in seconds) for Administration Console.
f-RemoteConsoleHelper-a-SessionTimeout-h: Specifies the Session Timeout value (in seconds) for the Remote Console Helper.
f-MailSession-a-SessionUsername-help: The username to be used to create an authenticated JavaMail Session, using a JavaMail Authenticator instance; if this is not set, it will be assumed that the Session is not to be authenticated.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_WatchN: The severity of the log message recorded by this action.

The severity level of the actions sent when this policy evaluates to true. When set, this level overrides the default value provided in the parent MBean. However, if no severity level is set (null), the value provided in the parent MBean is returned.
The default action severity level for all policies. When a policy triggers, the severity level is delivered with the action.
f-any_DefaultAuditor-a-Severity-help: The severity level at which auditing is initiated. Severity levels are ranked in this order: 1. INFORMATION, 2. WARNING, 3. ERROR, 4. SUCCESS, 5. FAILURE. If you select a given severity level, all events of that level or more will be audited. For example, if you set the severity to ERROR, then all FAILURE, SUCCESS, and ERROR events will be audited, but WARNING and INFORMATION events will not. You can instead set the severity to CUSTOM and then enable the specific severity level events you want to audit.
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource_Coheren: The logging severity level for Coherence logs.
f-any_SNMPLogFilter-a-SeverityLevel-help: The minimum severity of a message that causes a WebLogic Server SNMP agent to generate a notification.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Quota-a-: Indicates whether this quota is shared by multiple destinations that refer to it. If Shared is enabled (the default), all destinations referring to the quota object compete for resources the resources defined by that object. If one destination consumes a large number of messages or bytes, then this will prevent other destinations from obtaining quota. If Shared is disabled, the quota object behaves as a template. Each destination referring to the quota object gets its own internal instance of the object for tracking quota. Destinations within the same JMS module may share quotas in any way they want. However, quota sharing only takes place for destinations within the same JMS server. In other words, if destinations X and Y both share the same quota Q, and the quota Q has Shared enabled, then X and Y will only share quota if both are deployed to the same JMS server.
a-SharedCapacityForWorkManagers-help: Total number of requests that can be present in the server. This includes requests that are enqueued and those under execution. The server performs a differentiated denial of service on reaching the shared capacity. A request with higher priority will be accepted in place of a lower priority request already in the queue. The lower priority request is kept waiting in the queue till all high priority requests are executed. Further enqueues of the low priority requests are rejected right away. The default value is 65536.
f-any_NodeManager-a-ShellCommand-help: Specifies the local command line to use when invoking SSH or RSH node manager functions.
f-WebAppContainer-a-ShowArchivedRealPath: Global property to determine the behavior of getRealPath() for archived web applications. When this property is set to "true", getRealPath() will return the canonical path of the resource files.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: The percentage of the number of available connections to shrink from current pool capacity to the maximum of the configured minimum capacity, the current number of in-use connections or the running average (if configured).
The number of seconds to wait before shrinking a connection pool that has incrementally increased to meet demand. When set to 0, shrinking is disabled.
The amount of time to maintain a running average of the number of in-use connections. Shrinking ignores the running average when set to 0.

Specifies the number of additional number of connections to maintain above the current connection usage or the running average when shrinking. For example, a value of 20 indicates that the pool will not shrink lower than the current usage or running average plus 20%.
a-ShutdownGracePeriod-help: Specifies how long the server should wait for active transactions to complete before allowing shutdown.
f-any_SingleSignOnServices-a-SignAuthnRe: Specifies whether authentication requests must be signed. If set, all outgoing authentication requests are signed. The default value is false.
a-SignaturePreferX509Certificate-help: If the optional X.509 certificate chain ("x5c claim") is available from the JSON Web Key Set, this attribute specifies whether the public key obtained from the X.509 certificate in the supplied chain is used during the verification of the token signature.
a-SigningKeyAlias-help: Specifies the alias used to retrieve from the keystore the key that is used to sign assertions.
a-SigningKeyPassPhraseEncrypted-help: Specifies the credential (password) used to retrieve from the keystore the keys used to sign assertions.
f-any_CertificateManagement-a-SinglePurp: Whether the Domain Certificates Issuer should generate separate, single-purpose certificates for different purposes (server authentication, client authentication, signing and encryption), or generate one certificate that supports all those purposes.
a-SingleSignonDisabled-help: Specifies whether to disable single sign-on. The default value is false.
f-Cluster-a-SingletonSQLQueryHelper-help: The Singleton Services uses certain SQL commands to talk to the database. By default, the commands are obtained from a WebLogic-supplied implementation of weblogic.cluster.singleton.QueryHelper. If the database is not supported, or the SQL needs to be more optimized or altered for a particular use case, one can change the class used by setting this variable. The classname provided will be loaded at boot time, and used to execute the various SQL queries.
f-Cluster-a-SingletonServiceRequestTimeo: Specifies the maximum time, in milliseconds, for service activation requests will wait for response from cluster members. A value of 0 means that the request will wait indefinitely to complete. The default value is 30000.
a-SitConfigPollingInterval-help: Specifies the polling interval in seconds for finding the situational config file in the filesystem. The default value is 5.
a-SitConfigRequired-help: Specifies whether situational config files are required and WebLogic Server should fail to boot if situational config files are not present. The default value is false.
f-Cluster-a-SiteName-help: Specifies the name of the site with which this cluster is associated.
f-any_CoherenceMemberConfig-a-SiteName-h: Specifies the name of the geographic site where this member is hosted.
f-Topology-a-SiteName-help: The name of the site with which the domain is associated. Deprecated in 12.2.1.4.
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource_Coheren: The snapshot directory for the default persistence environment. If no value is specified, the directory which will be used is coherence/snapshot sub-directory under Domain Home directory.
a-SnmpAccessForUserMBeansEnabled-label: SNMP Access For User MBeans Enabled
a-SnmpAccessForUserMBeansEnabled-help: Configures this SNMP agent to provide read-only access to MBean types that you have created and registered (custom MBeans). If you enable this access, when you register a custom MBean in a WebLogic Server MBeanServer, this SNMP agent dynamically updates a runtime MIB module that WebLogic Server maintains for custom MBeans. For each custom MBean type, WebLogic Server adds a table to the MIB module. For each instance of the custom MBean, it adds a table row. While WebLogic Server does not persist the MIB as a file or other data structure, the OIDs in the MIB remain constant across server sessions. The MIB module for custom MBeans is managed by a subAgent. Its master agent is this WebLogic Server SNMP agent and it communicates with the master agent through the AgentX port.
a-SnmpEngineId-help: An identifier for this SNMP agent that is unique amongst all other SNMP agents in the current WebLogic Server domain. If you use SNMPv3 to send messages to this SNMP agent, you must specify the SNMP engine ID when you configure the SNMP manager. For an SNMP agent on an Administration Server, the default value is the name of the WebLogic Server domain. For an agent on a Managed Server, the default is the name of the server.
a-SocketBufferSizeAsChunkSize-label: Socket Buffer Size As Chunk Size
a-SocketBufferSizeAsChunkSize-help: Specifies whether the server's buffer size for sending or receiving data through a raw socket should be set to 4KB. Otherwise, the server does not impose a limit to the buffer size and defers to the operating system. This option is useful only on some operating systems for improving performance. It should be disabled in most environments so the default value is false.
a-SocketReaders-help: Specifies the number of socket reader threads. The default is -1.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Destinat: The direction (Ascending or Descending) in which this key will sort messages. Selecting the Ascending option for the JMSMessageID property implies a FIFO (first in, first out) sort order (the default for destinations). Select the Descending option for a LIFO (last in, first out) sort order.
a-SourceAccessPoint-help: The name of the local or remote access point where the source is located.
f-MessagingBridge-a-SourceDestination-he: The source destination from which this messaging bridge instance reads messages.
f-WTCServer_WTCtBridgeRedirect-a-SourceN: The name of a source queue or service. Specifies a JMS queue name, a Tuxedo queue name, or the name of a Tuxedo service.
a-SourcePath-help: The path to the source of the deployable unit on the Administration Server.
f-Application-a-SourcePath-help: The path to the source of the deployable unit on the Administration Server. If the source path is relative, it is resolved relative to InstallDir/app if InstallDir is not null; otherwise, it is resolved relative to the domain root.
f-WTCServer_WTCtBridgeRedirect-a-SourceQ: The name of the Qspace for a source location.
f-any_NetworkAccessPoint-a-SsLv2HelloEna: Indicate whether SSLv2Hello is enabled in a network channel.
a-SslEnabled-help: Specifies whether the TLS/SSL protocol is used when connecting to the Oracle Identity Cloud Service.
f-WTCServer_WTCLocalTuxDom-a-SslProtocol: The protocol version of the SSL connection this local access point uses when establishing a SSL connection.
f-WTCServer_WTCRemoteTuxDom-a-SslProtoco: The protocol version of the SSL connection this remote access point uses when establishing a SSL connection with specific local access point.
f-AdminConsole-a-SsoLogoutUrl-help: Specifies the log out URL for the Administration Console in a single sign-on (SSO) environment. Only needed when you use the Console with an SSO provider that requires a log out URL so that it can clean up its SSO session state. See the SSO provider documentation for details on the URL value.
f-any_SingleSignOnServices-a-SsoSigningK: The keystore alias for the key to be used when signing documents. The key is used to generate signatures on all the outgoing documents, such as authentication requests and responses. If you do not specify an alias, the server's configured SSL private key alias from the server's SSL configuration is used by default. If this value is not set, and the server's KeyStores setting is DomainKeystores, then the default Domain Keystores signing/encryption alias is returned.

The passphrase used to retrieve the local site's SSO signing key from the keystore. If you do not specify a keystore alias and passphrase, the server's configured private key alias and private key passphrase from the server's SSL configuration is used by default.
a-StacktraceDepth-help: Determines the number of stacktrace frames to display on standard out. All frames are displayed in the log file. A value of -1 means all frames are displayed.
a-StagingDirectoryName-help: The directory path on the Managed Server where all staged (prepared) applications are placed. If an absolute directory name is not specified, the path is relative to the root directory "/". Once configured, you cannot change the staging directory name. Remove all applications from the server prior to changing this attribute. The default staging directory is "stage", relative to the server root.
a-StagingMode-help: Specifies whether a deployment's files are copied from a source on the Administration Server to the Managed Server's staging area during application preparation. Staging mode for an application can only be set the first time the application is deployed. Once the staging mode for an application is set, it cannot be changed while the application is configured in the domain. The only way to change the staging mode is to undeploy and then redeploy the application. This attribute overrides the server's staging mode.
f-Server-a-StagingMode-help: Specifies the mode that specifies whether an application's files are copied from a source on the Administration Server to the Managed Server's staging area during application preparation. During application preparation, the application's files are copied from the source on the Administration Server to the Managed Server's staging area. If you specify nostage or external_stage, the copy will not occur. This is useful when the staging area is a shared directory, already containing the application files, or if this is a single server domain. The administrator must ensure that the Managed Server's staging directory is set appropriately. Deployment errors will result if the application is not available during the preparation or activation of the application. Each application can override the staging mode specified here.
f-ServerTemplate-a-StagingMode-help: Specifies the mode that specifies whether an application's files are copied from a source on the Administration Server to the Managed Server's staging area during application preparation. During application preparation, the application's files are copied from the source on the Administration Server to the Managed Server's staging area. If you specify nostage or external_stage, the copy will not occur. This is useful when the staging area is a shared directory, already containing the application files, or if this is a single server domain. The administrator must ensure that the Managed Server's staging directory is set appropriately. Deployment errors will result if the application is not available during the preparation or activation of the application. Each application can override the staging mode specified here.
f-MessagingBridge-a-Started-help: Specifies the initial operating state of a targeted messaging bridge instance.
a-StartupMode-help: The state in which this server should be started. If you specify STANDBY, you must also enable the domain-wide administration port. If you specify INACTIVE, the server will not be started and is just a placeholder server. To bring up this server we need to change startupMode to other value. In the RUNNING state, a server offers its services to clients and can operate as a full member of a cluster. In the ADMIN state, the server is up and running, but available only for administration operations, allowing you to perform server and application-level administration tasks without risk to running applications. In the STANDBY state, a server instance does not process any request; its regular Listen Port is closed. The Administration Port is open. It only accepts life cycle commands that transition the server instance to either the RUNNING or the SHUTDOWN state. Other Administration requests are not accepted. A STANDBY server's only purpose is to resume into the RUNNING state quickly; it saves server startup time.
a-StartupTimeout-help: Timeout value in seconds for server start and resume operations in seconds. If the server fails to start in the timeout period, it will force shutdown. The default value of 0 means that the server will wait indefinitely for the operation to complete.
a-StartupTimeoutNumOfThreadDump-label: Startup Timeout Number Of Thread Dumps
a-StartupTimeoutNumOfThreadDump-help: Sets total number of obtained thread dump when StartupTimeout is reached. The default value is 0.
a-StartupTimeoutThreadDumpInterval-help: Sets interval time, in milliseconds, of thread dump capturing when StartupTimeout is reached. The default value is 60000.
f-NMProperties-a-StateCheckInterval-help: Specifies the interval Node Manager waits to perform a check of the server state.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: The number of prepared and callable statements stored in the cache. (This may increase server performance.) WebLogic Server can reuse statements in the cache without reloading the statements, which can increase server performance. Each connection in the connection pool has its own cache of statements. Setting the size of the statement cache to 0 turns off statement caching.
The algorithm used for maintaining the prepared statements stored in the statement cache.

The time after which a statement currently being executed will time out. StatementTimeout relies on underlying JDBC driver support. WebLogic Server passes the time specified to the JDBC driver using the java.sql.Statement.setQueryTimeout() method. If your JDBC driver does not support this method, it may throw an exception and the timeout value is ignored. A value of -1 disables this feature. A value of 0 means that statements will not time out.
a-StaticGroupDNsfromMemberDNFilter-label: Static Group DNs from Member DN Filter
a-StaticGroupDNsfromMemberDNFilter-help: An LDAP search filter that, given the distinguished name (DN) of a member of a group, returns the DNs of the static LDAP groups that contain that member.
a-StaticGroupNameAttribute-help: Specifies the attribute of a static LDAP group object that specifies the name of the group. The default value is cn.
a-StaticGroupObjectClass-help: Specifies the name of the LDAP object class that stores static groups. The default value is group.
a-StaticMemberDNAttribute-help: Specifies the attribute of the LDAP static group object that specifies the distinguished names (DNs) of the members of the group. The default value is member.
a-StdoutFilter-help: The filter configuration for log events being sent to the standard out.
a-StdoutFormat-help: The output format to use when logging to the console.
a-StdoutLogStack-help: Specifies whether to dump stack traces to the console when included in logged message.
a-StdoutSeverity-help: The minimum severity of log messages going to the standard out. Messages with a lower severity than the specified value will not be published to standard out.
f-SAFAgent-a-Store-help: The persistent disk-based file store or JDBC-accessible database for the SAF agent. If a store is not configured, the server's default store is used.
f-JMSServer-a-StoreEnabled-help: Specifies whether message persistence is supported for this JMS server. When set to true: If the JMS server has no store configured, the targeted WebLogic Server instance's default store is used to store persistent messages. If the JMS server has a store configured, then the configured store is used to store persistent messages. When set to false, then this JMS server does not support persistent messages, and instead downgrades them to non-persistent. The default value is true.
f-JMSServer-a-StoreMessageCompressionEna: Enables the JMS store to perform message body compression. When set to false, the default value, no compression is performed.
f-SAFAgent-a-StoreMessageCompressionEnab: Enables the JMS store to perform message body compression. When set to false, the default value, no compression is performed.
f-any_ServerDiagnosticConfig-a-StoreSize: Specifies the period in hours at which diagnostic store file size check will be performed. The default value is 1.
a-StoreType-help: Specifies the type of this physical store.
a-StrictOwnershipCheck-help: Whether continue to boot if cannot find the current owner of TRS to do failback. This attribute is only meaningful for servers in cluster. If true, the server will fail to boot under this situation. If false, which is the default value, the server will continue to boot without trying to do failback.
f-any_SNMPStringMonitor-a-StringToCompar: The string against which the value of the monitored attribute will be compared. A notification is generated when the criteria specified by Notify Match or Notify Differ is satisfied.
f-SelfTuning_WorkManager_WorkManagerShut: Number of stuck threads after which the WorkManager is shutdown.
f-Cluster_OverloadProtection_ServerFailu: The number of stuck threads after which the server is transitioned into FAILED state. There are options in OverloadProtectionMBean to suspend and shutdown a FAILED server. By default, the server continues to run in FAILED state. If the StuckThreadCount value is set to zero then the server never transitions into FAILED server irrespective of the number of stuck threads.
f-any_ServerFailureTrigger-a-StuckThread: The number of stuck threads after which the server is transitioned into FAILED state. There are options in OverloadProtectionMBean to suspend and shutdown a FAILED server. By default, the server continues to run in FAILED state. If the StuckThreadCount value is set to zero then the server never transitions into FAILED server irrespective of the number of stuck threads. The default value is 0.
a-StuckThreadDiagnosticImageNotification: Stuck Thread Diagnostic Image Notification Enabled
f-any_WldfBuiltinWatchConfiguration-a-St: Enables the builtin WLDF watch to capture diagnostic image notification when stuck thread is encountered. The default value is false.
a-StuckThreadThreadDumpActionCount-label: Stuck Thread Thread Dump Action Count
f-any_WldfBuiltinWatchConfiguration-a-St: Signifies the number of successive thread dumps to capture for specified stuck thread thread dump action whenever it executes.
a-StuckThreadThreadDumpActionDelaySecond: Stuck Thread Thread Dump Action Delay Seconds
f-any_WldfBuiltinWatchConfiguration-a-St: The delay, in seconds, to pause between thread dump captures. The default value is 10.
a-StuckThreadThreadDumpActionEnabled-lab: Stuck Thread Thread Dump Action Enabled
f-any_WldfBuiltinWatchConfiguration-a-St: Enable the builtin WLDF watch to capture thread dumps action when stuck thread is encountered. The default value is false.
a-StuckThreadTimerInterval-help: The number of seconds after which WebLogic Server periodically scans threads to see if they have been continually working for the configured maximum length of time. The default value is 60.
f-any_WldfBuiltinWatchConfiguration-a-St: Enable the builtin WLDF watch to capture thread dump when stuck thread is encountered.
a-SubDeploymentName-help: The name of the subdeployment to use when targeting this entity. Entities are targeted using a subdeployment with this name. The targets of the subdeployment will be the targets of this entity.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Template: The name of the subdeployment that template parameters apply to. A subdeployment with the specified name must exist in the topic or queue for the parameters to apply.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_WatchN: The subject for the mail message. If the subject is not specified, a subject is created from the action information.
f-any_CertificateManagement-a-SubjectAlt: A list of words representing the Subject Alternative Names that the Domain Certificates Issuer should include when generating a server certificate. Each word must be one of the subject name constants defined by the CertificateConfigurationConstants interface. When generating a certificate, the Certificate Management Service replaces each constant with the corresponding value(s) obtained from the target server's configuration or the host it's running on. The certificate's CN attribute will be included as a Subject Alternative Name even if it is not explicitly configured here.
f-any_CertificateManagement-a-SubjectCom: The name the Domain Certificates Issuer should use for the CN attribute of a certificate's Subject: either the local hostname (hostname) or the server's listen address (listen_address). If no listen address is configured for the server, hostname will be used instead, regardless of the value set here. The CN value will also be added as a Subject Alternative Name (even if it is not explicitly configured as a Subject Alternative Name).
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Connecti: Specifies the subscription sharing policy on this connection.
f-any_SNMPLogFilter-a-SubsystemName-item: The name of the subsystem to add to the list selected by this log filter.
f-any_SNMPLogFilter-a-SubsystemName-help: A list of subsystems whose messages are selected by this log filter. If none are specified, messages from all subsystems are selected.
f-WLDFSystemResource_WLDFResource_WatchN: The subsystem name to be assigned to the log message.
f-any_DefaultAuditor-a-SuccessAuditSever: If the Severity value is set to Custom, causes the Auditing provider to generate audit records for events with a severity level of SUCCESS.
a-SyncFilterEnabled-help: Specifies whether the synchronization filter is enabled for servlet applications deployed on the security realm.
a-SyncFilterMatchCase-help: Specifies whether the synchronization filter performs case match when comparing the session user and the remote user.
a-SyncFilterOnlyClientCertRequests-label: Sync Filter Only Client Cert Requests
a-SyncFilterOnlyClientCertRequests-help: Specifies whether the synchronization filter only filters the requests with CLIENT_CERT or CLIENT-CERT Auth Type. The default value is true.
a-SyncFilterPreferHeader-help: Specifies whether the synchronization filter looks into the requests header before looking at the token for the remote user and tenant. This attribute is used only when the synchronization filter is enabled for requests with all authentication types.
a-SyncFilterUserHeaderName-itemHelp: Specifies an HTTP header name to add to the list.
a-SyncFilterUserHeaderName-help: Specifies the names of HTTP headers sent on requests that the synchronization filter uses to look for remote user information.
f-WebAppContainer-a-SynchronizedSessionT: Indicates whether to also invalidate all the other sessions when one of the sessions that share the same ID expires.
f-any_ServerDiagnosticConfig-a-Synchrono: Specifies the instrumentation events persistence policy. If true, events will be persisted synchronously within the same thread. If false, events will be queued up to be persisted in a separate thread.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Connecti: Specifies whether a synchronous consumer will prefetch messages (that is, messages sent from the server to the client) in one server access.
f-FileStore-a-SynchronousWritePolicy-hel: The disk write policy that determines how the file store writes data to disk. This policy also affects the JMS file store's performance, scalability, and reliability. Oracle recommends Direct-Write-With-Cache which tends to have the highest performance. The default value is Direct-Write.
f-any_DefaultFileStore-a-SynchronousWrit: The disk write policy that determines how the file store writes data to disk. This policy also affects the JMS file store's performance, scalability, and reliability. Oracle recommends Direct-Write-With-Cache which tends to have the highest performance. The default value is Direct-Write.
f-any_WebServicePhysicalStore-a-Synchron: Specifies the algorithm used when performing synchronous writes to the physical store.
a-SynthesizeAllowListEnabled-help: Specifies whether we have to synthesize the AllowList.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCDr: The system property name from which to get the value.
f-any_XMLEntitySpecRegistryEntry-a-Syste: The system ID of the external entity. When WebLogic Server is parsing an XML document and it encounters an external entity with this system ID, WebLogic Server resolves the entity (to either a local file or a URL resource) according to the values set for this Entity spec entry.
f-any_XMLParserSelectRegistryEntry-a-Sys: Specifies the system ID of the XML document type for which this XML registry entry is being configured. When WebLogic Server starts to parse an XML document that is identified with this system ID, it uses the SAX or DOM parser factory implementation class specified by this registry entry, rather than the built-in or default, when obtaining a SAX or DOM parser.
a-SystemPasswordEncrypted-help: The password required to access administrative functions on this server.
a-SystemSecurity-help: Specify the value System Security. The following variables are affected. clientCertAuthentication, clientAuthentication, identityAssertion confidentiality, integrity. The value set in this MBean would only be picked up if the value set in RTD.xml is "config".
a-TGIOPEnabled-help: Specifies whether this server supports Tuxedo GIOP (TGIOP) requests. (Requires you to configure WebLogic Tuxedo Connector (WTC) for this server.) The default value is true.
a-Target-help: The servers or clusters to which the deployment is deployed.
f-WTCServer_WTCtBridgeRedirect-a-TargetA: The name of the local or remote access point where the target is located.
f-MessagingBridge-a-TargetDestination-he: The target destination where a messaging bridge instance sends the messages it receives from the source destination.
f-WTCServer_WTCtBridgeRedirect-a-TargetN: The name of the target queue or service. Specifies a JMS queue name, a Tuxedo queue name, or the name of a Tuxedo service.
f-WTCServer_WTCtBridgeRedirect-a-TargetQ: The name of the Qspace for a target location.
a-Template-help: The JMS template from which the destination is derived. A template provides an efficient means of defining multiple destinations with similar configuration values. If a JMS template is specified, destination parameters that are set to their default values will instead inherit their values from the JMS template at run-time. However, if a JMS template is not defined, then the configuration values for the destination must be specified as part of the destination.
f-JMSServer-a-TemporaryTemplateName-help: The name of a configured JMS template that this JMS server uses to create temporary destinations. Entering a template name, requires you to specify the JMS module that contains this template. However, a template name cannot be specified if the Hosting Temporary Destinations field is disabled.
f-JMSServer-a-TemporaryTemplateResource-: The name of a JMS module that contains a template that this JMS server can use to create temporary destinations. Entering a JMS module name requires you to specify a temporary template name. However, a module name cannot be specified if the Hosting Temporary Destinations field is disabled.
a-Tenant-help: Specifies the name of the primary tenant where users and groups reside from the Oracle Identity Cloud Service. When the primary tenant is not configured, the user authentication processing must identify the tenant name.
a-TenantDataFlushInterval-help: Specifies the interval, in seconds, that the cached data for all the tenants, including the metadata and public key is flushed. Adjusting the interval impacts how long the tenant data is cached for reuse before it is updated. The default value is 0, which means that tenant data from a previous download is not cleared unless triggered by an MBean operation or configuration change.
a-TenantDataReloadEnabled-help: Specifies whether to re-load Oracle Identity Cloud Service tenant data when a token validation error occurs.
a-TenantDataReloadInterval-help: Specifies the interval, in seconds, that the Oracle Identity Cloud Service tenant data would not be removed when a token validation error occurs. Adjusting the interval impacts how long the tenant data is cached for reuse before repeated token validation errors result in a tenant data re-load. The default value is 300.
a-TenantHeaderName-itemHelp: Specifies an HTTP header name to add to the list.
a-TenantHeaderName-help: Specifies the names of HTTP headers sent on requests to the Oracle Identity Cloud Service that are used to determine the tenancy during authentication.
a-TenantHostNameTemplate-help: Specifies the tenant-based host name, in Fully Qualified Domain name (FQDN) format, comprised of a tenant name and a host name. This attribute contains the tokens, such as {%tenant}.{%host}, that are replaced with the actual values.
a-TenantName-itemHelp: Specifies a tenant name to add to the list.
a-TenantName-help: Specifies the list of allowable tenant names consumed from the Oracle Identity Cloud Service. When no tenant names are configured, any tenant from the Oracle Identity Cloud Service is accessible.
a-TenantTokenClaim-help: Specifies the token attribute used to get the Identity Domain from the token. The default value is "user_tenantname".
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: Enables WebLogic Server to test a connection before giving it to a client. (Requires that you specify a Test Table Name.)

The number of seconds a WebLogic Server instance waits between attempts when testing unused connections. (Requires that you specify a Test Table Name.) Connections that fail the test are closed and reopened to re-establish a valid physical connection. If the test fails again, the connection is closed. In the context of multi data sources, this attribute controls the frequency at which WebLogic Server checks the health of data sources it had previously marked as unhealthy. When set to 0, the feature is disabled.

The name of the database table to use when testing physical database connections. This name is required when you specify a Test Frequency and enable Test Reserved Connections. The default SQL code used to test a connection is select count(*) from TestTableName. Most database servers optimize this SQL to avoid a table scan, but it is still a good idea to set the Test Table Name to the name of a table that is known to have few rows, or even no rows. If the Test Table Name begins with SQL, then the rest of the string following that leading token will be taken as a literal SQL statement that will be used to test connections instead of the standard query.
